音乐心理学：简介

The Psychology of Music: A Very Short Introduction

本书适合任何想以轻松易懂的方式学习新知识的人。本书由专家撰写，已被翻译成45多种语言。

VERY SHORT INTRODUCTIONS are for anyone wanting a stimulating and accessible way into a new subject. They are written by experts, and have been translated into more than 45 different languages.

该系列始于1995年，如今涵盖了各学科的广泛主题。VSI图书馆目前拥有超过550册藏书，涵盖了从心理学、科学哲学到美国历史和相对论等各个领域的简明入门知识，并且还在持续扩充各个学科领域的藏书。

The series began in 1995, and now covers a wide variety of topics in every discipline. The VSI library currently contains over 550 volumes—a Very Short Introduction to everything from Psychology and Philosophy of Science to American History and Relativity—and continues to grow in every subject area.

现已推出非常简短的介绍：

虽然最终版本中的任何错误都是我自己造成的，但我仍要感谢Robert Gjerdingen、Erin Hannon、Daniel Müllensiefen、Carmel Raz和Renee Timmers，他们在早期阶段阅读了部分手稿并提供了有益的反馈。Martin Miller和Theodore Hellmuth对完整草稿提供了宝贵的评论。多年来，我在阿肯色大学“音乐与心灵”荣誉研讨会上的学生们帮助塑造了本书的内容和重点。阿肯色大学的休假使我得以完成这本书。

Although any errors in the final version are my own, I am grateful to Robert Gjerdingen, Erin Hannon, Daniel Müllensiefen, Carmel Raz, and Renee Timmers for reading portions of the manuscript in early stages and providing helpful feedback. Martin Miller and Theodore Hellmuth gave invaluable commentary on a complete draft. Students in my Honors Colloquium on Music and the Mind at the University of Arkansas over the years helped shape the book’s content and focus. A sabbatical from the University of Arkansas enabled me to finish the volume.

第一章

Chapter 1

音乐心理学的艺术与科学

The art and science of music psychology

音乐似乎是人类行为中最难解释的。世界各地的人们都在创作音乐——美国人平均每天听音乐四个小时——然而，我们通常不太擅长谈论它。这种对语言描述的抵触，导致一些哲学家认为音乐根本无法言喻。“写关于音乐的文章，”从弗兰克·扎帕到塞隆尼斯·蒙克，每个人都曾说过，“就像跳舞一样。”

Music can seem to be the human behavior that is least susceptible to explanation. People all over the world make music—the average American listens to it for four hours a day—yet we are generally not very good at talking about it. This resistance to verbal description has led some philosophers to suggest that music is simply ineffable. “Writing about music,” goes one quotation that has been attributed to everyone from Frank Zappa to Thelonious Monk, “is like dancing about architecture.”

然而，这种困难并没有阻止一代又一代人运用不同的思维模式去理解音乐。至少从毕达哥拉斯时代开始，人们就试图用数学来理解音乐结构。而音乐学家和民族音乐学家则认为音乐是人类历史和文化的产物。

Yet this difficulty has not stopped generation after generation from using diverse modes of thought to try to make sense of music. Since at least the age of Pythagoras, people have attempted to understand musical structures in terms of mathematics. Musicologists and ethnomusicologists, alternatively, think about music as a product of human history and culture.

音乐心理学提供了一个不同的框架。它将音乐视为人类思维的产物。这种视角的一大优势在于，心理学已经开发出一套巧妙的工具来内隐地研究认知过程，而无需人们明确地报告这些过程。即使一个人无法用语言描述自己的音乐体验，心理学家也可以利用神经影像或行为任务中的反应时间来推断促成这种体验的心理过程。

Music psychology offers a different framework. It views music as a product of the human mind. One powerful advantage of this perspective is that psychology has developed a clever set of tools to study cognitive processes implicitly, without requiring people to explicitly report on them. Even if a person cannot describe her musical experience in words, psychologists can use neuroimaging or reaction times on a behavioral task to infer the mental processes that made that experience possible.

音乐心理学不仅借鉴了行为研究的技术，还借鉴了被统称为认知科学的更广泛的研究方法。音乐认知科学整合了哲学、音乐理论、实验心理学、神经科学、人类学和计算机建模的思想，以解答关于音乐在人类生活中所扮演角色的种种重大（或细微）问题。例如，一位哲学家可能会构建关于音乐体验现象学的理论——描述聆听音乐的感受——而该理论或许能够启发行为测试。一位音乐理论家或许能够识别出存在于数千首歌曲中的一种模式。一位神经科学家或许能够研究人们对这种模式的反应。

The psychology of music draws not just on the techniques of behavioral research, but also on the broader collection of approaches known collectively as cognitive science. The cognitive science of music integrates ideas from philosophy, music theory, experimental psychology, neuroscience, anthropology, and computer modeling to answer the big (and little) questions about music’s role in human lives. For example, a philosopher might theorize about the phenomenology of musical experience—characterizing what it feels like to listen to music—and this theory might inspire behavioral tests. A music theorist might identify a pattern that appears in thousands of songs. A neuroscientist might investigate responses to this pattern.

尽管存在这种跨学科和协作精神，将科学方法应用于音乐研究——在典型的课程目录中，音乐是一个人文学科——却可能被指责为还原论，即怀疑一个复杂的主题被过于简化地研究。例如，许多音乐心理学研究的参与者是北美、欧洲或澳大利亚的大学本科生。在标准的音乐心理学研究中，参与者会对西方调性音乐的片段做出反应——这类音乐是用大调和小调写成的，你可能在广播中或在伦敦或芝加哥的音乐厅听到过。如果将这类研究作为普遍音乐过程的唯一证据，它们可能无法认识到文化在人类感知中所扮演的深刻角色。

Despite this interdisciplinary and collaborative spirit, applying scientific methodologies to the study of music—a humanistic topic, in a typical course catalogue—risks accusations of reductionism, the suspicion that a complex topic is being examined in overly simplistic ways. For example, participants in many studies on the psychology of music are college undergraduates in North America, Europe, or Australia. In standard music psychology studies, participants respond to excerpts of Western tonal music—the kind written in major and minor keys, that you might hear on the radio or at a concert hall in London or Chicago. If studies like these are taken as the sole evidence of universal musical processes, they might fail to acknowledge the profound role culture plays in human perception.

音乐心理学的艺术在于运用严谨的科学方法探究人类的音乐能力，同时运用精妙的人文主义方法来构建和解读科学。通过结合这些技术，音乐心理学可以解决以下问题：

The art of music psychology is to bring rigorous scientific methodologies to questions about the human musical capacity, while applying sophisticated humanistic approaches to framing and interpreting the science. By combining these techniques, music psychology can address questions such as:

•音乐意味着什么？
•有些人比其他人更擅长音乐吗？如果是，为什么？非人类动物也能拥有音乐天赋吗？
•音乐性的哪些方面源于生物学，哪些方面源于文化？
•音乐训练或经验如何影响生活的其他领域，从语言习得到记忆到健康？
•人们为什么如此热爱音乐？是什么促使他们聆听或演奏音乐？为什么不同的人喜欢不同的音乐？
•音乐如何让人们产生感受？
•音乐的功能与语言有哪些相似或不同之处？
•是什么让一些表演如此精彩，而另一些却不那么精彩？
•从婴儿期到老年，音乐技能和品味是如何在一生中习得的？
•为什么有些音乐会让人想动起来或者跳舞？

这些问题中的许多问题至少自我们有文字记载以来就一直被提出。为了理解当代人对这些问题的看法，有必要思考它们在历史进程中是如何产生的。

Many of these questions have been asked for at least as long as we have written records. To understand contemporary perspectives on them, it helps to consider how they emerged across the course of history.

关于音乐和心灵的思考史

The history of thinking about music and the mind

早在公元前六世纪，哲学家们就苦苦思索，为什么某些音符组合在一起听起来很和谐——或者说是辅音——而其他音符却听起来不和谐。传说毕达哥拉斯在一家铁匠铺里发现，敲击铁器时产生辅音音程的锤子的重量往往以简单的整数比值相互关联，例如2:1或3:2（尽管这实际上适用于振动琴弦的长度，而不适用于振动金属物体的重量）。这一发现似乎意味着，音乐感知植根于一个基本的数学真理，当时人们认为，这呼应了天体轨道所发出的“天体和谐”。物体。通过将感知到的和谐与神圣的数值关系联系起来，这一观点呈现出一种引人入胜的有序立场：或许可以通过研究纯粹的数学领域，而不是人类混乱的领域来理解音乐体验。公元前四世纪，希腊哲学家阿里斯托塞努斯采取了一种更具经验性的方法，将重点从数值关系转移到人类的感官和知觉系统，但他的研究成果在很大程度上未能获得关注。

As far back as the sixth century bce, philosophers puzzled over why certain pairs of notes seem to sound good together—or consonant—and others do not. According to legend, Pythagoras discovered in a blacksmith shop that the weights of hammers that produce consonant intervals when striking iron tend to relate to one another by simple integer ratios such as 2:1 or 3:2 (even though this actually holds true for the length of vibrating strings, not for the weights of vibrating metal objects). This discovery seemed to imply that musical perceptions were rooted in a fundamental mathematical truth, understood at the time to echo a “harmony of the spheres” emitted by the orbits of celestial objects. By linking perceived consonance with divinely ordained numeric relationships, this viewpoint presented an appealingly orderly stance: perhaps musical experience could be understood by studying the pure domain of mathematics, rather than the messy domain of human beings. When the Greek philosopher Aristoxenus, in the fourth century bce, adopted a more empirical approach, shifting the focus from numeric relationships to human sensory and perception systems, his work largely failed to gain traction.

在研究音乐时，将人为因素排除在外的诱惑并非仅限于古希腊。人们对什么音乐好听存在分歧——甚至对什么才算音乐也持有不同意见。抛开他们的观点和感知，研究主题就会简单得多。即使到了21世纪，一些音乐理论家仍然将音乐概念化为一系列抽象结构的集合，使其能够独立于创作或聆听音乐的人进行分析。音乐心理学的一项根本贡献，就是将人类音乐创作者和聆听者置于这一主题研究的核心。

The seduction of factoring people out of the equation when studying music is hardly relegated to ancient Greece. People disagree about what music sounds good—they even disagree about what counts as music. Bypassing their opinions and perceptions makes for much simpler subject matter. Even into the twenty-first century, some music theorists conceptualized music as a collection of abstract structures, amenable to analysis independent of the humans who create or listen to them. One fundamental contribution of the psychology of music is to place human music makers and listeners at the center of research questions on this topic.

十六世纪的科学革命首次给理性主义观点带来了重大裂痕。天文学家发现，月亮、太阳和行星并非绕地球运行，这打破了天体音乐的哲学基础。文森佐·伽利略指出，简单整数比与感知到的和声之间的关系，只适用于特定材料和特定情况——例如，它适用于拨动时发出悦耳声音的琴弦长度，但并不适用于同时敲响时发出悦耳声音的钟声的音量。到了1600年，弗朗西斯·培根将音乐视为人类交流情感的过程，而非神圣比例在尘世的体现。此后不久，勒内·笛卡尔开始思考这样的观点：简单的比例更令人愉悦，因为感官系统能够比复杂的比例更有效地处理它们。

The scientific revolution of the sixteenth century provided the first significant cracks in the rationalist perspective. Astronomers discovered that the moon, sun, and planets did not trace circular orbits around the earth, puncturing the philosophical underpinnings of the music of the spheres. Vincenzo Galilei showed that the relationship between simple integer ratios and perceived consonance held only for certain materials under certain circumstances—it worked for the length of strings that sounded good when plucked together, for example, but not for the volume of bells that sounded good when rung together. By 1600, Francis Bacon was talking about music in terms of the very human process of communicating emotion, rather than in terms of the earthly manifestation of divine proportions. René Descartes, shortly thereafter, was considering the notion that simple ratios were more pleasing because the sensory system could process them more effectively than complex ones.

然而，即使将焦点转移到人类听众身上，学者们也未能免受还原论的影响。一些十八、十九世纪最具影响力的音乐思想家，包括让-菲利普·拉莫和雨果·黎曼，仍然设法将音乐结构描绘成必然源于一套定律——这些定律被重新定义为感知的而非声学的。他们主张西方音高组织模式的首要地位，并将其归因于声音物理学与耳朵生理特性的相互作用。赫尔曼·亥姆霍兹1863年的论文标题概括了当时研究人员的抱负：《论音调感觉作为音乐理论的生理基础》。

Yet even in shifting the focus to human listeners, scholars were not immune to the appeal of reductionism. Some of the most influential musical thinkers of the eighteenth and nineteenth centuries, including Jean-Philippe Rameau and Hugo Riemann, still managed to depict musical structures as arising inevitably from a set of laws—laws newly cast as perceptual rather than acoustic. They asserted primacy for the Western mode of organizing pitch, attributing it to the interaction of the physics of sound and the physiological characteristics of the ear. The title of Hermann Helmholtz’s 1863 treatise encapsulates the aspirations of researchers at this time: On the Sensations of Tone as a Physiological Basis for the Theory of Music.

亥姆霍兹之后的科学家们着迷于将严谨的方法论应用于音乐这样一个无定形的话题。为了达到这种严谨性，他们进行了实验，只使用简化的人工刺激（一些当代研究人员轻蔑地称之为“嘟嘟声”），一次只呈现一个，没有任何背景信息。或许不出所料，这项研究并没有激发音乐家的想象力，也在很大程度上未能提供与更广泛的音乐实践相关的见解。

The scientists who followed Helmholtz were entranced by the notion of applying methodological rigor to a topic as amorphous as music. To achieve this rigor, they conducted experiments using simplified, artificial stimuli (disdainfully referred to by some contemporary researchers as “beeps and boops”) presented one at a time, without context. Unsurprisingly, perhaps, this research did not capture the imagination of musicians, and it largely failed to offer insights relevant to broader musical practices.

这一趋势的例外包括理查德·瓦兰切克（Richard Wallanschek）在二十世纪初的研究。他运用神经学研究了一些高阶音乐主题，例如韵律（即声音在时间中的组织方式）以及曲目说明（即音乐厅经常向古典音乐会观众提供的描述）。瓦兰切克认为，曲目说明是徒劳的，因为智力信息和情感信息是在大脑的不同通道中处理的，任何理性分析都无法影响一个人对乐曲的根本情感体验——这一假设与后续研究截然相反。更令人不安且同样错误的是，瓦兰切克还援引神经学来解释他所认为的欧洲音乐优于非洲音乐的原因。

Exceptions to this trend include work around the turn of the twentieth century by Richard Wallanschek, who used neurology to examine high-level musical topics such as meter—the organization of sounds in time—and program notes, the descriptions that concert halls often provide to classical concertgoers. Wallanschek argued that program notes were a waste of effort because intellectual information and emotional information were processed in different channels of the brain, and no amount of rational analysis could affect a person’s fundamentally emotional experience of a piece—a supposition roundly contradicted by subsequent research. More troublingly and equally falsely, Wallanschek also appealed to neurology to elucidate what he viewed as the superiority of European to African music.

二十世纪早期研究中的两种截然相反的趋势——一方面严谨地研究与音乐关系不大的低级现象，另一方面则研究缺乏文化意识的高级现象——构成了一系列双重危险，而音乐心理学至今仍在努力规避这些危险。那些回避日常音乐的复杂性，转而使用精心控制的合成刺激的研究，可能无法揭示现实世界的音乐行为；而那些针对实际音乐体验的研究——如果没有以人文主义的精妙之处进行恰当的框架和解读——则可能会误导性地将科学的标签赋予文化错误假设。

These two opposing trends in early-twentieth-century research—toward rigorously investigating low-level phenomena with little musical relevance, on the one hand, and investigating high-level phenomena with little cultural awareness, on the other—establish a set of twin dangers around which the psychology of music still aims to navigate today. Studies that avoid the complexities of everyday music and instead use carefully controlled, synthetic stimuli can fail to shed light on real-world musical behaviors, but studies that target actual musical experiences—if not appropriately framed and interpreted with humanistic sophistication—can seem misleadingly to confer the stamp of science on cultural misassumptions.

二十世纪初心理学家卡尔·西肖尔（Carl Seashore）的著作——尽管其创造力和巨大影响力——却体现了这两种危险。西肖尔设计了一些测试来评估人们的音乐潜力。这些测试包括聆听两个音调并判断哪个音调更高，或者聆听三个咔嗒声并判断第一对和第二对音调之间是否有更长的时间间隔。1922年，爱荷华州得梅因市公立学校所有五年级和六年级的学生都参加了这些测试，《科学美国人》称赞其“近乎完美”。西肖尔表达了一种乐观的愿景，认为他的测试或许可以让具有音乐潜能的农场男孩接受乐器训练，并有机会接触更广阔的音乐世界。但这些测试的实施却带有一个更黑暗、更挑剔的目的——《科学美国人》的文章宣称这些测试具有“巨大的经济意义”，因为“大量的资金被浪费在美国那些永远无法成为音乐家的孩子身上”。换句话说，如果一个孩子没有通过考试，为什么要浪费时间和金钱去强迫一个音乐白痴表演呢？

The early-twentieth-century work of psychologist Carl Seashore—despite its creativity and substantial influence—exemplifies both these dangers. Seashore devised tests to assess people’s individual musical potential. These tests involved such tasks as listening to two tones and judging which was higher or listening to three clicks and deciding whether a longer span of time separated the first or second pair. They were administered in 1922 to all children in the fifth and sixth grades in the Des Moines, Iowa, public schools, and praised by Scientific American as “well-nigh flawless.” Seashore articulated an optimistic vision, in which his tests might allow farm boys with latent musical talent to receive training on an instrument and the chance to connect to a broader musical world. But the tests were implemented with a darker, winnowing purpose—the Scientific American article touts the “enormous economic importance” of the tests, owing to “the amount of money which is wasted upon children in the United States who can never become musicians.” If a child did not pass, in other words, why waste time and money trying to squeeze performances out of a musical dunce?

1.卡尔·西肖尔发明了声调测量仪，用于记录和测量歌唱音调的声学特性，这是他为识别“音乐天赋”而设计的一系列测试的一部分。

1. Carl Seashore devised the tonoscope to record and measure the acoustic characteristics of sung pitches, one component of his battery of tests designed to identify “musical talent.”

Seashore 的项目使用了简化的刺激物，例如音调和咔哒声，单独呈现，并将对这些刺激物的反应解读为高水平文化现象音乐天赋的指标。科学的社会力量赋予了这项研究权威性。这项技术能够有力地支持一个原本模糊且鲜少被检验的假设——在这个例子中，音乐天赋是与生俱来的，并且在人群中分布不均。它可以被用来指导现实世界中关于哪些人应该接受音乐教育等问题的决策。

Seashore’s project used simplified stimuli like tones and clicks, presented in isolation, and interpreted responses to them as indicative of a high-level cultural phenomenon musical aptitude. The societal power of science gave the study the authoritative force to support an otherwise hazy and little-examined assumption—in this case, the assumption that musical aptitude is innate and unevenly distributed among the population. It could then be used to guide real-world decisions on questions such as who should have access to music education.

音乐心理学的研究通常依赖于采用一个高层次的、有趣的概念（例如，音乐天赋、音乐记忆或情绪反应），并在一个被称为操作化的过程中，识别出一种可以用来代表该概念的可测量行为。这就是艺术所在。在诸如音乐性以及具体的可测量行为（例如音高辨别任务中的表现）需要严谨的解读逻辑，而且，就像《海岸》一样，有时可能会出错。在音乐心理学史上的所有现象中，或许没有哪个比莫扎特效应更能体现解读失误的危险了。

Work in the psychology of music typically depends on taking a high-level, interesting concept (for example, musical aptitude, or musical memory, or emotional response) and—in a process referred to as operationalizing—identifying a measurable behavior that can be taken to represent it. Therein lies the art. Slipping back and forth between broad humanistic concepts such as musicality and concrete measurable behaviors, such as performance on a pitch discrimination task, requires careful interpretive logic, and, as with Seashore, it can sometimes go wrong. Of all the phenomena in the history of the psychology of music, perhaps none better exemplifies the danger of interpretive slippage than the notion of the Mozart effect.

这始于1993年的一项研究。在这项研究中，大学生被要求听十分钟莫扎特奏鸣曲，或听十分钟放松指导，或静坐十分钟，然后再进行空间推理任务。当学生们在听完莫扎特音乐后的10到15分钟内完成任务时，他们的空间推理得分比放松或静坐时更高。

It started with a 1993 study in which college students either listened to ten minutes of a sonata by Mozart, or listened to ten minutes of relaxation instructions, or sat in silence for ten minutes before performing a spatial reasoning task. When the students performed the task within ten to fifteen minutes after listening to Mozart, their spatial reasoning scores were higher than if they had relaxed or sat in silence.

在家长们对孩子智力担忧、西方经典艺术家和音乐家拥有特殊天赋的普遍观念的背景下，这项研究的设计细节被遗忘了。在公众的心目中，科学刚刚证明了莫扎特能让孩子更聪明——尽管这项研究并没有使用儿童，也没有测量一般智力，而且正如作者们谨慎指出的那样，听莫扎特音乐的效果在15分钟后就消失了。

In a climate of parental anxiety about children’s intelligence and widespread notions that artists and musicians in the Western canon possessed special genius, the details of the study’s design got lost. In the mind of the general public, science had just proved that Mozart made children smarter—despite that the study had not used children and had not measured general intelligence, and, as the authors carefully noted, that the effect of listening to Mozart disappeared after fifteen minutes.

乔治亚州州长渴望获得这些益处，于1998年安排向该州所有新生儿的父母发放古典音乐CD，佛罗里达州立法机构也提议要求州政府资助的日托中心每天为其所照顾的孩子播放古典音乐。这些出于好意的举措却基于解读偏差，他们用空间推理任务的短期进步来代表一般智力，用大学生来代表幼儿。这怎么可能呢？

Eager to reap these benefits, the governor of Georgia in 1998 arranged for classical music CDs to be distributed to all parents of newborns in the state, and the Florida legislature proposed that state-funded day-care centers be required to play classical music for their charges every day. These well-intentioned initiatives were based on interpretive slippage, where short-term improvements on a spatial reasoning task were taken to represent general intelligence and where college students were taken to represent toddlers. How could this happen?

首先，为了强调科学发现的相关性，媒体有时会以一种方式概括研究结果，激发更多兴趣，但并未谨慎地承认解读的局限性。另一方面，人们倾向于根据现有的文化叙事来理解新发现。早在莫扎特研究之前，一种流行的文化叙事就概括了古典音乐，尤其是其最著名的作曲家，在智力上具有优越性。在这种框架下，人们很容易相信被动接触莫扎特的音乐可能会产生令人高尚的效果。

For one thing, in an effort to highlight the relevance of scientific findings, the media sometimes generalize results in a way that encourages more interest but does not carefully acknowledge interpretive limits. For another, people tend to understand new findings in terms of existing cultural narratives. Well before the Mozart study, a prevalent cultural narrative outlined the supposed intellectual superiority of classical music, in general, and its most renowned composers, in particular. Within this framework, it was easy to believe that passive exposure to Mozart’s music might have ennobling effects.

然而，从科学的角度来看，最初的研究无法证明莫扎特或古典音乐与其他作曲家和其他音乐传统相比具有什么比较效果，因为比较条件包括静坐或听放松指示。只有通过比较听莫扎特的音乐与听贝多芬、拉维·香卡或披头士的音乐的效果，才能确定这种特定音乐（而不是一般音乐）的任何特殊益处。事实上，当最终进行此类研究时，很明显，任何音乐都可以带来同样的短期益处，只要它是适度乐观和引人入胜的。认知表现的提高可以归因于唤醒，而不是莫扎特。在跑步机上快步走也会产生同样的好处。当人们进入受到刺激和注意力集中的状态时，他们在测试中的表现会更好。

From a scientific standpoint, however, the original study could not demonstrate anything about the comparative efficacy of Mozart or classical music compared to other composers and other traditions because the comparison conditions involved sitting in silence or listening to relaxation instructions. Only by comparing the effect of listening to Mozart with the effect of listening to Beethoven or Ravi Shankar or the Beatles could any special benefit of this particular music, rather than of music in general, be established. In fact, when studies like these were eventually run, it became clear that the same short-term benefit could be achieved by any music, so long as it was moderately upbeat and engaging. The boost in cognitive performance could be attributed to arousal, not to Mozart. Walking briskly on a treadmill produces the same benefit. When people are brought into a stimulated and focused state they perform better on tests.

然而，尽管有这些后续发现，尽管未能重复最初的研究，一排排的塑料婴儿玩具上仍然摆放着按下后会播放莫扎特曲调的按钮。事实上，“小莫扎特”是一个注册商标。重塑主流文化叙事可能需要科学家、记者和音乐家数十年的讨论、写作和演奏。要加快社会普遍理解的速度，需要更广泛地参与在数据和解释之间来回切换的解释逻辑。音乐心理学在推进这种参与方面具有独特的优势，因为该领域的学者们已经参与了某种形式的自20世纪80年代初以来，翻译界一直致力于人文学科与科学之间的交流。通过学习如何跨越学科界限进行交流，他们为与广大音乐创作者和听众更好地沟通铺平了道路。

Yet despite these subsequent findings, and despite failures to replicate the original study, aisles and aisles of plastic baby toys still feature buttons that deploy Mozart tunes when pressed. Baby Mozart, in fact, is a trademarked brand. It can take decades of scientists and journalists and musicians talking and writing and playing to reshape dominant cultural narratives. Increasing the pace of general societal understanding would require broader engagement with the interpretive logic used to move back and forth between data and interpretation. The psychology of music is uniquely well poised to advance this engagement because scholars in this area have already been participating in a form of translation since the early 1980s: between the humanities and the sciences. By learning how to communicate across disciplinary boundaries, they have paved the way for better communication with the music-making and music-listening public at large.

当代音乐与心灵的探讨

Contemporary approaches to music and the mind

二十世纪初，实验心理学被研究行为的潜力所震撼。受巴甫洛夫和他的唾液狗的启发，哈佛大学心理学家BF·斯金纳试图将思维视为一个黑匣子，使其无法进行科学研究，而是通过严格测量人类的行为来理解人类。但到了20世纪50年代，计算机科学和神经科学这两个学科开始并行发展。它们引入了一套方法，用于探究执行计算的黑匣子内部，包括计算机和大脑。随着人们努力解答关于人类思维的重大问题，一种连接心理学、计算机科学、人类学、语言学和神经科学的新范式应运而生，被称为认知科学。

In the early twentieth century, experimental psychology was dazzled by the potential of studying behavior. Inspired by Pavlov and his salivating dogs, Harvard psychologist B. F. Skinner sought to bracket off the mind as a black box, not amenable to scientific study, and understand humans instead by rigorously measuring their behavior. But by the 1950s, the disciplines of computer science and neuroscience had begun to emerge in parallel. They introduced a set of methods for peering inside black boxes that perform computations, both computers and brains. As people strived to answer big questions about human thought, a new paradigm linking psychology, computer science, anthropology, linguistics, and neuroscience came to be known as cognitive science.

将这些领域联系在一起的一大问题是人类语言的本质。语言是如何运作的？婴儿如何在出生后的最初几年里如此迅速地学习语言？从事人类语言能力研究的人们将音乐视为一个有趣的比较案例。与语言一样，音乐也由单个声音元素的复杂模式构成。与语言一样，音乐在不同人类文化中也存在差异。与语言一样，音乐也随着时间的流逝而动态地发生，并且能够被记录下来。而且，可以说，与语言一样，音乐似乎是人类独有的。

One of the big questions that united these fields concerned the nature of human language. How does it work and how do babies learn it so quickly over their first few years of life? People engaged in research about the human capacity for language came to view music as an interesting comparison case. Like language, music consists of the complex patterning of individual sound elements. Like language, music varies across human cultures. Like language, music occurs dynamically in time, and it is capable of being notated. And arguably, like language, music seems to be unique to humans.

当代音乐心理学的研究很大程度上得益于语言心理学，并吸收了其许多理论和方法。各种方法逐渐构成了这一新兴研究领域的核心：计算机建模、语料库研究、行为心理学研究、认知神经科学方法、临床方法和定性方法。

Contemporary work in the psychology of music owes much to the psychology of language, adopting many of its theories and methods. Various approaches have come to form the core of this new field of study: computer modeling, corpus studies, behavioral research, cognitive neuroscience methods, clinical approaches, and qualitative approaches.

计算机建模

Computer modeling

了解人类如何执行任务的一种方法是编写程序让计算机执行该任务。例如，人类如何创作音乐？在 20 世纪 80 年代，研究人员尝试让计算机模仿巴赫和莫扎特等作曲家的风格创作音乐，以此来解决这个问题。谷歌最近开展的一个名为Magenta的项目则设定了一个更加宏伟的目标：尝试利用机器学习的力量，从计算机中获取引人入胜的原创音乐。这类项目依赖于这样一种理念：大脑就像计算机一样，可以被有效地概念化为一台信息处理机器。通过识别计算机创作动人音乐所必须使用的策略，这些努力为大脑如何完成同样的任务提供了初步假设。

One way to find out how a human might perform a task is to program a computer to do it. How do people compose music, for example? In the 1980s, researchers tackled this question by trying to get a computer to write music in the style of composers such as Bach and Mozart. A recent project at Google titled Magenta has taken on an even more ambitious goal: attempting to harness the power of machine learning to elicit compelling original music from computers. These kinds of projects rely on the notion that the brain, like a computer, can be productively conceptualized as an information-processing machine. By identifying the strategies a computer must use to produce engaging music, these endeavors provide initial hypotheses for how the brain might accomplish the same task.

科学家们还利用计算机建模来解决诸如以下问题：人们在听音乐时如何决定在哪个节拍上拍手？表演者如何做出富有表现力的决定，例如哪些音符应该停留、哪些音符应该缩短、哪些音符应该演奏得更响亮，哪些音符应该在微妙的延迟后引入？听众如何判断在一首特定的乐曲中哪些音符听起来紧张，哪些音符听起来放松？这些问题可能很难解决。编写计算机程序来模拟所讨论主题的某些方面——无论该模型最终被证明有多么不充分——都可以帮助建立一个易于理解的起点。例如，在思考人们如何能够如此轻松地跟着节拍打拍子时，可以形成一个初步假设：只要音乐的响度超过某个阈值，人们就会打拍子。通过用这种策略对计算机进行编程，并观察它在各种歌曲中打拍子或误打拍子的方式，可以揭示该理论的局限性。在模型中添加新的策略——当最低音符低于某个限度时打拍子或者构建一个有利于按规律间隔敲击的函数——可以完善关于人类如何追踪音乐节拍的现有理论。行为研究人员可以开展研究，系统地改变音乐示例中的响度和音高，并追踪人们在这些片段中敲击方式的变化。通过这种方式，计算机建模和实验心理学可以携手推进对人类音乐处理方式的理解。

Scientists have also harnessed computer modeling to address questions such as: How do people decide which beats to clap on when they’re listening to music? How do performers make expressive decisions, such as which notes to linger on, which to shorten, which to play louder, and which to introduce after a subtle delay? How do listeners decide which notes sound tense and which sound relaxed in a particular piece? These questions can be challenging to tackle. Programming a computer to model some aspect of the topic under consideration—no matter how inadequate the model might ultimately prove—can help establish a tractable place to start. For example, in thinking about how people can tap along to the beat so easily, one could form an initial hypothesis that they simply tap whenever the loudness of the music exceeds a certain threshold. By programming a computer with this strategy and observing the way it taps or mis-taps to various songs, the limitations of this theory can be exposed. Adding new strategies to the model—tapping when the lowest note dips below a certain limit or building in a function that favors tapping across regularly spaced intervals—can refine existing theories about how humans track the musical beat. Behavioral researchers can then set up studies that systematically vary the loudness and pitch height in musical examples and track the changes in how people tap to these excerpts. In this way, computer modeling and experimental psychology can partner to advance the understanding of human musical processing.

语料库研究

Corpus studies

数字化程度的提高使得从海量数据中识别模式成为可能，而这些数据量庞大，手工调查难以做到。现在，只需几分钟就能统计出海顿弦乐四重奏或日本十九世纪流行歌曲中B、C或F调的数量，并比较它们的分布。同样，统计数十张舒伯特歌曲录音中歌手和钢琴家对时间和响度的所有调整也非常简单。

Increased digitization has made it possible to identify patterns in huge sets of data that are too large to investigate by hand. It now takes mere minutes to count the number of Bs or Cs or F-sharps in the Haydn string quartets, or in Japanese nineteenth-century popular songs, and to compare these distributions. It is similarly straightforward to tally all the timing and loudness modifications made by singers and pianists in dozens of recordings of a particular Schubert song.

乐谱和录音表演所代表的数据类型非常广泛，这使得研究人员能够提出一些音乐心理学的基本问题。例如，人们经常在口语乐句结束时放慢语速。通过测量录音表演中的时间模式，研究人员发现人们在乐句结束时也会放慢语速，从而揭示了更多关于语言和音乐之间关系的信息。此外，通过观察这些时间模式如何随时间和地点的变化而变化，语料库研究可以揭示这些模式在多大程度上受到文化而非生物学的影响。最重要的是，这些研究只需一台计算机和一些编程知识即可完成——无需招募参与者或建立实验室。然而，许多语料库研究依赖于以特殊方式编码乐谱或音频以使其易于查询的数据库——这些数据库的开发通常是这类工作中最耗费资源的部分。选择哪些方面数据库中呈现的音乐会影响从研究音乐中可以获得什么样的见解。

The kind of data represented by notated music and recorded performance is extensive, and allows researchers to ask questions fundamental to music psychology. For example, people often slow down at the end of spoken phrases. By measuring timing patterns in recorded performances, researchers discovered that people also slow down at the end of musical phrases, revealing more about the relationship between language and music. Moreover, by looking at how these timing patterns vary as a function of time and place, corpus studies can shed light on the degree to which such patterns are influenced by culture rather than by biology. Best of all, these studies can be done with a computer and a little programming knowledge—there is no need to recruit participants or set up a lab. Many corpus studies, however, depend on databases that encode musical notation or audio in special ways to make them easy to query—the development of these databases is often the most resource-intensive part of this kind of work. Choices about what aspects of the music get represented in the database influence what kinds of insight can be gained from studying it.

行为研究

Behavioral research

音乐心理学中的许多问题只有在受控条件下研究行为才能得到解答。在这里，行为可以指人做出的任何可测量的反应——执行任务时的反应时间、脚尖轻敲，或对特定问题的回答。例如，研究人员可能想知道记忆某些类型的旋律模式是否更容易。理想情况下，他们想知道这种记忆提升是否适用于所有人，但由于无法测试所有人，他们选择随机样本，并使用统计数据来确定他们的发现是否可能推广到更大的群体。然而，许多音乐心理学研究以西方大学的本科生作为参与者——这很难说是世界上随机抽取的人群样本。这些研究与其说是阐明所有人类如何聆听音乐，不如说是考察具有特定文化背景的人如何聆听音乐。

Many questions in the psychology of music are answerable only by studying behavior under controlled conditions. Behavior, in this context, can designate any kind of measurable response made by a person—reaction time when performing a task, or toe taps, or answers to particular questions. For example, researchers might want to know whether it is easier to remember certain kinds of melodic patterns. Ideally, they would like to know whether this memory boost extends to all people, but since it is not feasible to test everyone, they select a random sample and use statistics to determine whether their findings are likely to generalize to the larger population. But many studies in music psychology use undergraduates at universities in the West as participants—hardly a random sample of people in the world. Rather than illuminating how all humans hear music these studies might more aptly be thought to examine how humans with a particular cultural background do.

在实验过程中，参与者可能会被逐一引导至实验室的隔音室，并通过耳机播放由不同音乐模式组成的刺激。然后，他们可能会听到成对的模式，并被询问在实验的第一部分听到了哪种模式。如果他们对某一特定类型的模式给出了更准确的回答，统计工具可以评估这种差异是反映了更大群体中存在的真实效应（人们确实更容易记住这种模式），还是偶然发生的（实际上，两种模式都同样容易记住，但随机误差导致了差异的出现）。

During an experimental session, participants may be ushered one at a time into a soundproof booth in a laboratory and played stimuli consisting of different musical patterns over headphones. Then, they may be played pairs of patterns and asked which they heard in the first part of the experiment. If they provide more correct responses for a particular type of pattern, statistical tools can assess the chances that this difference reflects a real effect present in the larger population (people really remember this pattern more easily) or occurred by chance (it is actually equally easy to remember both patterns, but random error led to the appearance of a difference).

这类研究的一个重要挑战是生态效度——人们在实验室环境中理解简化刺激的认知过程在多大程度上音乐研究如何体现出人们理解现实世界中丰富的、社会性的音乐体验的过程？虽然这一挑战在社会科学的许多研究中都存在，但它对于研究音乐等复杂的文化行为尤为重要。

One important challenge for this type of research is ecological validity—to what extent are the cognitive processes people use to make sense of simplified stimuli in a laboratory environment representative of the processes they use to make sense of rich, socially embedded musical experiences in the real world? Although this challenge characterizes much work in the social sciences, it is particularly relevant to research that tackles a complex cultural behavior like music.

一些宏大的人文问题常常推动着音乐心理学的研究：是什么驱使着人们享受音乐？为什么人类具有音乐天赋？然而，实验设计者必须找到将这些概念操作化的方法——以离散且易于处理的方式测试和测量这些概念的方法。这是大量艺术首次进入科学的契机。以误导性的方式操作化重要概念的实验，可能会导致科学乍一看很可靠，但最终却无法令人满意。例如，卡尔·西肖尔 (Carl Seashore) 想要了解儿童的音乐潜力，但他使用音调辨别任务的表现等指标来将其操作化。让儿童辨别出两个相差 1/108 个音调的音符中哪个音更高，这虽然可以提供很好的定量数据，但这似乎并不是衡量音乐潜力的有用方法。

Big, humanistic questions often motivate research in the psychology of music: What drives musical enjoyment? Why are humans musical? Yet people designing experiments must identify ways to operationalize these concepts—ways to test and measure them discretely and tractably. This is the first juncture at which a substantial amount of art enters into the science. Experiments that operationalize important concepts in misleading ways can result in science that might look robust at first glance but ultimately prove unsatisfactory. Carl Seashore, for example, wanted to understand the musical potential of children, but he operationalized it using things like performance on a tone discrimination task. Getting children to identify which of two notes 1/108th of a tone apart is higher makes for good quantitative data but hardly seems like a useful measure of musical potential.

图 2描绘了行为研究在定量和定性推理之间移动的方式。首先，必须从可测量变量的相互作用的角度重新表述大问题——这个过程需要丰富的人文洞察力。一旦完成了这种汇集，就可以应用成熟的方法来收集数据、测量结果并确定它们与实验参与者所构成样本的更大群体之间的可能关系。所有这些都可以概念化为发生在图 2中心的方框内。但在研究的最后阶段，必须对这些发现进行解释，并将其与最初激发研究的更大问题联系起来。这里再次体现了洞察力的需要，以及误传的危险——例如，将一项针对大学生的研究解释为莫扎特可以提高婴儿长期智力的证据。

Figure 2 depicts the way behavioral research moves between quantitative and qualitative reasoning. First, big questions must be restated in terms of the interaction of measurable variables—a process that requires substantial humanistic insight. Once this funneling has been accomplished, well-established methods can be applied to collect data, measure the results, and specify their likely relationship to the larger population of whom the experiment’s participants form a sample. All of this can be conceptualized as taking place within the box at the center of Figure 2. But in the final stage of research, these findings must be interpreted and connected to the larger questions that motivated the study in the first place. Here again lies the need for insight, and the danger for misrepresentation—for example interpreting a study of college students as evidence that Mozart increases the long-term intelligence of babies.

2.研究人员从激励性问题入手，这些问题通常涉及情绪或记忆等宏大主题。他们会设计具体的方法，从行为上测量这些现象。一旦记录了这些任务的表现，他们就必须解释这些具体发现与更广泛的研究主题之间的关系。尤其是在研究音乐等文化现象时，他们必须仔细考虑所测量的行为是否足以替代更广泛的主题。

2. Researchers start with motivating questions, often concerning big topics such as emotion or memory. They devise concrete ways of measuring these phenomena behaviorally. Once performance on these tasks has been recorded, they must interpret how the specific findings relate to the broader topic of interest. Especially in the case of research on a cultural phenomenon like music, they must pay careful attention to whether the measured behavior serves as an adequate proxy for the broader topic.

仅凭一项研究，几乎不可能以单一方式将情感体验或音乐潜能等宏大概念令人满意地转化为可测量的变量。音乐心理学的进展是循序渐进地贯穿数十个项目的。通常，一个实验的局限性可以通过运行新的实验来克服，新的实验可以控制潜在的混淆因素（另一个可能影响结果的变量），或者以一种新的、更有效的方式将主题操作化。这种跨多个研究的进展潜力有助于推动音乐心理学作为一个领域获得越来越深刻的洞察，即使每一项单独的研究可能只贡献有限的视角。

It is almost impossible to satisfactorily operationalize big concepts like emotional experience or musical potential into measurable variables in just one way within just one study. Progress in the psychology of music occurs incrementally across dozens and dozens of projects. Often, limitations in one experiment can be addressed by running a new experiment that controls for a potential confound (another variable that might have been influencing the results) or operationalizes the topic in a new and more powerful way. This potential for progress across multiple studies helps the psychology of music drive toward deeper and deeper insight as a field, even though each individual study might contribute only a limited view.

由于人们通常无法准确记录自己的认知过程，而且他们通常缺乏直接接触构成其信念、经历和行为的认知过程的途径，因此心理学家开发了许多巧妙的方法来隐性地测量这些认知过程，而无需依赖直接提问。例如，心理学家可以测量他们的反应时间、呼吸频率或其他一些间接的情绪指标，而不是询问参与者对某事的感受。反应。这种识别内隐测量的能力使实验心理学成为理解音乐体验的一种特别有用的方法。由于人们通常不习惯或无法用言语描述他们的音乐体验，有时甚至将其描述为根本无法言喻或无法用语言描述的体验，因此，无需言语描述即可进行的内隐方法在阐明音乐体验方面具有特殊的力量。

Because people are often unreliable reporters of their cognitive processes, and because they generally lack direct access to the cognitive processes that underlie their beliefs, experiences, and actions, psychologists have developed a host of clever ways of measuring them implicitly, without relying on direct questions. For example, instead of asking participants how they feel about something, psychologists might measure their reaction time, or respiration rate, or some other indirect indicator of emotional response. This capacity for identifying implicit measures makes experimental psychology an especially useful approach for understanding musical experience. Because people are often unaccustomed or unable to report verbally on their musical experiences, sometimes going so far as to characterize them as fundamentally ineffable or incapable of being described in words, implicit methods that bypass the need for verbal report have special power to illuminate musical experience.

认知神经科学方法

Cognitive neuroscience methods

除了从行为推断认知加工过程的某些方面外，21世纪的研究人员还可以使用各种方法通过研究大脑来推断认知加工过程。音乐心理学中最常用的认知神经科学技术是脑电图（EEG）和功能磁共振成像（fMRI）。

In addition to inferring aspects of cognitive processing from behavior, researchers in the twenty-first century can use a variety of methods to infer cognitive processing from studying the brain. The cognitive neuroscience techniques used most commonly in the psychology of music are EEG and fMRI.

脑电图 (EEG) 依靠放置在头皮上的电极来测量电位变化，从而推断神经活动。EEG 可以精确测量神经反应的时间进程。由于音乐是在时间中发生的，研究人员通常想知道一个特定音符相对于另一个特定音符可能引发什么样的反应，因此 EEG 精确定位特定时刻反应的能力尤为重要。然而，它的空间分辨率较差。大脑三维结构内复杂的神经活动模式叠加在一起，影响放置在头皮上的特定电极的记录，因此很难确定每个成分的确切来源位置。

EEG relies on electrodes placed along the scalp to measure changes in electrical potential, from which neural activity can be inferred. EEG allows the time-course of neural response to be precisely measured. Since music takes place in time, and researchers often want to know what kind of response one particular note might elicit in contrast to another particular note, EEG’s capacity to pinpoint responses to individual moments is particularly useful. Its spatial resolution, however, is poor. Complex patterns of neural activity within the three-dimensional structure of the brain sum to influence the recordings of particular electrodes placed on the scalp, making it difficult to identify the exact place where each component originated.

然而，包括 fMRI 在内的神经影像学技术，能够提供关于神经活动位置的极佳证据。但其弊端在于时间分辨率较差，这使得它对于追踪音乐过程中感知的逐刻变化不太有用。神经影像学技术能够生成我们熟悉的大脑图像，其中的活动区域由彩色斑点。借助功能磁共振成像 (fMRI)，研究人员可以提出以下问题：音乐和语音是否依赖于相同的神经回路？人们在被动聆听音乐时是否会激活运动区域？接受过音乐训练的人与未接受过音乐训练的人处理语音的方式是否不同？

Neuroimaging, however, including fMRI, can provide excellent evidence about the location of neural activity. The trade-off involves poorer temporal resolution, making it less useful for tracking the moment-by-moment perceptual changes as the music progresses. Neuroimaging produces those familiar pictures of the brain within which areas of activity are represented by colorful blotches. With fMRI, researchers can ask questions like: Do music and speech rely on the same neural circuitry? Do people engage motor regions when they listen passively to music? Do people with musical training process speech differently than people without it?

3.脑电图帽将电极固定在头皮上，使研究人员能够测量电位变化。脑电图对于推断无法用言语描述自身经历的人的神经活动尤其有用，比如这名五个月大的婴儿。

3. EEG caps affix electrodes to the scalp, allowing researchers to measure changes in electrical potential. EEG can be especially useful for inferring neural activity in people who cannot report verbally on their experience, such as this five-month-old infant.

与其他方法相比，神经科学方法对公众想象力的影响更大。研究表明，当人们获得不同质量的心理学解释时，他们能够准确地评估其逻辑性——将好的论点识别为好的，将坏的论点识别为坏的——直到添加暗示大脑区域的括号（例如，“如杏仁核活动所示”）。当糟糕的论点提及神经科学时，人们倾向于认为该论点在逻辑上更合理。

Neuroscientific approaches influence the public imagination disproportionately in comparison to other approaches. Studies have shown that people, when provided psychological explanations of varying quality, were able to accurately rate the logic—identifying good arguments as good and bad arguments as bad—until parentheticals alluding to brain regions were added (for example, “as shown by activity in the amygdala”). When bad arguments included allusions to neuroscience, people tended to think the argument was more logically sound.

神经影像学的说服力使其成为一种重要的工具，但也增加了对研究假设产生误解和过度自信的可能性。尤其重要的是，要严格评估音乐认知神经科学研究的基础理论，以确保它们能够阐明而非歪曲音乐丰富的文化实践。

Neuroimaging’s persuasive power makes it an important tool, but also raises the possibility of misinterpretation and overconfidence in the research’s assumptions. It is especially important to rigorously evaluate the theory underlying cognitive neuroscience studies of music to ensure that they illuminate rather than misrepresent the rich cultural practice of music.

临床方法

Clinical approaches

有时，研究人类音乐处理能力受损时哪些方面出了问题，是了解其最简单的方法。例如，临床研究可以观察脑损伤患者，并将受损区域与观察到的音乐缺陷联系起来，从而得出结论，了解哪些能力取决于哪些大脑区域。一些临床研究专注于特定疾病，例如威廉姆斯综合征（一种发育障碍性疾病），这些疾病通常与相对较高的音乐素养水平相关。

Sometimes it is easiest to learn about human musical processing by studying what goes awry when it is impaired. Clinical studies can look at people with brain damage, for example, and link the injured areas with observed musical deficits to draw conclusions about what capacities depend on what brain regions. Some clinical studies focus on particular conditions, such as the developmental disorder Williams syndrome, that are typically associated with relatively high degrees of musicality.

临床方法也可以将音乐作为一种干预手段进行研究，探究演奏、学习或聆听音乐如何改善健康，或某种特定的歌唱疗法如何帮助失语症患者（中风或其他脑损伤后导致的语言障碍）重新学习说话。纪录片《Alive Inside》（2014）记录了音乐对痴呆症患者的影响。临床研究采用严谨的方法来揭示音乐最有效的治疗用途。

Clinical approaches can also study music as an intervention, examining the ways that playing, studying, or listening to music can improve health, or the way a particular variety of singing therapy can assist people with aphasia (impaired language following stroke or other brain injury) in learning to speak again. Documentary films such as Alive Inside (2014) chronicle the impact music can have on patients with dementia. Clinical research applies rigorous methods to uncovering the most effective therapeutic uses of music.

定性方法

Qualitative approaches

音乐处理的一些方面最好通过访谈、调查和观察等定性研究来研究。例如，麻省理工学院的音乐教授珍妮·班伯格（Jeanne Bamberger）通过给孩子们蒙特梭利铃铛，并让他们画出他们所听到和演奏的内容，为当代音乐发展心理学的研究奠定了基础。通过翻阅通过数十份回复，她能够推断出不同年龄段的儿童倾向于拥有的音乐表征类型。瑞典心理学家阿尔夫·加布里埃尔森（Alf Gabrielsson）采访了数百人，了解他们的音乐巅峰体验——他们最强烈、最激动人心的音乐时刻——并梳理其中的共性。

Some aspects of musical processing are best studied qualitatively, with interviews and surveys and observation. MIT music professor Jeanne Bamberger, for example, laid the foundation for contemporary work in the developmental psychology of music by giving children Montessori bells and asking them to draw representations of what they heard and played. By paging through dozens and dozens of responses, she was able to make inferences about the kinds of musical representation children tended to possess at different ages. Swedish psychologist Alf Gabrielsson interviewed hundreds of people about their peak experiences of music—their most intense and emotional musical moments—and combed through them to identify commonalities.

这种密切的观察可以产生理论和假设，供后续研究进行定量研究。由于音乐行为极其复杂多样，可能需要多年的定性研究才能实现任何定量方法。

This kind of close observation can yield theories and hypotheses that subsequent studies can investigate quantitatively. Because musical behaviors are so complex and so various, they can require years of qualitative study before any quantitative approach is possible.

第二章

Chapter 2

音乐的生物学起源

The biological origins of music

数万年前的考古记录中就出现了用动物骨骼制成、带有穿孔指孔的笛子。声乐和器乐存在于所有已知的人类文化中。音乐的悠久历史和普遍性似乎表明其起源于生物学。但世界各地音乐实践的多样性似乎反而表明其起源于文化。这种多样性延伸到了音乐构成的概念本身：黑脚族的术语“ saapup”涵盖了歌唱、舞蹈和仪式，并没有为纯粹的声学音乐开辟出一个独立的概念。其他语言，包括泰语和梵语，有一个词同时表示音乐和舞蹈，而其他一些语言则有分别表示歌唱和器乐的词，但没有一个将它们融合在一起的总体类别。作为探讨音乐与生物学之争的切入点，识别哪些音乐特征往往在不同文化中共享将大有裨益。一个引人入胜且自相矛盾的共同特征是，人们倾向于将自己的音乐体系视为“自然的”，而非文化建构的。

Flutes made of animal bones with perforated finger holes appear in the archaeological record tens of thousands of years ago. Vocal and instrumental music exists in all known human cultures. Music’s age and ubiquity seem to argue that its origins are biological. But the diversity of musical practices around the world seems to argue instead that its origins are cultural. This diversity extends to the very notion of what constitutes music: the Blackfoot term saapup encompasses singing, dancing, and ceremony, without carving out a separate concept for the purely acoustic. Other languages, including Thai and Sanskrit, have a single word that denotes both music and dance, while still others have separate words for singing and instrumental music but no overarching category that combines them. As an entry point to the debate about music and biology, it can be useful to identify what musical features tend to be shared across cultures. One fascinating—and paradoxical—shared characteristic is a tendency for people to view their own musical system as “natural” rather than culturally constructed.

在西方，人们将“协和音”（即认为某些音符组合在一起听起来很和谐）归因于诸如数学或内耳物理学之类的宇宙力量。然而，齐玛内人，一个与世隔绝、几乎不受西方文化影响的亚马逊社会，却将协和音和不协和音视为同等重要的。令人愉悦。尽管有证据表明文化在塑造人们对音乐的审美反应方面发挥着关键作用，但音乐交流的便捷性和强大力量却使人们难以想象，他们对声音的基本反应并非普遍存在。感知到的自然性与实际的文化依赖性之间的这种差异，正是音乐如此强大的原因：它传递着关于文化和身份的信息，同时又让人感觉直接、不受任何中介。

In the West, people have attributed consonance—the perception that certain notes sound good together—to such universal forces as mathematics or the physics of the inner ear. Yet the Tsimané, an isolated Amazonian society with little exposure to Western culture, were shown to rate consonance and dissonance as equally pleasant. Despite evidence that culture plays a critical role in shaping aesthetic responses to music, something about the ease and power of musical communication makes it difficult for people to imagine that their own fundamental responses to sound are not universally shared. This divide between perceived naturalness and actual cultural dependency is precisely what allows music such tremendous force: it transmits messages about culture and identity while feeling direct and unmediated.

世界各地的音乐文化普遍或普遍地具有某些共同特征。不同文化倾向于将相差八度的音高视为等值，并将这些音高之间的空间划分为音阶。音阶倾向于不均匀地分配八度，从而更容易构建丰富的层次化音乐结构。音高之间最常见的音程通常很小——大约相当于钢琴上两个相邻琴键形成的音程。在已知的所有文化中，至少有一些音乐是有韵律的——基于规律的节拍模式——这些节拍通常分为两拍或三拍。音乐通常以离散的、可重复的行为进行，例如歌曲的演奏，而重复往往在音乐结构的多个层次上发挥着重要作用。即使两首歌曲被转调（修改为从不同的音高开始），只要音符之间的关系模式保持不变，它们仍然可以被识别为同一首歌曲。

Certain characteristics are broadly or universally shared among musical cultures throughout the world. Cultures tend to recognize pitches an octave apart as equivalent, and they divide the space between them into scales. Scales tend to apportion the octave unevenly, making it easier to build rich hierarchic musical structures. The most common interval between pitches tends to be small—about the size of the interval formed by two adjacent keys on a piano. At least some of the music in every known culture is metric—based on the regular pattern of a beat—and these beats often group into twos and threes. Music usually takes place in discrete, repeatable acts, such as the performance of a song, and repetition tends to play a major role at multiple levels of musical structure. Two songs can be recognized as the same even when they are transposed—modified to start at a different pitch level—as long as the pattern of the relationships between the notes stays the same.

音乐经常出现在仪式和娱乐的情境中。许多文化都认识到音乐能够引发特定的心境，并在群体聚集时营造一种特殊的氛围。在世界各地，人们在群体中体验音乐的频率远高于独自一人。音乐常常被认为具有超越语言的表达能力。即使音乐并非指向具体的物体或理念，它也能显得意义深远；相反，它似乎在模糊的、多重的可解读性中穿梭。剑桥大学音乐学家伊恩·克罗斯认为，这种“浮动意向性”的特质——即音乐是关于……的感觉——某种东西，但无法确切地说那种东西是什么——它允许一大群听音乐或做音乐的人体验到共同交流的乐趣，即使他们对具体细节的理解可能大相径庭。事实上，超越自我的感觉往往是世界各地聆听音乐的标志。这种强烈的体验被称为兴奋、情感过剩，或（用更通俗的说法）高度兴奋状态。音乐不是被聆听和接收，而是倾向于将人们带入它的变迁中，引发共鸣（脚趾敲击或点头）或心照不宣的参与感（在心里跟着唱，或感觉自己被音乐吸引而融入其中）。

Music occurs frequently in contexts of ritual and play. Many cultures recognize its capacity to induce particular states of mind, and to create a special atmosphere when groups assemble. Worldwide, people experience music much more frequently in groups than alone. Music is often perceived as expressive in ways that go beyond language. Music can seem deeply meaningful even when it does not denote a concrete object or idea; rather, it seems to traffic in the ambiguous, the multiple interpretable. Cambridge musicologist Ian Cross has suggested that this quality of “floating intentionality”—the sense that music is about something, but resists pinning down what precisely that something might be—allows for large groups of people listening to or making music to experience the pleasure of a shared communicative experience even though the specific details of their understanding might differ profoundly. Indeed, the sense of being transported beyond one’s self tends to be a hallmark of musical listening across the world. This powerful kind of experience has variously been referred to as effervescence, a surplus of affect, or (in less fanciful terms) a heightened state of arousal. Rather than be listened to and merely received, music tends to sweep people into its vicissitudes, eliciting sympathetic movement (toe taps or head nods) or a tacit sense of participation (mentally singing along, or feeling drawn out of yourself and into the music).

这种能力构成了达勒姆民族音乐学家马丁·克莱顿所定义的音乐的四大主要功能的基础：调节心理或生理状态、调解自我与他人、发挥象征作用以及协助协调行动。尽管不同的音乐传统都倾向于发挥这些功能，但它们运用的声音材料却大相径庭。只有一种音乐类型在不同文化中倾向于运用相同的特征：摇篮曲。在世界各地，摇篮曲往往音调更高、节奏更慢、声调更温暖。在父母在场的情况下录制的摇篮曲比在没有父母的情况下录制的摇篮曲更容易引导婴儿入睡——这表明父母与婴儿互动时，某些声音特质会自动显现。这不仅适用于摇篮曲，也适用于婴儿导向型言语——成年人与婴儿交谈的特殊方式。他们会放慢语速，夸张语调，并增加重复次数——所有这些变化都使言语更具音乐性。婴儿对这些修改反应更佳；他们喜欢经过这种音乐化的言语。音乐在人们最早的社会经验中所扮演的根本性角色，往往支持“人类本质上是音乐的”这一观点。

This capacity underlies what Durham ethnomusicologist Martin Clayton identifies as the four primary functions of music: to regulate a mental or physiological state, to mediate between self and other, to function as symbols, and to help coordinate action. Despite the fact that diverse musical traditions all tend to enact these functions, they marshal very different sonic materials to do so. Only one musical genre tends to use the same features from one culture to another: the lullaby. All over the world, lullabies tend to feature higher pitch levels, a slower pace, and a warmer vocal tone. Lullabies recorded by a parent in the presence of an infant entrance babies more successfully than lullabies recorded in the absence of one—suggesting that certain vocal qualities emerge automatically when parents interact with infants. This is true not only for lullabies, but also for infant-directed speech—the special way adults tend to talk to babies. They slow their speech down, exaggerate its prosody, and use more repetition—all changes that infuse speech with more music-like qualities. Infants respond preferentially to these modifications; they like speech that has been musicalized in this way. The fundamental role that music plays in people’s earliest social experiences tends to support a vision of humans as essentially musical.

音乐大脑

The musical brain

寻找人类这种基本音乐天赋的逻辑起点是大脑。随着神经成像工具在21世纪初的不断发展，我们能够识别执行特定任务（例如听音乐）时大脑中参与的区域。最初合理的预期可能是神经成像技术能够揭示一个音乐中心——大脑中一个专门处理音乐的独特解剖区域。然而，最终发现的证据表明，音乐依赖于一种特别分散的神经回路阵列。聆听、理解和演奏音乐的能力并非依赖于某个特定区域，而是依赖于遍布大脑的神经网络——从语音到运动规划的许多其他活动都需要用到这些神经网络。这种重叠可能解释了音乐体验和训练能够赋予多种能力，例如学习第二语言、读写能力、执行功能以及社交和情感处理。

A logical first place to look for this essential human musicality is the brain. As neuroimaging tools have evolved during the first part of the twenty-first century, it has become possible to identify the regions of the brain that engage when performing particular tasks, such as listening to music. A reasonable initial expectation might have been that neuroimaging would uncover a music center—a distinct anatomical region of the brain devoted to processing music. Instead, what emerged was evidence that music relies on an especially diffuse array of neural circuitry. Rather than depending on a single dedicated region, the ability to hear, understand, and make music calls on networks spread throughout the brain—networks used by many other activities from speech to movement planning. This overlap likely explains some of the benefits musical experience and training can confer on abilities as diverse as learning a second language, literacy, executive function, and social and emotional processing.

与早期音乐训练相关的研究最深入的特征之一是较厚的胼胝体。胼胝体是连接大脑左右两侧的神经纤维束。对这一发现的推测性解释指出，大脑中有多个区域负责音乐体验，并认为学习音乐的重要益处之一是改善大脑不同部分之间的沟通。这在直觉上是合理的，因为演奏乐器涉及感知技能（例如区分不同的音高）、运动技能（例如协调手臂动作）、视觉技能（例如读谱或观察乐团的其他成员）、认知技能（例如解读乐曲的结构）、情感技能（例如解读旋律的表现力）、社交技能（例如与老师或指挥合作）以及执行技能（例如规划练习课程）。换句话说，音乐的特别之处可能不在于它与其他事物有何不同，而在于它将其他事物联系在一起。

One of the best-studied characteristics associated with early music training is a thicker corpus callosum. The corpus callosum is a bundle of nerve fibers that connects the left and right sides of the brain. Speculative interpretations of this finding point to the multiplicity of regions subserving musical experience, and argue that one of the important benefits of learning music is improving communication between different parts of the brain. This makes intuitive sense because playing an instrument involves perceptual skills such as distinguishing different pitches, motor skills such as coordinating arm movements, visual skills such as reading music or watching other members of an ensemble, cognitive skills such as interpreting a piece’s structure, emotional skills such as interpreting the expressive aspects of a melody, social skills such as working with a teacher or conductor, and executive skills such as planning a practice session. In other words, what might be special about music is not so much that it is different from everything else, but rather that it draws everything else together.

另一方面，现有研究无法确定音乐训练是否会使胼胝体增厚，或者胼胝体较厚的人是否更有可能主动寻求音乐训练。唯一能确定的方法是进行一项纵向研究，在儿童开始音乐训练之前扫描他们的大脑，并在成年后再次扫描，但这类研究成本高昂，逻辑上也十分复杂。因此，许多关于音乐训练对大脑影响的研究本质上是相关性而非因果性的——它识别出训练与特定特征之间的关联，但无法确认训练是否真的导致了这种影响。

On the other hand, it is impossible to conclude from existing research whether music training leads to a thicker corpus callosum, or whether people with a thicker corpus callosum are likelier to seek out music training in the first place. The only way to know for sure would be to engage in a longitudinal study, scanning children’s brains before the onset of music training and again, as adults, at the end of it, yet studies like this are expensive and logistically complex. Accordingly, much of the research on the effect of music training on the brain is correlational rather than causal in nature—it identifies an association between training and specific characteristics, but it cannot confirm whether training actually caused the effect.

聆听音乐往往显得毫不费力，无需任何中介。转瞬之间，我们就能辨认出一首儿时流行的歌曲，或是感受到一段旋律中某种难以言喻的悲伤。然而，这些印象始于物理现象——耳膜振动，导致耳膜后方微小骨质移位，进而扰动内耳液体，进而移动毛细胞，将电信号传递至听觉神经。这些信号经过多个中转站进行处理，中转站会整合双耳信息，计算出声音的方位，调节诸如惊吓反应之类的反射，并将听觉信息与视觉等其他感官信息整合，最终到达大脑皮层——大脑外层褶皱的部分，负责产生意识、更高层次的思维和感知。

Listening to music often seems effortless and unmediated. Within a fraction of a second, we can recognize a song that was popular during our childhood or sense a specific and difficult-to-articulate kind of sadness within a melody. Yet these impressions begin as physical phenomena—the vibration of eardrums, which displaces the tiny bones behind them, which perturbs the fluid in the inner ear, which, in turn, moves hair cells, sending electrical signals up the auditory nerve. These signals pass through several waystations that refine the signal, combine information from both ears to compute the location of the sound, modulate reflexes such as the startle response, and integrate acoustic information with information from other modalities, such as vision, before reaching the cortex—the folded outer layer of the brain that gives rise to awareness and higher-level thought and perception.

初级听觉皮层位于大脑两侧靠近耳朵的地方，位于颞叶的颞上回。接受过大量音乐训练的人的这个区域更大：考虑到皮层具有可塑性，即随着使用和经验而变化的趋势，这并不奇怪。但接受过音乐训练的人的脑干细胞也能更准确地追踪声音的特性。因为这部分大脑，通常被随意地称为“爬行动物”，是人类最古老的大脑区域之一，已经进化了数百万年。几年前，音乐就被用来调节呼吸和心跳等基本功能，而得知音乐体验可能能够增强其某些功能，尤其令人吃惊。

The primary auditory cortex is located along the sides of the brain near the ears, on the superior temporal gyrus in the temporal lobe. This region is larger in people with extensive musical training: not surprising, given the cortex’s plasticity, or tendency to change with use and experience. But cells in the brainstem also track properties of sound more accurately in people who have had music training. Because this part of the brain, often referred to casually as “reptilian,” is one of the oldest in humans, having evolved millions of years ago to regulate essential functions such as breathing and heartbeats, it is particularly startling to learn that musical experience might be able to enhance aspects of its functioning.

虽然初级听觉皮层负责识别音高等任务，但许多我们认为与音乐息息相关的行为，例如跟随节拍或关注歌曲的表现力，却依赖于远远超出其范围的神经回路。负责自主运动计划和执行的运动皮层，在人们聆听音乐时也会参与其中，即使他们静坐不动。这一发现支持了这样一种观点：音乐可以引发想象运动的体验，将听众拉入其轨道，甚至让静止的听众也产生一种共鸣的身体参与感。基底神经节是位于皮层下方的神经元簇，负责监督目标导向的动作序列、构成根深蒂固习惯的运动模式以及动作学习。它们在处理基于节拍的音乐方面也发挥着至关重要的作用——这种音乐具有时间特征，可以让听众跟着拍手并预测未来事件发生的时间点。例如，电子舞曲鼓励这种参与和时间预测，但中世纪的素歌却没有。在素歌中，音符漫无目的，缺乏时间规律性，听众无法准确知道下一个音符何时出现。

Although the primary auditory cortex is responsible for tasks such as recognizing pitch, many of the behaviors we think about as distinctly musical, such as following a beat or attending to the expressive qualities of a song, rely on circuitry that extends far beyond it. The motor cortex, responsible for the planning and execution of voluntary movements, also engages when people listen to music, even when they are sitting still. This finding supports the notion that music can elicit experiences of imagined movement, pulling listeners into its orbit and involving even stationary listeners in a sense of sympathetic physical engagement. The basal ganglia, clusters of neurons located underneath the cortex, oversee goal-directed action sequences, movement patterns that form parts of ingrained habits, and action learning. They also contribute critically to processing beat-based music—music with the kind of temporal characteristics that allow listeners to clap along and predict the timepoint at which future events will happen. Electronic dance music, for example, encourages this kind of involvement and temporal prediction, but medieval plainchant does not. In plainchant, the notes amble around without the kind of temporal regularity that would allow listeners to orient precisely to when the next note should occur.

音乐带来的巅峰情绪反应也受到了认知神经科学的广泛关注。当音乐引发强烈的愉悦感，并伴有寒意或脊背发凉时，包括腹侧纹状体、眶额皮质和腹侧内侧前额皮质在内的奖赏回路就会启动。食物和性爱带来的狂喜体验也会激活同样的回路，但在这些情况下，更容易想象是进化压力刺激了这些行为。神经递质多巴胺的释放在奖赏系统中起着关键作用。聆听音乐时，多巴胺不仅会在最强烈的愉悦时刻释放，而且在听到这些话之前，预期和预测也起着至关重要的作用，即使在被动聆听中也是如此。

Peak emotional responses to music have also received substantial attention from cognitive neuroscience. When music triggers intense pleasure accompanied by a sensation of chills, or shivers down the spine, reward circuitry, including the ventral striatum, orbitofrontal cortex, and ventral medial prefrontal cortex, deploys. Ecstatic experiences of food and sex activate the same circuitry, but, in those cases, it is easier to imagine evolutionary pressure incentivizing the behavior. The release of the neurotransmitter dopamine plays a key role in the reward system. When listening to music, dopamine releases not only during the most intensely pleasurable moment, but also during the moments leading up to it, signaling the critical role of anticipation and prediction even in passive listening.

音乐的神经科学研究表明，音乐和语言处理之间存在大量重叠。音乐和言语的工作记忆似乎依赖于相同的神经基础，一些人认为，音乐的结构和规则部分与支持语言语法处理的区域相同。

Neuroscientific studies of music show substantial overlap between music and language processing. Working memory for music and speech seems to rely on the same neural underpinnings, and some argue that the structural, rule-based aspects of music are supported by the same regions that support the processing of grammar in language.

我们很难不注意到，音乐处理与人类其他功能，从运动到动机，有着多么深刻的融合。这种功能的重叠，以及大脑的根本可塑性——或者说，改变的能力——为音乐体验能够影响一系列其他能力奠定了基础。

It is difficult not to notice how deeply musical processing integrates with other aspects of human functioning, from movement to motivation. This functional overlap and the brain’s fundamental plasticity—or capacity to change—sets up the circumstances by which musical experience can affect a host of other abilities.

音乐与健康

Music and health

音乐对人类生活和健康有着强大影响的观念已存在数千年。在《理想国》中，柏拉图称赞音乐训练能够塑造灵魂，并且他主张禁止某些音阶，因为它们会导致酗酒和懒惰。据说他的学生用音乐治疗从歇斯底里到癫痫等各种神经疾病。但关于音乐和健康的观念不仅在西方流传；世界各地的文化都将音乐融入到治疗仪式中。许多人本能地借助音乐来帮助他们感觉更好，或者帮助他们跑得更快或举起更重的重量。在美国，一个名为美国音乐治疗协会的专业组织和在英国名为英国音乐治疗协会的组织负责监督音乐治疗应用的培训和研究。

The notion that music powerfully affects human life and wellness has existed for millennia. In The Republic, Plato extolled music training as capable of shaping the soul—and he advocated banning particular scales on the basis that they encouraged drunkenness and laziness. His students are said to have used music to cure nervous disorders ranging from hysteria to seizures. But ideas about music and health circulate not only in the West; cultures the world over integrate music into healing ceremonies. Many people intuitively turn to music to help them feel better or to help them run faster or lift heavier weights. In the United States, a professional organization known as the American Music Therapy Association and, in the United Kingdom, the British Association for Music Therapy, oversee training and research in the therapeutic applications of music.

负责音乐的神经回路和负责运动控制的神经回路重叠意味着简单的听音乐有时可以帮助患有严重运动障碍的人。例如，帕金森病患者会出现一种运动迟缓的症状，即使是简单的任务和四处走动也难以完成。他们还会出现震颤、肌肉僵硬以及平衡和僵硬问题。帕金森病是一种退行性疾病，会影响大脑深层细胞，包括基底神经节。该区域也是对节拍型音乐进行预期处理的中心。当帕金森病患者聆听有节奏的音乐时，他们的步态会明显改善（YouTube 上有许多精彩的视频，捕捉了听音乐前后的步态差异），他们的协调性、姿势和平衡能力也会得到改善。这种益处并非源于任何类型的节奏——例如，可以通过闪烁的图像产生视觉节奏，或者通过在特定时间模式下施加触觉压力来产生触觉节奏——而只能源于对听觉节奏的反应。听觉系统的反应时间比其他感觉系统快几十毫秒，并且它对时间规律性和结构有着独特的适应能力。帕金森病患者的动作能够与音乐的节拍结构同步，步态和协调性的显著改善有时甚至会持续到治疗结束后。

The overlap of the neural circuitry devoted to music and the neural circuitry devoted to motor control means that the simple act of listening to music can sometimes help people with serious movement disorders. People with Parkinson’s disease, for example, experience a kind of slowed movement that makes even simple tasks and getting around difficult. They also suffer from tremors, muscle stiffness, and problems with balance and rigidity. Parkinson’s, a degenerative disorder, affects cells in deep parts of the brain, including the basal ganglia. This area also serves as the seat of anticipatory processing for beat-based music. When people with Parkinson’s disease listen to rhythmic music, their gait noticeably improves (YouTube features a number of compelling videos capturing gait differences before and during music listening), as does their coordination, posture, and balance. This benefit does not accrue to just any kind of rhythm—it is possible to generate visual rhythms by flashing images, for example, or tactile ones by applying touch pressure in particular temporal patterns—but only in response to auditory rhythms. The auditory system’s reaction time is faster by several tens of milliseconds than these other sensory systems, and it is uniquely attuned to temporal regularity and structure. People with Parkinson’s disease synchronize their movements to the beat structure in the music, and considerable improvements in gait and coordination can sometimes extend past the end of the therapeutic session.

负责处理音乐的神经回路也与负责处理语音的神经回路存在重叠。左半球下额回因中风或外伤而受损的人可能会患上非流利性失语症，这是一种极其令人沮丧的障碍，即使失去了流利说话的能力，语言理解能力仍然能够保留。旋律语调疗法是一种成熟的治疗这种疾病的方法，它利用言语的音乐性来促进右半球未受损区域的语言发展。无法说出单个单词的人会被教导用歌唱的方式，并逐渐过渡到无需额外强调旋律和节奏的说话方式（YouTube 上详细记录了这一过程）。由于治疗师的最终目标是帮助患者能够流利地自发讲话，他们还会教患者通过轻敲左手、哼唱并轻声吟唱来生成自己的目标短语，鼓励他们努力将短语听成内心的歌声。许多完成该项目的人不仅能够自给自足，还能在学习课程之外学习更多短语。

Neural circuitry devoted to music processing also overlaps with the neural circuitry devoted to speech processing. People who experience damage to the inferior frontal gyrus in the left hemisphere via stroke or traumatic injury can acquire nonfluent aphasia, an extremely frustrating impairment in which language comprehension can be preserved even as the ability to speak fluently is lost. Melodic Intonation Therapy, a well-established treatment for this condition, harnesses the musical aspects of speech to encourage language development within undamaged regions in the right hemisphere. People who cannot produce individual words are taught to sing them and gradually to transition to speaking them without the extra melodic and rhythmic emphasis (a procedure well chronicled on YouTube). Since therapists ultimately hope to help their patients produce fluent spontaneous speech, they also teach them to generate their own target phrases by tapping their left hand, humming and then softly singing the words, encouraging them to strive to hear the phrase as if it were being sung internally. Many people who graduate from the program attain self-sufficiency and the power to learn additional phrases beyond the study sessions.

音乐在大脑多个区域和通路的驻留，有助于音乐记忆在痴呆症严重破坏记忆系统的情况下依然存在。大量临床观察表明，即使病情发展到晚期，痴呆症患者仍然能够记住并享受青春期的音乐。此外，患有严重认知障碍的人也能继续识别音乐片段的情感共鸣。一些人声称，这些成功的音乐记忆片段可以改善在体验过程中以及体验结束后，非音乐相关任务的认知功能。

Music’s colonization of multiple brain areas and pathways helps musical memories survive even when dementia has profoundly disrupted memory systems. Numerous clinical observations suggest that dementia patients can remember and enjoy the music of their adolescence even when they have progressed to advanced stages of the disease. Moreover, people with serious cognitive impairments can continue to identify the emotional resonance of musical selections. Some claim that these episodes of successful musical remembering can improve cognitive functioning on non-music-related tasks in the moments during and immediately after the experiences.

数据显示，与没有背景音乐的新生儿重症监护病房 (NICU) 的婴儿相比，在有背景音乐的新生儿重症监护病房 (NICU) 中，婴儿进食更多、哭闹更少、睡眠质量更好，住院天数也更少，这进一步证实了音乐与健康之间的基本联系。此外，在播放音乐的病房工作的成年人也表示焦虑感有所降低，这可能是一个中介变量——婴儿的康复结果改善可能源于更冷静的医护人员能够提供更好的护理。另一种关于音乐对 NICU 婴儿有益的假设认为，音乐能提供对发育和康复至关重要的神经刺激，而挣扎的婴儿无法通过其他方式获得这种刺激。

Very basic connections between music and health are reinforced by data showing that babies in neonatal intensive care units (NICUs) with background music eat more food, cry less, sleep better, and require fewer days in the hospital than babies in units without background music. Then again, adults working in the units that play music also report feeling less anxious, which serves as a possible mediating variable—babies’ improved outcomes could derive from the capacity of a calmer staff to provide improved care. An alternative hypothesis for music’s benefit to NICU babies holds that it provides neurological stimulation essential to development and recovery that struggling babies lack the energy to obtain in other ways.

对于所有年龄段的人来说，放松的音乐都能产生不同的生理效应，从降低血压到减慢脉搏。当人们听自己喜欢的音乐时，他们的疼痛感耐受力会提高，衡量标准是他们愿意将手浸入极冷水中的时间长短等行为。然而，这些影响显然受到文化和经验的影响，因为对一个群体来说可能非常愉悦的音乐，对另一个群体，或者对处于不同境遇的同一个人，可能非常令人厌恶，甚至造成创伤。关塔那摩湾的囚犯被强迫听金属乐队（Metallica）的录音，作为一种酷刑；在20世纪90年代德克萨斯州韦科监狱围攻期间，大卫教派的成员也被迫听安迪·威廉姆斯的专辑，目的也是一样的。

For people of all ages, relaxing music can produce distinct physiological effects ranging from lowered blood pressure to a slower pulse. When people listen to music they enjoy, their pain tolerance improves, as measured by such behaviors as the length of time they’re willing to keep their hand immersed in extremely cold water. Yet these effects are clearly mediated by culture and experience, since music that can be highly pleasurable to one group can be highly obnoxious—even traumatic—to another, or to the same people in a different circumstance. Guantánamo Bay prisoners were subjected to recordings of Metallica as a form of torture, and during the 1990s siege of its Waco, Texas, compound, members of the Branch Davidian sect were subjected to Andy Williams albums for the same purpose.

非人类动物有音乐天赋吗？

Are nonhuman animals musical?

乍一看，人类似乎是唯一拥有音乐天赋的动物。我们进化史上最亲近的“亲戚”——类人猿，并不会自发地做出那些我们能识别为音乐的行为。灵长类动物并没有表现出对音乐的持续偏好，无论是对寂静还是对和谐悦耳的音乐，还是对不和谐的、被西方听众视为不和谐的音乐。

At first glance, humans seem to be the only musical animals. Our closest evolutionary relatives, the great apes, do not spontaneously indulge in behaviors we would recognize as musical. Primates do not show a consistent preference for music over silence, or for consonant, pleasant-sounding music over music that is dissonant and perceived by Western listeners as discordant.

然而，仔细观察就会发现，不同物种各自拥有构成音乐才能的某些基本要素。例如，大猩猩、黑猩猩和猕猴通过拍手或敲击树木、原木或自己的胸口来打鼓，啄木鸟则用喙来钻孔。许多不同物种，包括鸣禽、鹦鹉、蜂鸟、海豹、大象、蝙蝠和鲸鱼，都表现出声音学习的能力——即通过模仿获得新发声的能力。这种能力与音乐才能尤为密切相关，因为它依赖于听觉系统（负责感知和呈现声音）与运动系统（负责再现声音）之间的关键联系。听觉系统和运动系统之间的这种联系也是人类音乐能力的关键基础。与人类一样，所有三种表现出声音学习能力的鸟类都拥有连接听觉区域和运动区域之间的直接神经通路，而没有声音学习能力的物种则不具备这种通路。

Yet a closer examination reveals that different species possess in isolation some of the building blocks that together constitute musicality. For example, gorillas, chimpanzees, and macaques drum by clapping their hands or banging on trees, logs, or their own chests, and woodpeckers drill with their beak. A host of different species, including songbirds, parrots, hummingbirds, seals, elephants, bats, and whales, exhibit vocal learning—the ability to acquire new vocalizations through imitation. This ability relates particularly closely to musicality because it depends on a key link between the auditory system, which is devoted to perceiving and representing sound, and the motor system, which is devoted to reproducing it. This connection between the auditory and the motor systems also critically underlies the human musical capacity. Like humans, all three bird species that exhibit vocal learning possess direct neural pathways between auditory and motor regions that species without vocal learning do not possess.

其他一些物种也表现出群体同步性——大群雄性萤火虫可以同步闪光；大群雄性青蛙、蝉和蟋蟀可以同步（或称“同步”）它们的求偶鸣叫，发出嘈杂的合唱。这种同步定位的能力也是人类能够跟着节拍打拍子或进行合奏的基础。从蟋蟀、海豹、鸣禽到黑猩猩，这些展现出部分音乐才能的动物显然不占据进化树上的任何一个分支。据推测，这些能力是在不同物种中独立产生的，而不是通过从共同祖先遗传而来的。人类的近亲并不比远亲表现出更多的构成能力，这一事实意味着音乐才能的进化并不存在简单明了的路径。

Several other species exhibit group synchrony—large groups of male fireflies can flash in time with each other; large groups of male frogs, cicadas, and crickets can synchronize, or entrain, their mating calls to generate a noisy chorus. This capacity to orient together in time also underlies the human ability to tap along to a beat or play with an ensemble. The animals that display parts of the musical capacity, ranging from crickets, seals, and songbirds to chimpanzees, clearly do not occupy a single branch of the evolutionary tree. Presumably, these abilities arose independently in different species rather than via inheritance from a shared ancestor. The fact that humans’ closest relatives do not display more of the component abilities than more distant relatives implies that no simple and unambiguous path for the evolution of musicality exists.

一些关于动物音乐天赋的案例研究引起了人们的特别关注。21世纪初，YouTube上一段名为“雪球”（Snowball）的凤头鹦鹉随着后街男孩的歌曲翩翩起舞的视频引起了加州拉霍亚市神经科学研究所的阿尼鲁德·帕特尔（Aniruddh Patel）和约翰·艾弗森（John Iversen）的注意。他们着手系统地研究“雪球”是否能够在不依赖训练员视觉提示的情况下，自发地与节拍同步。他们以几种不同的速度播放了“雪球”最喜欢的歌曲，并录下了它的动作，分析了动作的波峰和波谷，并测量了它们与基础节拍的一致性。“雪球”确实能够使自己的动作与不同的音乐节拍同步：这非凡地展现了动物能够完成一项此前被认为是人类才能完成的任务的能力。它能够根据听觉节奏模式调整动作，这展现了听觉-运动联系，这种联系被认为对人类的音乐天赋至关重要。

Some case studies of animal musicality have aroused special interest. In the 2000s, a YouTube clip of a cockatoo named Snowball dancing to a Backstreet Boys song was brought to the attention of Aniruddh Patel and John Iversen at the Neurosciences Institute in La Jolla, California. They set out to systematically study whether Snowball could spontaneously synchronize to a beat without relying on visual cues from a trainer. They played Snowball’s favorite song at several different speeds and video recorded his movements, analyzing their peaks and troughs and measuring their degree of alignment with the underlying beat. Snowball was indeed able to synchronize his movements to different musical beats: a remarkable demonstration of an animal’s capacity to perform a task previously thought to be relegated to humans. His ability to modulate his movements in response to auditory timing patterns demonstrates the kind of auditory-motor connections thought to be essential to musicality in humans.

同样令人吃惊的是，研究人员发现，只要按下正确的按钮，鸽子就能用喙正确地识别出新的音乐片段，并将其归类为斯特拉文斯基的这项研究表明，鲤鱼能够识别《春之祭》或巴赫的管风琴作品，并能够被训练将新的音乐片段分类为布鲁斯或古典音乐。这些结果虽然引人注目，但并不意味着鱼类和鸟类拥有审美感知。相反，它们表明一些鱼类和鸟类能够感知区分音乐流派的基本声学特征，例如是否存在管风琴或贝斯。例如，鸽子无需掌握抽象的风格特征或音阶系统信息即可完成这项任务。

Also startling were findings that pigeons could be trained to correctly categorize by pushing the correct button, with their beak, new musical excerpts as originating from Stravinsky’sRite of Spring or a Bach composition for organ, and that carp could be trained to categorize new musical excerpts as blues or classical. Striking as these results seem, they do not imply that fish and birds possess aesthetic sensibilities. Rather, they demonstrate that some fish and birds can detect the basic acoustic features that distinguish musical genres, such as the presence or absence of an organ or a bass guitar. The pigeons need not have abstracted stylistic features or information about the scale system, for example, to perform the task.

过度解读这些研究的诱惑，为文化现象的科学考察提供了一个重要的提醒——解读应从研究中精确的操作出发，谨慎行事，同时注意潜在的混淆因素。进一步的实验工作可以解决悬而未决的问题。例如，用刺激的MIDI转录重新运行鸽子和鲤鱼的研究，使乐器在斯特拉文斯基和巴赫之间，或布鲁斯和古典音乐之间保持一致，可以确定分类是否依赖于低级声学线索。一旦乐器的表面特征被剥离，鸟类和鱼类大概就无法再区分不同的类别了。

The temptation to overinterpret these studies provides an important reminder about the scientific examination of cultural phenomena—interpretation should proceed carefully from the precise manipulations in the study, remaining mindful of potential confounds. Further experimental work can resolve outstanding questions. For example, rerunning the pigeon and carp studies with MIDI transcriptions of the stimuli, so that the instrumentation did not vary between Stravinsky and Bach or between blues and classical, could determine whether the categorization relied on low-level acoustic cues. Once the surface feature of instrumentation was stripped away, the birds and fish would presumably no longer be able to discriminate between the categories.

有一种鸣禽，红腹灰雀，以展现出非凡的才能而闻名。一只特别有进取心的红腹灰雀能够从训练员那里学会一首四十五音符的曲子，并准确地以原音高唱出。其他红腹灰雀可以与训练员交替演唱，等待人类唱完一段后再继续唱。这些成就不仅体现了它们在相对音高（抽象四十五音符模式并以不同音高再现的能力）方面的非凡学习能力，也体现了它们在节奏和预判（等待人类唱完旋律部分并以合适的音高继续演唱的能力）方面的非凡学习能力。

One songbird species, the bullfinch, has been known to demonstrate especially prodigious abilities. A particularly enterprising bullfinch was able to learn a forty-five-note tune from its trainer and perform it accurately at the original pitch level. Other bullfinches can sing in alternation with a trainer, waiting their turn to continue a tune after the human sings an intervening part. These achievements represent impressive learning not only in terms of relative pitch (the capacity to abstract the forty-five-note pattern and reproduce it at another pitch level), but also in terms of timing and anticipation (the ability to wait through the human’s part of the melody and enter with the appropriate continuation).

音乐的进化起源

The evolutionary origins of music

不同物种的比较研究证据并不能完整地展现音乐的进化史。没有清晰的渐进路径可以追溯不同物种中个体构成要素的习得，最终导致人类音乐天赋的全面发展。同样，也没有任何确凿的证据，例如独特的大脑结构或特定的基因组合，能够明确地证明音乐的生物学基础。因此，一些人完全拒绝接受自然选择直接塑造音乐能力的观点，认为音乐是人类利用为其他目的而进化的生物器官的发明，这并不奇怪。进化心理学家史蒂芬·平克将音乐比作“听觉芝士蛋糕”，概括了这种观点。正如对芝士蛋糕的特定口味并非进化而来——相反，芝士蛋糕利用了人类对糖和脂肪的潜在偏好——他认为，音乐天赋并非源于进化压力。相反，他认为，音乐天赋依赖于其他能力，这些能力的进化显然是为了支持增强生存的功能。

Evidence from comparative studies of different species does not tell a compelling story about music’s evolutionary history. No clear incremental path through different species traces the acquisition of individual components leading to full-blown musicality in humans. Similarly, there is no smoking gun, such as a distinct brain structure or particular set of genes, that unambiguously demonstrates a biological basis for music. It is not surprising, then, that some have rejected the idea that natural selection directly shaped the musical capacity at all, viewing music instead as a human invention exploiting biological apparatuses that evolved for other purposes. Evolutionary psychologist Steven Pinker encapsulated this perspective when he referred to music as “auditory cheesecake.” Just as a specific taste for cheesecake did not evolve—rather, cheesecake exploits underlying proclivities for sugar and fat—he argues that aptitude for music did not arise from evolutionary pressure. Instead, he suggests, musicality relies on other capacities that evolved to support more clearly survival-enhancing functions.

那些认为创作和欣赏音乐的能力具有更直接的生物学基础的人，指出了这些能力可能通过多种方式获得适应性。音乐促进社会联系，可能使更紧密、更高效的群体在进化中占据优势。音乐调节婴儿的唤醒状态，可能使婴儿在父母用手进行其他有益活动时能够茁壮成长，从而获得进化优势。音乐帮助人们及时同步行为和注意力，可能使劳动协调性更强，从而获得进化优势。或许，音乐能力是通过性选择而产生的，就像孔雀的尾羽一样（尽管在所有已知文化中，音乐天赋是两性共同的特征，这一事实似乎与这一观点相悖）。

People who believe that the ability to make and enjoy music has a more direct biological basis point to several ways that these capacities might have been adaptive. Music facilitates social bonding, potentially resulting in the evolutionary advantage of tighter-knit and more effective groups. Music modulates infant arousal states, potentially resulting in the evolutionary advantage of babies who could flourish while their parents used their hands to perform other useful tasks. Music helps people sync their behavior and attention in time, potentially resulting in the evolutionary advantage of better coordinated labor. Perhaps the capacity for music arose through sexual selection, like the peacock’s tail (although the fact that musicality characterizes both genders in all known cultures seems to argue against this notion).

通过调查世界各地的音乐实践多样性和大脑结构的多样性，我们可以清楚地看到支持这一观点的必要条件是音乐本身包含许多单独的组成部分；因此，它的进化史可能涵盖各种阶段和机制。当人们思考进化时，他们通常会思考适应，即赋予生存优势的特定特征逐渐在种群中占据主导地位的过程。但其他过程也起了作用。有时，在一个称为扩展适应的过程中，由于赋予特定益处而进化的特征最终会实现一种新的、有用的功能，而这种功能最初并未被选择，而这种新功能推动了进一步的进化。在其他情况下，特定的、被选择的特征会带来不影响进化轨迹的副产品；它只是与原始特征“免费”相伴。这些副产品被称为拱肩。

What does seem clear from surveying the diversity of musical practice around the world and the diversity of brain structures required to support it is that music itself encompasses a host of individual components; accordingly, its evolutionary history is likely to encompass a variety of stages and mechanisms. When people think about evolution, they often think about adaptation, the process by which a particular trait that confers a survival advantage gradually becomes dominant within a population. But other processes contribute as well. Sometimes, in a process called exaptation, a trait that evolved because it conferred a particular benefit ultimately enables a new and helpful function for which it was not originally selected, and this new function drives further evolution. In other cases, a particular, selected-for trait brings along a by-product that does not affect evolutionary trajectories; it merely “comes along for free” with the original characteristic. These by-products are called spandrels.

音乐能力的出现可能涉及不同阶段的适应、扩展适应和拱肩——这是一个混乱的假设，它掩盖了那些试图将音乐归因于生物学来证明其文化作用的人的愿望。这种观点认为，音乐值得关注和支持，因为进化将它写入了我们的基因。但真的需要用这种过于简单的解释来支持一种遍布全球、深刻地感动着如此众多人的行为吗？或许，不妨稍微解释一下：即使音乐是100%的拱肩，并非源于直接的选择压力，它对众多生物基质的依赖、其全球普遍性以及其强大的社会影响力，都为持续探究这种独特的人类艺术提供了理由。

The emergence of the capacity for music likely involved adaptations, exaptations, and spandrels at different stages—a messy supposition that belies the aspirations of people who would seek to justify music’s cultural role by attributing it to biology. Music is worthy of interest and support, the argument goes, because evolution wrote it into our genes. But need this simplistic account really be recruited to buttress the merits of a behavior that spans the world and moves so many so profoundly? A bit of devil’s advocacy may help illuminate the point: even if music were 100 percent spandrel, having arisen through no direct selective pressure, its reliance on so many biological substrates, its global universality, and its substantial societal power all make the case for sustained inquiry into this distinctively human art.

第三章

Chapter 3

音乐作为语言

Music as language

音乐给人一种强有力的沟通感。音乐真的是一种语言吗？如果是，它的含义是什么？它又是如何传达这些含义的？要精通音乐需要什么？音乐语法和语言语法的运作方式一样吗？
