Music can feel like it communicates powerfully. Is music actually some sort of language? If so, what does it mean and how does it convey these meanings? What would it take to be fluent in music? Do musical grammars work the same way as linguistic grammars?

的确，音乐和语言之间确实存在一些惊人的相似之处。作为交流系统，它们都包含一些通用的组成部分，但也存在着巨大的文化差异。两者都由复杂的听觉信号组成，这些信号可以（但并非必须）以符号的形式进行视觉呈现。两者都涉及人际协调：就语言而言，是进行对话；就音乐而言，是与一群人一起演奏。两者都将离散的声音单元组合成丰富的结构——就语言而言，是句子和段落；就音乐而言，是短语和乐段。

Indeed, some similarities between music and language seem striking. As communicative systems, they both feature some universal components and much cultural variation. Both consist of complex auditory signals that can be (but do not have to be) visually represented in notation. Both can involve interpersonal coordination: to hold a conversation in the case of language, or to play with a group in the case of music. Both combine discrete sound units into rich structures—sentences and paragraphs in the case of language, phrases and sections in the case of music.

由于认知心理学在转向音乐之前已经研究了多年的语言，心理语言学提供了丰富的假设、方法和问题，帮助在早期阶段构建了尚处于萌芽阶段的音乐认知科学。即使到了现在，将音乐与语言进行比较仍然是一种颇具吸引力的基础方法。在最糟糕的情况下，这可能会导致人们忽视音乐中不符合语言模型的方面。但更多时候，它会带来积极的结果：通过阐明语言模型无法迁移的原因，比较为思考音乐提供了一个新的框架。数十年来，对音乐与语言关系的研究已结出丰硕的成果。

Because cognitive psychology had studied language for many years before turning to music, psycholinguistics provided a rich collection of hypotheses, methods, and questions to help frame the nascent cognitive science of music in its earliest stages. Even now, comparing music to language remains seductive as a foundational approach. In the worst case, this can result in a kind of blindness to the aspects of music that do not fit the linguistic model. But more often, it results in something positive: by delineating the ways in which linguistic models fail to transfer, the comparison provides a new framework for thinking about music. The multi-decade inquiry into the relationship between music and language has borne rich fruit.

音乐语法和音乐表现力

Musical grammar and musical expressivity

语言最显著的特征之一是句法，即支配句子结构的一套规则。因此，“劳拉吃西兰花”与“西兰花吃劳拉”是截然不同的断言。语言包含一组原子单位——单词——它们按照这套规则排列，因此某些违反规则的组合是不正确或无意义的（“劳拉吃西兰花”）。与语言一样，音乐也由一组原子单位——单个音符——组成，这些音符按照某些规则组合而成。大多数人都是在婴幼儿时期通过日常接触，隐性地学习支配语言的句法规则，无需任何正式指导。然而，一旦进入学校，他们就可以以更明确的方式学习这些规则，例如在语法课上。同样，大多数人也是在隐性地学习支配音乐的句法规则，无需任何正式指导，只需通过日常聆听即可，尽管也可以选修旨在明确传达这些规则的音乐理论课程。

One of the most distinctive elements of language is syntax, the set of rules that governs sentence structure, making “Laura eats broccoli” an entirely different assertion from “broccoli eats Laura.” Language involves a set of atomic units—words—that are arranged in conformance with this set of rules so that some combinations that break the rules are incorrect or nonsensical (“eats broccoli Laura”). Like language, music consists of a set of atomic units—individual notes—that are combined according to certain rules. Most people learn the syntactic rules that govern language implicitly, without any formal instruction, simply through everyday exposure as a baby and toddler. Once they enter school, however, they can study these rules in a more explicit way, in grammar classes, for example. Similarly, most people learn the syntactic rules that govern music implicitly, without any formal instruction, simply through everyday listening, although it is possible to take classes in music theory that aim to convey them explicitly.

没有上过音乐课的人可能会声称自己没有学过那些所谓的音符组合规则。但任何能注意到演奏者弹错音符，或直觉地预知乐曲即将结束的人，都已经抽象出了音乐底层结构规则的重要部分。以错误音符为例。它可能会因为不属于底层调，或者因为它的跳跃与主导旋律线不符而显得不协调，从而显得不正确。虽然大多数情况下，这类错误音符是由于演奏者失误造成的，但作曲家有时会直接将其写入乐谱，例如20世纪俄罗斯作曲家谢尔盖·普罗科菲耶夫的“错误”故意强调听起来像错误的音符的旋律。音乐理论家大卫·休伦分析了普罗科菲耶夫《彼得与狼》的主题，以说明这些故意的“错误音符”可以被艺术地运用，以传达特定的表达特质——在本例中，就是将彼得刻画成任性或淘气的样子。这种灵活性是否意味着音乐规则比语言规则更具可塑性？

People who have not taken music classes might assert that they have not learned the supposed rules that govern the ways notes are put together. But anyone who has noticed when a performer played a wrong note or intuited when a piece was about to come to an end has abstracted important parts of the music’s underlying structural rules. Take the case of the wrong note. It might pop out as incorrect because it does not belong to the underlying key, or because it makes an awkward leap that does not fit with the governing melodic line. Although most of the time, a wrong note of this sort arises because of performer error, composers will sometimes write them directly into the score, as in the case of twentieth-century Russian composer Sergei Prokofiev’s “wrong note” melodies, which purposely emphasize notes that sound like errors. Music theorist David Huron analyzes the theme from Prokofiev’s Peter and the Wolf to illustrate that these intentional “wrong notes” can be used artistically, to transmit specific expressive properties—in this case, a characterization of Peter as willful or mischievous. Does this flexibility mean that music’s rules are more malleable than those of language?

要回答这个问题，请考虑上面使用的句法错误的话语的例子：“吃西兰花劳拉”。不难想到在哪些情况下可以采用这种表达方式来达到真正的交际目的。例如，一个班上有两个学生都叫劳拉。第一天，她们进行了自我介绍，并讲了一个有趣的事实来帮助班上的人互相了解。第一个劳拉说她不吃西兰花。第二个劳拉开玩笑说，事实上，她吃西兰花。从那时起，老师就叫第二个学生“吃西兰花劳拉”。就像音乐的例子一样，错误的音符带有特定的表达联想，这种句法错误的语言用法传达了一种特定的态度：它暗示着不敬和老师试图娱乐的意图。

To answer this question, consider the example of the syntactically incorrect utterance used above: “eats broccoli Laura.” It is not difficult to think of scenarios in which this expression could be adopted to serve a real communicative purpose. There could be a class, for example, in which two students were named Laura. On the first day, they introduced themselves, including a fun fact to help people in the class get to know each other. The first Laura said she does not eat broccoli. The second Laura joked that she does, in fact, eat broccoli. From then on, the teacher called the second student “eats broccoli Laura.” Like the musical example, where the wrong note carries particular expressive associations, this linguistic use of a syntactical mistake conveys a particular attitude: it suggests irreverence and an attempt by the teacher to entertain.

但另一个语言学的例子又如何呢？简单地颠倒一下首尾两个词，就能把原本相对无害的“女人吃西兰花”的描述，变成恐怖电影里“西兰花吃女人”的场景。句法在决定单个句子的意义方面起着至关重要的作用。音乐意义的运作方式与语言截然不同，但句法也发挥着同样重要的作用。要理解这一作用，需要思考结构是如何随时间展开的。

But what about the other linguistic example, where the simple reversal of the first and last words could transform the relatively innocuous description of a woman eating broccoli into the horror-movie scenario of broccoli eating a woman? Syntax plays a critical role in determining the meaning of individual sentences. Musical meaning works very differently from language, but syntax plays a similarly important part. To understand this role requires thinking about how structure unfolds in time.

当我们聆听语音时，我们会不断预测接下来会出现哪些单词，并提前分配认知资源来处理这些单词。这种预测处理快速而高效——它会预先选择最有可能的后续单词，这样我们就不会浪费时间。随着对话的进行，人们需要花费大量时间搜索数千个可能的词语表达。一旦对方说“你好吗”，一些资源就已经分配给“你”了。经典证据来自启动效应研究，这些研究表明，人们在执行任意任务时，例如数字母或检测单词中的错误（这些错误可以从先前的上下文中预测）时，速度确实更快。例如，在上下文句子“邮递员差点被___咬了”之后，人们对“狗”的反应比对“猪”的反应更快。此外，脑电图（EEG）是一种用于测量大脑电活动的工具，可以检测到人们对不太可能的词语做出反应时出现的惊讶神经特征。

When we listen to speech, we constantly predict what words will come next, and allocate cognitive resources to processing them in advance. This predictive processing is speedy and efficient—it preselects the most likely continuations, so that we do not waste time searching through thousands of possible word representations as the conversation ensues. Once a partner says, “How are,” some resources have already been allocated to “you.” The classic evidence comes from priming studies, in which people are shown to be reliably faster at performing arbitrary tasks such as counting letters or detecting errors in words that are predictable from the preceding context. For example, people are faster at responding to “dog” than “pig” after the context sentence: “The mail carrier was almost bitten by the ___.” Moreover, EEG, a tool for measuring electrical activity in the brain, detects neural signatures of surprise in response to unlikely words.

这些发现也延伸到了音乐中令人意想不到的事件。即使没有接受过正规音乐训练的听众，在既定的音乐环境中不太可能出现的音符和和弦也会引发同样的脑电图特征。同样地，当音符或和弦的音色是什么，以及它是否走调时，如果根据先前的背景可以预测该音符或和弦，那么他们对此类任意问题的反应时间也会更快。

These findings extend to surprising events in music. Even in listeners with no formal musical training, notes and chords that are unlikely within the established musical context elicit these same EEG signatures. Similarly, reaction times to arbitrary questions like what timbre a note or chord is and whether it is in or out of tune are faster when the note or chord is predictable given the preceding context.

但是，音乐序列的可预测性真的就意味着它们具有句法性吗？马里兰大学心理学家 L. Robert Slevc 及其同事通过在人们阅读句子时播放和弦序列来解答这个问题。音乐和语言刺激都表现出某种预测性违规，但这种违规并不总是句法性的。例如，句法音乐违规可能涉及从调外拉出的和弦，但非句法违规可能涉及在小提琴演奏一系列和弦后突然出现长笛演奏的和弦。只有在句法音乐违规与句法语言违规同时发生的情况下，反应时间才会过度减慢，这表明音乐和语言中的句法违规利用了相同的有限神经资源。人们对这些资源究竟是什么存在分歧。相反除了支持句法处理之外，它们还可能支持更一般的过程，例如错误检测或记忆方面。

But does the predictability of musical sequences actually make them syntactic? University of Maryland psychologist L. Robert Slevc and colleagues addressed this question by playing people chord sequences as they read sentences. Both the musical and the linguistic stimuli featured some kind of predictive violation, but the violation was not always syntactic. For example, a syntactic musical violation might involve a chord drawn from outside the key, but a non-syntactic violation could involve the sudden occurrence of a chord played by flutes after a succession of chords played by violins. Only in the cases where syntactic musical violations happened at the same time as syntactic language violations were reaction times excessively slowed, suggesting that syntactic violations in music and language draw on the same finite neural resources. People disagree about exactly what these resources might be. Instead of supporting syntactic processing in particular, they might undergird more general processes such as error detection or aspects of memory.

无论这些认知资源的具体性质如何，对即将发生的音乐事件形成预期的能力，使得独特的表达功能成为可能。人们在聆听音乐时，会发现有些时刻紧张悬而未决，而另一些时刻则平静而充满决心。这些印象会随着音乐的进展而动态波动。在一种研究这些感知的成熟方法中，人们会在音乐播放时实时连续移动滑块，当他们感觉到紧张感增强时，将滑块向前推；当他们感觉到紧张感减弱时，将滑块向后拉。惊喜——音乐做出听众未曾预料到的事情的时刻——往往会引发高度紧张的印象。相反，听众往往会体验到音乐按照预期路径进行时，紧张感减轻、更加放松的时刻。

Regardless of the precise nature of these cognitive resources, the ability to form expectations about impending musical events makes unique expressive functions possible. As people listen to music, they find some moments tense and unresolved and other moments calm and full of resolution. These impressions fluctuate dynamically as the music progresses. In one well-established method for studying these perceptions, people move a slider continuously in real time, as a piece of music plays, pushing it forward as they perceive the tension to build and pulling it back as they perceive the tension to recede. Surprises—moments where the music does something the listener did not predict—tend to elicit impressions of high tension. Conversely, listeners tend to experience moments where the music takes the expected path as less tense and more relaxed.

这种预期参与已被证明能够激活多巴胺系统，该系统是大脑奖赏回路中最容易理解的部分之一。音乐的句法结构与其表达力的主观体验之间的这种联系令人着迷，因为它能够从客观结构特征的角度解释我们难以表达的部分音乐感受。

This anticipatory engagement has been shown to activate the dopamine system, one of the best understood parts of the brain’s reward circuitry. This link between the syntactic structure of music and subjective experiences of its expressivity is tantalizing because it accounts for parts of our difficult-to-articulate musical sensations in terms of objective structural features.

音乐和语言学习

Learning in music and language

在没有明确训练的情况下，人们如何获得音乐语法方面的专业知识？无论是音乐还是语言，接触特定的系统就足以让人们获得对其结构的隐性知识——这些知识可以通过精心设计的实验揭示，但人们可能无法清晰地表达出来。正如出生在北京的婴儿能够掌握中文，出生在巴黎的婴儿能够掌握法语一样，婴儿也可以掌握印度古典音乐的语法，或者西方古典音乐或两者兼而有之，取决于他们接触到什么。

How do people acquire expertise with musical syntax in the absence of explicit training? In both music and language, exposure to a particular system suffices to give people implicit knowledge of its structure—knowledge that cleverly designed experiments can expose, but that people may not be able to articulate. Just as a baby born in Beijing will acquire competence in Chinese but a baby born in Paris will acquire competence in French, babies can acquire the syntax of Indian classical music or Western classical music or both, depending on what they are exposed to.

20世纪60年代，语言学家诺姆·乔姆斯基提出，婴儿不可能如此迅速地学习语言，除非他们拥有一种先天的语言机制，使他们倾向于学习特定的语法和结构关系。20世纪80年代初，作曲家弗雷德·勒达尔和语言学家雷·杰肯多夫将这一理论应用于音乐，认为构成语言结构的层级结构也构成了音乐结构的基础。乔姆斯基的树形结构分析法（其中每个单词都可以被赋予一个角色，以阐明其在句子中的作用）可以与勒达尔和杰肯多夫对乐句的树形结构分析法（其中每个音符都可以被赋予一个角色，以阐明其功能）并列。这两棵树看起来非常相似。

In the 1960s, the linguist Noam Chomsky proposed that infants could not possibly learn language so rapidly unless they possessed an innate language mechanism that predisposed them to learning particular kinds of grammar and structural relations. In the early 1980s, the composer Fred Lerdahl and the linguist Ray Jackendoff adapted this theory to music, arguing that the kinds of hierarchy that underlie linguistic structure also underlie musical structure. Chomsky’s tree structure analyses, in which every word could be assigned a role that clarified its function within the sentence, could be placed side by side with Lerdahl and Jackendoff’s tree structure analyses of musical phrases, in which every note could be assigned a role that clarified its function. The two trees looked remarkably similar.

20世纪90年代，一系列同时使用语音和音乐的研究似乎表明，一种更简单的机制或许促成了这两个领域快速的内隐学习特征。这些研究始于一个基本问题：婴儿是如何学习将语音流分解成单词的？想想听外语的体验。学习过程中最棘手的初始障碍之一，就是弄清楚一个单词在哪里结束，下一个单词在哪里开始。

During the 1990s, a set of studies using both speech and music seemed to suggest that a simpler mechanism might contribute to the rapid implicit learning characteristic of both domains. These studies began with a fundamental question: how do infants learn to segment the speech stream into words? Think about the experience of listening to a foreign language. One of the toughest initial barriers to learning is figuring out where one word stops and the next begins.

为了模拟这种情况，心理学家珍妮·萨弗兰（Jenny Saffran）及其同事给八个月大的婴儿播放了连续的音节串——比如“ba-la-do-ni-sa”——除了音节之间的过渡概率外，没有任何区别。例如，没有停顿，也没有可能表示边界的重音音节。婴儿们并不知道，研究人员已经将语音流构建成由三个音节的伪词（例如“ba-la-do”）组成。定义伪词的唯一因素是一个音节过渡到下一个音节的可能性。在一个伪词中，这个概率是100百分比——“ba”后面总是跟着“la”，而“la”后面总是跟着“do”。但任何伪词都可以跟在任何其他伪词后面，这意味着在一个伪词的最后一个音节之后，过渡到下一个音节的概率并非100%。事实上，伪词“ba-la-do”的最后一个音节“do”和下一个伪词的第一个音节“ni”之间的过渡概率只有33%。除了音节连续概率的这种变化之外，没有任何东西可以区分伪词。婴儿似乎只是听到了一串很长的音节。

To simulate this situation, psychologist Jenny Saffran and colleagues played eight-month-old babies continuous strings of syllables—think “ba-la-do-ni-sa”—with no differentiation except for the transition probabilities between the syllables. There were no pauses, for example, or accented syllables of the sort that might indicate boundaries. Unbeknownst to the babies, the researchers had structured the speech stream so that it was composed of three-syllable pseudowords such as “ba-la-do.” The only thing that defined pseudowords was the likelihood of one syllable to progress to the next. Within a pseudoword, the probability was 100 percent—“ba” was always followed by “la,” which was always followed by “do.” But any pseudoword could follow any other one, meaning that after the last syllable of one pseudoword, the transition probability to the next syllable was not 100 percent. In fact, the transition probability between “do,” the last syllable of the pseudoword “ba-la-do,” and “ni,” the first syllable of the next pseudoword, was only 33 percent. Nothing aside from this change in the probability of syllable succession distinguished pseudowords. It seemed like babies were just hearing a very long string of syllables.

然而，在随后的测试中，婴儿们能够区分构成伪词的三个音节序列和不构成伪词的三个音节序列，这表明他们能够追踪所接触音频的统计特征。显然，婴儿并没有公开地追踪这些统计数据——他们无法告诉研究人员“do”总是跟在“la”后面；相反，他们默默地吸收了这些数据，甚至无需刻意尝试，而成年人也能做到。

Yet in a subsequent test, the infants could distinguish three syllable successions that formed pseudowords from three syllable successions that did not, revealing that they had tracked the statistical characteristics of the audio to which they had been exposed. Clearly, infants did not track these statistics overtly—they could not tell a researcher that “do” followed “la” 100 percent of the time; rather, they absorbed them implicitly, without even trying, a feat adults can perform as well.

使用未分化的音符串而非音节进行的研究表明，音乐学习的原理与之类似。婴儿和成人都能够通过简单的一系列音调，抽象出一个音符跟随另一个音符的概率。这种储存声音事件统计信息的倾向似乎巩固了人们在没有正式指导的情况下，仅通过沉浸式学习就能获得音乐和语言能力的能力。

Research using undifferentiated strings of notes instead of syllables revealed that musical learning works similarly. Both infants and adults were able to abstract the probability for one note to follow another from simple exposure to a series of tones. This propensity to store statistical information about acoustic events seems to undergird the ability of people to acquire competence in music and language simply through immersion, in the absence of formal instruction.

人们最终获得的能力在语言和音乐方面往往有所不同。大多数人能够毫不费力地掌握理解和表达的能力。然而，就音乐而言，大多数人能够掌握聆听和理解的能力，但演奏乐器或唱歌则需要更专业的指导。这种差异可能并非源于语言和音乐之间的本质差异，而是源于文化差异。它们的流行程度和使用情况。虽然大多数婴儿会被邀请与对话伙伴进行主动对话，但在日常生活中，只有少数婴儿会被邀请进行定期的音乐互动。研究人员仍在持续探究音乐创作能力在人群中的分布比语言能力更具差异性的原因，一些人将其归因于文化，另一些人则将其归因于生物学。

The kind of competence people ultimately acquire tends to differ between language and music. Most people effortlessly acquire the ability to both understand and produce speech. In the case of music, however, most people acquire the ability to listen and understand, but require more specialized instruction to play an instrument or sing. This difference may stem not from some essential dissimilarity between language and music, but rather from cultural differences in their prevalence and usage. Whereas most babies are invited into active dialogue with conversation partners, a smaller number are invited into regular musical interactions during daily life. Researchers continue to investigate the reasons that music-making ability is distributed more variably in the population than speaking ability, with some attributing it to culture and others to biology.

音乐意义

Musical meaning

从某种层面上讲，语言是由词汇构成的，这些词汇的含义可以在字典里找到。似乎没有任何同等层次的音乐分析能够提供与这种查字典的类似性。但语言比较的魅力吸引着一些学者尝试寻找。20世纪50年代，音乐学家德里克·库克（Deryck Cooke）将音程（两个音高之间的距离）视为音乐意义的原子层面。他煞费苦心地翻阅声乐乐谱，找出倾向于与每个音程对应的词汇，并认为这些词汇构成了这些乐谱的传统含义。例如，他得出结论，小六度表达的是“在流动的语境中积极的痛苦”。

At one level, language is comprised of words whose meanings are capable of being listed in a dictionary. No comparable level of music analysis seems to provide an analog to this kind of dictionary lookup. But the allure of linguistic comparison has enticed some scholars to try and find one. In the 1950s, musicologist Deryck Cooke pursued the interval—the distance between two pitches—as the atomic level of musical meaning. He painstakingly paged through scores of vocal music, identifying the words that tended to be set to each interval, and argued that these constituted their conventional meanings. He concluded, for example, that the minor sixth expresses “active anguish in the context of flux.”

然而，常识告诉我们，语言语义的概念并不能如此直接地转化为音乐。例如，我体验到的旋律并非是一系列具有特定现实世界意义的音程。然而，清晰的音乐之外的联想确实存在。Stefan Koelsch 用脑电图证明，一段音乐片段可以像一句口语一样轻易地唤起目标词汇的记忆。例如，一首教堂赞美诗可以让听众想象出“虔诚”这个词。

Common sense suggests, however, that the notion of a linguistic semantics does not translate to music so straightforwardly. I do not, for example, experience a melody as a succession of intervals with specific real-world meanings. Yet clear extra-musical associations do exist. Stefan Koelsch used EEG to demonstrate that target words could be brought to mind by a musical excerpt as easily as by a spoken sentence. For example, a church hymn could make a listener imagine the word “devotion.”

阿肯色大学的研究人员给受试者播放了他们从未听过的无歌词管弦乐片段，并要求他们自由地讲述他们在聆听过程中想象的任何故事。这是一项令人震惊的不受约束的任务——研究人员预计答案会大相径庭，而且主观性。相反，在许多选段中，大多数受访者在他们的故事中使用了相同的词语，通常是来自电影联想的词语。例如，在李斯特的一段从未在动画片中使用过的选段之后，大多数人描述了一个故事，其中有乱窜的老鼠、两个互相追逐的角色、一只猫和一只老鼠，或者（最具体的）是汤姆和杰瑞。在18世纪作曲家泰勒曼的一段相对晦涩的选段之后，88%的自由构建的叙事描述使用了这些暗示盛大事件的词语之一：舞厅、舞蹈、庆祝活动、盛大派对或皇室婚礼。

Researchers at the University of Arkansas played people wordless orchestral excerpts they had not heard before and asked them to provide free-response accounts of any story they had imagined while listening. This is an alarmingly unconstrained task—researchers expected responses to be wildly divergent and subjective. Instead, for many of the excerpts, a majority of respondents used the same words in their stories, often words drawn from cinematic associations. For example, after an excerpt by Liszt that itself had never been used in a cartoon, the majority of people described a story featuring scurrying mice, two characters chasing one another, a cat and a mouse, or (most specifically) Tom and Jerry. After a relatively obscure excerpt by eighteenth-century composer Telemann, 88 percent of freely constructed narrative descriptions used one of these words that connote a grand affair: ballroom, dance, celebratory event, fancy party, or royal wedding.

本研究中，反应一致性的范围不仅局限于特定词汇的使用，还涵盖了动词时态等特征。一些片段会引发对正在发生的事件的描述，而另一些则会引发对未来即将发生的事件的描述。令人惊讶的是，通常被认为相对抽象的音乐，却能引发特定文化背景下听众的直接具体联想。广告商可以利用这些关系，既可以尝试将产品与特定的曲调或风格联系起来，也可以尝试唤起广告中未明确表达的联想。

Response agreement in this study extended beyond the specific words used to characteristics like verb tense, with some excerpts eliciting descriptions of events that were already happening, and some eliciting descriptions of events that were about to happen in the future. It is striking that music, typically thought of as relatively abstract, triggers immediate concrete associations to listeners within a particular culture. Advertisers can take advantage of these relationships, both by seeking to align their product with a particular tune or style and by trying to evoke associations not overtly stated within the commercial.

尽管关于音乐能够指涉非音乐实体的新发现层出不穷，但大多数人在提及音乐意义时，想到的并非这些语义关联。他们常常思考的是音乐如何在他们的生活中获得意义，以及音乐为何对他们如此重要。同一首歌，对于听着它结识女友的人和听着它与女友分手的人来说，意义可能截然不同。伦纳德·科恩的《哈利路亚》已被用于数十部电视剧、电影和公共活动，从加拿大官方反对党领袖杰克·林顿的国葬到2016年美国总统大选后《周六夜现场》的首集。一首特定的音乐作品可以承载广泛的情感共鸣，取决于背景和听众的先前经验。

Despite new discoveries about music’s capacity to refer to nonmusical entities, these semantic associations are not what most people think about when they mention musical meaning. Often, they are thinking instead about how music comes to acquire significance in their lives, and why it matters to them. The same song can mean very different things to someone who met his girlfriend while listening to it and someone who broke up with his girlfriend while listening to it. Leonard Cohen’s “Hallelujah” has been used in dozens of television shows and movies, and at public events ranging from the state funeral in Canada of Official Opposition leader Jack Layton to the first episode of Saturday Night Live following the 2016 US presidential election. One particular piece of music can take on a wide range of emotional resonances, depending on the context and the prior experiences of the listener.

音乐之所以能够被理解为一种沟通或表达意义的方式，在于它能够以富有想象力的方式调动运动系统，例如，用适度的节奏激发跑步者的活力，或将听众沉浸在大提琴独奏的哀婉旋律中。聆听音乐并非将一系列声音视为某种超越音乐本身、真实意义的线索，而是常常需要以富有想象力的方式融入声音本身，首先关注的是它们的声音特质，而不是它们所代表的其他概念。人们有时将其描述为一种超越语言、深入体验本身的交流。

One of the ways that music can be understood to communicate or mean something comes from its capacity to imaginatively engage the motor system, energizing a runner with a just-fast-enough beat or sympathetically wrapping the listener into the mournful contours of a solo cello line. Instead of approaching a series of sounds as pointers to some extra-musical, real-word meaning, musical listening often involves imaginatively inhabiting the sounds themselves, and orienting first to their sonic qualities rather than to some other concept for which they stand. People sometimes describe this as a kind of communication that goes beyond words, into the grain of experience itself.

但与语言一样，即使是这种意义也高度依赖于文化。神经科学家 Patrick Wong 及其同事发现，在印度比哈尔邦农村长大、很少接触西方古典音乐的听众和在伊利诺伊州芝加哥长大、很少接触印度古典音乐的听众不仅对来自另一种文化的片段的识别记忆下降，而且对与基本表达参与相关的任务的反应也明显不同 - 例如，他们对来自陌生文化的音乐中紧张感的印象与本地听众不同。在芝加哥由印度父母抚养长大的听众，从小就接触印度和西方古典音乐，他们对这两种风格的反应相似，在记忆表现或感知到的紧张感方面没有区别。各种各样的音乐意义都源于心智和文化之间复杂的相互作用。

But as with language, even this kind of meaning is highly dependent on culture. Neuroscientist Patrick Wong and colleagues found that listeners raised in a rural part of Bihar, India, with little access to Western classical music and listeners raised in Chicago, Illinois, with little access to Indian classical music not only showed decreased recognition memory for excerpts from the other culture, but also responded significantly differently to tasks related to basic expressive engagement—for example, their impressions of tension in music from the unfamiliar culture did not match those of native listeners. Listeners raised in Chicago by Indian parents who had been exposed to both Indian and Western classical music since childhood responded similarly to both styles, not differentiating them in terms of memory performance or perceived tension. Musical meaning of all varieties emerges out of a complex interplay between mind and culture.

音乐与语言的互动

Music-language interactions

有些人在音乐方面有特殊的经验，比如对某种乐器进行了广泛的训练；有些人在语言方面有特殊的经验，比如能流利地说多种语言。鉴于由于处理语音和音乐的认知系统之间存在重叠，因此，在一个领域的经验或天赋会影响另一个领域的能力。早期音乐训练鼓励儿童仔细聆听声音。他们需要仔细聆听、对位音调并重现时间序列。接受早期音乐训练的儿童表现出更精确的频率跟踪反应，这些反应来自脑干中的细胞，这些细胞的作用是将声音信息传递到更高级的处理中心。童年时期学习音乐的成年人即使在停止训练数十年后，仍能继续受益于这些更高保真度的神经反应。

Some people have special experience with music, such as extensive training on an instrument, and some have special experience with language, such as speaking multiple languages fluently. Given the overlaps between the cognitive systems that process speech and music, experience or aptitude in one domain can affect abilities in the other. Early musical training encourages children to attend carefully to sound. They need to listen closely, match pitch, and reproduce temporal sequences. Children with early musical training demonstrate more accurate frequency-following responses from cells in the brainstem whose job it is to relay information about sound to higher processing centers. Adults who studied music during childhood continue to benefit from these higher-fidelity neural responses, even decades after the training has ceased.

脑干音调追踪准确性的提高可能是音乐训练对阅读能力有益的部分原因。由于阅读技能从根本上取决于语音意识——即解析和表达语言组成部分声音的能力——通过音乐训练培养的卓越听觉处理能力可能有助于儿童学习阅读或提高在嘈杂环境中理解语音的能力。然而，关于这一主题的大部分研究都是将恰好接受过音乐训练的儿童与未接受过音乐训练的儿童进行比较，而不是随机将儿童分配到接受或不接受训练的组。如果参加音乐课的儿童一开始就具有更高的听觉处理能力，那么最终的语言能力提升可能源于这种潜在的能力差异，而不是训练本身。

The increased accuracy of pitch tracking in the brainstem likely contributes to some of the benefits musical training has been shown to confer on reading ability. Because reading skills depend fundamentally on phonological awareness—the ability to parse and represent the component sounds of a language—the superior auditory processing developed through musical training might help children learn to read or improve a person’s ability to understand speech presented in a noisy environment. Yet much of the research on this topic compares children who happen to have received musical training with children who have not, rather than randomly assigning children to a group that will or will not receive training. If children who enroll in music lessons tend to have higher aptitude for auditory processing to begin with, eventual linguistic benefits might accrue from this underlying aptitude difference, rather than from the training itself.

音乐训练最重要的组成部分之一是引导注意力适时变化——提前与声音互动，预测某些事件何时发生。例如，在二重奏表演中，学生可能需要仔细聆听才能理解何时入场。练习适时分配注意力或许是音乐训练在其他领域取得成就的关键。一项涉及数十名儿童的研究表明，幼儿园时期的节奏再现能力可以预测孩子未来的阅读能力。二年级。此外，那些能够最成功地与节拍同步的学龄前儿童在一系列阅读前测试中也得分最高。音乐训练甚至与成年人的外语学习成绩优异有关。接受过音乐训练的人在听不熟悉的声调语言时，能够更准确地编码语言音高——例如普通话或泰语，在这些语言中，音高传达的是语义，而不仅仅是语调变化。这些益处也适用于临床人群；音乐训练可以提高患有阅读障碍（如诵读困难）儿童的阅读技能。

One of the most important components of musical training involves guiding attention in time—engaging with sound anticipatorily to predict when certain events will occur. For example, a student might need to listen closely to understand when to enter during a duet performance. Practice with allocating attention in time might underpin some of the benefits musical training can provide on achievement in other domains. A study involving dozens of children demonstrated that the capacity to reproduce rhythms in kindergarten predicted reading ability in second grade. Additionally, preschoolers who could most successfully synchronize with a beat also scored highest on a battery of pre-reading tests. Musical training is even associated with superior foreign-language learning in adults. Individuals who have had musical training encode linguistic pitch more accurately when listening to an unfamiliar tone language—a language such as Mandarin Chinese or Thai where pitch conveys semantic meaning rather than mere inflection. These benefits can also apply to clinical populations; musical training improves skills in children with reading impairments such as dyslexia.

音乐对语言处理的影响不仅源于对音调和节拍的更多参与，也源于对听觉模式的更广泛参与。接受过音乐训练的人在音乐和语言结构方面都表现出更卓越的内隐学习能力。他们的执行功能也普遍得到改善，从听觉注意力、工作记忆到执行控制——即设定和追求目标的能力——这可能会影响他们学习新语言的能力。

Music’s impact on language processing stems not only from increased engagement with pitch and timing, but also from increased engagement with auditory patterns more generally. People with musical training show superior implicit learning of both musical and linguistic structures. They also exhibit general improvements in executive functions ranging from auditory attention and working memory to executive control—the capacity to set and pursue goals—that may influence their capacity to acquire new languages.

音乐能力与语言能力之间的这种关系似乎是双向的。声调语言使用者在各种音乐感知任务（例如音高记忆和旋律辨别）上的表现都比不讲声调语言的人更好。他们追踪音高的能力也更强，双语者（能够流利地使用两种语言的人）也是如此。

This relationship between musical and linguistic ability seems to be bidirectional. Tone-language speakers perform better on a variety of music perception tasks, such as pitch memory and melodic discrimination, than people who do not speak a tone language. They also track musical pitch more effectively, as do bilinguals, people who speak two languages fluently.

言语与音乐之间的界限

The border between speech and music

语音和音乐通常表现出不同的时间特征。语音中的频率随着辅音和元音的相继出现而快速变化。另一方面，音乐表演中的频率变化往往更慢，也更稳定。单个音符会持续一段不连续的时长，然后过渡到下一个音符。此外，音乐语言往往具有一定程度的时间规律性，而说话则不然——通常情况下，跟着歌曲拍手比跟着演讲更容易，也更容易被社会接受。然而，音乐与演讲之间的界限模糊不清，且受文化影响。史蒂夫·莱奇的弦乐四重奏《Different Trains》融合了录音片段，将其潜在的旋律引申出来，并在乐器之间来回传递。说唱艺术家巧妙地利用日常言语中潜藏的韵律和节奏，创作出引人入胜的音乐表演。

Speech and music typically exhibit different timing profiles. The frequencies within speech sounds change rapidly as consonants and vowels succeed one another. The frequencies within musical performances, on the other hand, tend to change more slowly and exhibit more stability. Individual notes are sustained for discrete durations before giving way to the next one. Additionally, music tends to feature a degree of temporal regularity that speaking does not—it is typically much easier, and more socially acceptable, to clap along to a song than to a speech. Yet the border between music and speech is porous and influenced by culture. Steve Reich’s string quartet Different Trains incorporates snippets of recorded speech, coaxing out their underlying melodies and passing them back and forth among the instruments. Rap artists virtuosically exploit the rhyme and rhythm latent within everyday speech to spin compelling musical performances.

4.声谱图是一种表示声音的方式。x 轴表示时间，y 轴表示频率。图像的暗度表示该频率在特定时间的能量。上方的柱状图是一个人唱​​“一闪一闪，小星星”的声谱图。下方的柱状图是同一个人朗读“一闪一闪，小星星”的声谱图。相比朗读版本，演唱版本的频率稳定时间更长。

4. Spectrograms are a way of representing sound. The x-axis represents time. The y-axis represents frequency. The darkness of the image represents the amount of energy present at that frequency at that time. The top bar is a spectrogram of a person singing “Twinkle, Twinkle, Little Star.” The bottom bar is a spectrogram of the same person speaking the words “Twinkle, Twinkle, Little Star.” Frequencies in the sung version are stable for longer periods than in the spoken version.

一些核心的相似之处使得这些界限很容易被模糊。音乐和语音往往由独立的片段（乐句或句子）组成，这些片段逐层聚合，形成更大的结构（章节或段落）。在这些片段的末尾，声音的音调往往会下降并减慢。某些特定的特征，例如速度和音调高度，往往与相似的表达功能相一致，无论它们出现在语音还是音乐中——例如，低沉而缓慢的声音往往被解读为悲伤。

Several core similarities make it easy to blur these boundaries. Both music and speech tend to be comprised of individual segments (phrases or sentences) that aggregate hierarchically into larger structures (sections or paragraphs). At the end of these segments, sounds tend to descend in pitch and slow down. Particular characteristics, such as speed and pitch height, tend to align with similar expressive functions regardless of whether they occur in speech or music—sounds that are low and slow, for example, tend to be interpreted as sad.

心理学家戴安娜·德意志（Diana Deutsch）发现了一种惊人的感知错觉，揭示了语音和音乐之间的界限是多么模糊。首先，人们听一段完整的口语。然后，他们听到这段口语的一段简短片段（例如几个词）重复多次。经过这段重复的聆听后，他们再次聆听完整的原始口语。对于大约85%的人来说，重复的片段现在以一种戏剧性的方式从其余口语中脱颖而出：听起来就像是在唱歌一样。

Psychologist Diana Deutsch discovered a striking perceptual illusion that exposes how thin the border between speech and music really is. First, people listen to a full spoken utterance. Then, they hear a short snippet of this utterance (a few words, for example) repeated a number of times. After this period of repeated exposure, they listen to the complete original utterance again. For about 85 percent of people, the snippet that had been repeated now stands out from the rest of the utterance in a dramatic way: it sounds as if it were being sung.

在语音转歌曲的幻觉中，声音的序列没有任何变化。变化发生在听者的脑海中。经过多次重复后，最初听起来像是在说的同一段话，现在听起来像是在唱歌。在这种情况下，重复发挥了音乐化的作用。而且，重复不仅可以使语音更具音乐性——循环播放也能使随机的音调序列听起来更具音乐性，环境声音的片段也是如此。经过几次体验后，滴水的滴答声或铲子在岩石上拖动的刺耳声音，听起来就像是有目的的音乐行为，带有突出的节奏和音调。

In the speech-to-song illusion, nothing changes about the sequence of sounds. The change occurs in the mind of the listener. After numerous repetitions, the same snippet that had initially sounded like it was being spoken begins to sound like it is being sung. In this scenario, repetition acts as a musicalizing force. And repetition can musicalize more than just speech—looping makes random sequences of tones sound more musical as well, as well as snippets of environmental sound. After a few exposures, the plips and plops of dripping water or the screeches of a shovel being dragged across a rock can come to sound like purposeful musical acts, with foregrounded rhythm and pitch.

音乐结构往往比语言结构包含更多的重复。例如，流行歌曲中的副歌重复多次，却不会对其在排行榜上的地位产生明显的影响。如果你的对话对象重复了类似的内容，然而，频率过高通常会令人不快。重复会激发人们对声音的参与——这是音乐聆听的核心要素，对语言感知而言可能不那么重要。经过多次聆听后，听众知道接下来会发生什么，并能预测甚至跟着唱。这种用声音聆听而非聆听声音的特质，尤其象征着我们对音乐的特殊投入。

Musical structures tend to include much more repetition than linguistic ones. Choruses in pop songs, for example, recur many times without apparent detriment to their position on the charts. If your conversation partner repeated himself with similar frequency, however, it would ordinarily be unpleasant. Repetition encourages a participatory orientation with the sound—a central component of musical attending that may be less critical to language perception. After a number of exposures, a listener knows what is coming next, and can anticipate and even sing along with it. This quality of listening with the sound rather than listening to it is particularly emblematic of the special kind of engagement we bring to music.

听完演讲后，对单个单词的逐字记忆通常很差。相反，对所传达实际内容的记忆往往会提高。口头语言有时仅仅是传达真正感兴趣的对象——语义——的渠道。音乐体验通常无法以这种方式概括——它们各个组成声音的细微差别和质感不能被它们所传达的抽象内容所抛弃。

After listening to a speech, verbatim memory of the individual words used is often quite poor. Instead, gist memory—for the actual content conveyed—tends to be elevated. Spoken words sometimes function as mere conduits for the real object of interest: the semantic meaning. Musical experiences usually are not able to be summarized in this way—the nuances and textures of their individual constituent sounds cannot be discarded in favor of some abstract content they are conveying.

重复可以迫使听众留意他们已经听过的声音的新部分，从而增强他们对声音材料本身的参与度，并相应地增强他们对演讲音乐性的理解。普通演讲可以通过头韵、重复以及特殊的旋律和节奏强调来充分利用这种音乐潜力。这种情况在公开演讲和呼唤式布道中尤为常见。马丁·路德·金的“我有一个梦想”演讲就利用其重复的合唱和强劲的音调，促使听众共同下定决心。这样的演讲可以被认为是运用音乐策略来激发参与感和共同目标。

Repetition can force listeners to attend to new parts of sounds they have already heard, increasing their engagement with the sonic materials themselves and accordingly with the musical aspects of the presentation. Ordinary speech can take advantage of this musical potential with alliteration, repetition, and special melodic and rhythmic emphasis. This happens with special frequency in public oration and call and response preaching. Martin Luther King Jr.’s “I Have a Dream” speech uses its repeated chorus and dynamic swells to urge the audience into shared resolve. Speech like this can be thought of as adopting musical strategies to encourage a sense of participation and shared intent.

第四章

Chapter 4

及时聆听

Listening in time

音乐动态地展开，一个音符接一个音符，一个瞬间接一个瞬间。一场演出不可能一下子就被全部吸收；听众必须运用记忆系统来重建已经发生的事件，感知系统来接收当前正在发生的事件，并运用预测机制来预判接下来会发生什么，从而适应每一个音乐瞬间。所有这些系统都会影响对每个事件发生时间的体验，以及连续的“时间”凝聚成特定时间感知的能力，例如节拍、节奏、开头或结尾。

Music unfolds dynamically, note by note, moment by moment. A performance cannot be taken in all at once; listeners must orient to each passing musical moment using memory systems to reconstruct events that have passed, perceptual systems to take in events that are presently sounding, and predictive mechanisms to anticipate what might happen next. All of these systems affect the experience of when each individual event occurs, and the capacity of successive whens to cohere into particular temporal perceptions, such as a beat, a rhythm, a beginning, or an ending.

感知韵律和节奏

Perceiving meter and rhythm

音乐中最独特的时间体验之一是韵律——在持续的音乐流中，某些时间点被赋予了节拍的特殊地位。充当节拍的时间点以大致相等的时间间隔相继出现。有些节拍感觉强，有些感觉弱，通常以强弱（二拍）或强弱弱（三拍）的模式衔接。

One of the most distinctive temporal experiences in music is meter—the sense that certain time points within the ongoing musical flow acquire special status as beats. Time points that function as beats succeed one another at roughly equal temporal intervals. Some of the beats feel strong and some feel weak, often following one another in a strong-weak (duple) or strong-weak-weak (triple) pattern.

听觉线索会影响哪些时间点充当节拍。例如，一个特别响亮且音调特别低的时刻更有可能充当节拍，尤其是在它之前以固定时间间隔出现的其他时刻重音相似。但单凭声学特征无法解释韵律感知。许多证据表明，人类思维在韵律体验的生成过程中发挥着积极作用。

Auditory cues influence which time points act as beats. For example, a moment that is particularly loud and features an especially low note is likelier to function as a beat, especially if other moments preceding it at regular temporal intervals were similarly accented. But acoustic features alone cannot explain the perception of meter. Many kinds of evidence point to the active role of the human mind in generating metric experience.

首先，即使是完全没有声学差异的声音——例如，提醒驾驶员打开转向灯的滴答声——也会发生感知转变，似乎在强弱节拍之间交替，偶尔会引发驾驶员的头部摆动，暗示驾驶员正在欣赏舞曲，而不仅仅是试图转弯。这种现象被称为主观节奏化，它表明即使在没有引人注目的声音提示的情况下，大脑也能产生节奏。

For one thing, even sounds that possess no acoustic differentiation at all—ticks that inform the driver when she has activated the turn signal, for example—can undergo perceptual transformation and seem to alternate between strong and weak beats, occasionally triggering head bobs that imply the driver is enjoying dance music rather than just trying to make a turn. This phenomenon, termed subjective rhythmization, illustrates the way the mind can generate meter even in the absence of compelling acoustic cues.

另一方面，有些段落的韵律模糊——例如，它们可能被听成二拍子或三拍子。人们可以通过听一段以二拍子或三拍子为特征的乐段，或者仅仅通过预先想象二拍子或三拍子，就能被引导听到重音是每两拍或每三拍子出现一次。换句话说，只要调整心态，人们就能听到不同的重音模式。

For another, some passages are metrically ambiguous—they can be heard as either duple or triple, for example. People can be primed to hear the accents as occurring every two beats or every three by listening to an earlier passage featuring duple or triple meter, or merely by imagining a duple or triple meter in advance. Simply by adjusting their mindset, in other words, people can actually hear different accent patterns.

一旦人们开始感知某个特定的节拍，声音提示就很难干扰其节奏。例如，当某个节拍已经牢固确立时，在正确的位置插入一个停顿，会让人感觉是静音本身被强调了，而不是节拍发生了变化。即使插入一些轻快的、不合拍的重音，也无法使感知到的节拍与这些新的重音保持一致；相反，人们会固执地坚持原来的模式，让新的重音像切分音一样噼啪作响。切分音在当代流行音乐中随处可见，它们是指与基础节拍反相的强调时刻；这种不匹配赋予了它们独特的冲击力和舞蹈性。

Once people start perceiving a particular meter, acoustic cues have a tough time derailing them. When a meter has been strongly established, for example, the insertion of a pause in the right spot will result in the perception that the silence itself is accented rather than that the meter has changed. Even inserting jaunty off-beat accents does not cause the perceived meter to shift into alignment with these new emphases; instead, people stubbornly cling to the original pattern, allowing the new accents to crackle as syncopations. Ubiquitous in contemporary pop music, syncopations are moments of emphasis that proceed out of phase with the underlying beat; this mismatch gives them a particular quality of punchiness and danceability.

事实上，在所有音乐特征中，韵律似乎与身体运动联系最为紧密。神经影像学显示，运动系统的某些部分会被有节奏的音乐激活，但不会被没有节奏的音乐激活。人们对于哪些音乐片段能够激发愉悦的舞动欲望有着广泛的共识。这些被称为“高律动”的音乐片段能够引发自发的节奏运动，并将身体动作与音乐的时间结构更精准地结合起来。

Of all music’s features, in fact, meter seems to be most closely linked with bodily movement. Neuroimaging shows that aspects of the motor system are activated by music with a beat—but not by music without one. People agree widely on which musical excerpts arouse a pleasurable drive to move. These excerpts, termed “high-groove,” elicit spontaneous rhythmic movements as well as more accurate couplings between body movements and the music’s temporal structure.

节拍依赖于层级结构。为了理解这种层级结构，想象一下一群人跟着一首歌拍手。这些拍手声表达了一种特殊的节拍水平，人们最容易与之同步。但如果集中注意力，也许可以每拍两次脚就打一次拍子，或者每拍四次点一次头。这些拍脚和点头代表了节拍层次的更高水平。人们最容易拍手的节拍水平通常每 600 毫秒出现一次。这相当于每分钟 100 次 (bpm)，这是音乐节奏或速度的常用单位。许多乐曲的节奏在 60 到 120 bpm 之间。这个优选的范围与人们通常行走、心跳和哺乳期新生儿的正常吸吮速度相匹配。

Meter relies on hierarchical organization. To get a sense of this hierarchy, imagine a group of people clapping along to a song. These claps articulate a privileged metric level, the one to which people synchronize most easily. But with concentration, it might also be possible to tap your foot every two claps or nod your head every four. These foot taps and head nods represent higher levels of the metric hierarchy. Beats at the level to which people clap most readily tend to occur every 600 milliseconds. This works out to around 100 beats per minute (bpm), the unit by which music’s tempo, or speed, is often measured. Many pieces have a tempo that falls somewhere between 60 and 120 bpm. This preferred range matches the rate at which people typically walk, hearts usually beat, and breastfeeding newborns normally suckle.

人们会预测性地与这些时间组织层面互动，积极地预测未来时间点的事件。当人们被要求跟着节拍器打拍子时，他们的表现相当准确（在更丰富的音乐情境中更是如此），但他们并非在打拍子时精确同步——而是在打拍子之前20到60毫秒。听众会进行预期处理，将注意力提前锁定在他们预期音乐事件发生的时间点。当连续呈现几个时间间隔而不是孤立的时间间隔时，他们能够更准确地捕捉节奏变化并判断持续时间，因为序列使他们能够做出预测。音乐建立的时间模式越清晰，就越容易将该模式投射到未来并形成具体的预期。

People interact with these levels of temporal organization predictively, actively anticipating events at future timepoints. When people are asked to tap along with metronome clicks, they perform quite accurately (even more so in response to richer musical contexts), but they do not synchronize precisely at the clicks—instead, they tap 20 to 60 milliseconds before them. Listeners engage in anticipatory processing, targeting their attention ahead to the points in time at which they expect musical events to occur. They register tempo changes and judge duration more accurately when presented with several temporal intervals in succession rather than one in isolation, because the series enables them to make predictions. The clearer the temporal patterning the music establishes, the easier it is to project that patterning forward and form specific expectations.

最有力的证据是，节拍感知能够将注意力引导至特定时间点，即人们更容易察觉到发生在强拍上的音高变化。据推测，这种感知优势的产生是因为人们会在预期节拍出现之前就将注意力引导到它们身上。反过来，我们可以认为这种预期实际上定义了节拍重音：节拍是人们会将特殊预期焦点分配到的时间点。这种观点对表演者来说具有实际意义——这意味着只要强拍上的音符正确，他们或许能够在复杂的乐段中略作修改。它还具有更深层次的哲学意义，阐明了音乐如何在人群中同步时间定位，从而增强他们在公共音乐会上的凝聚力和交流感。

The strongest evidence for metric perception as a way of directing attention to particular points in time is the discovery that people detect pitch changes more easily when they occur on strong beats. Presumably, this perceptual benefit accrues because people direct attention to anticipated beats before they occur. It is possible to flip this logic around and argue that this anticipation actually defines metric accent: beats are timepoints toward which people allocate special anticipatory focus. This perspective has practical ramifications for performers—it suggests that they might be able to fudge a bit of the passagework in a complicated section so long as they get the notes on the strong beats correct. It also has more philosophical ramifications, illuminating the means through which music might synchronize temporal orientation in large groups of people, contributing to their sense of bonding and communion at public concerts.

感知限制了我们聆听音乐的时间。当音乐事件之间的时间间隔少于 100 毫秒（即它们以每秒超过 10 个音符的速度相继发生）时，它们往往会被感知为单一连续的声音，而不是一系列独立的声音，或者一系列长度和数量不确定的事件。但当事件之间的时间间隔超过 1500 毫秒时，我们很难保持对它们节奏关系的感知——它们听起来更像是缺乏明显节奏联系的孤立事件。因此，许多音乐事件发生在 100 到 1500 毫秒之间的最佳时间点。

Perceptual limits constrain how we hear music in time. When less than 100 milliseconds separate musical events (when they follow one another at a rate faster than 10 notes per second), they tend to be experienced as a single continuous sound rather than a series of individual ones, or as a series of events of uncertain length and number. But when more than 1,500 milliseconds separate events, it becomes difficult to maintain a sense of their rhythmic relationship—they seem more like isolated occurrences lacking a palpable rhythmic connection. Many musical events, accordingly, take place in the sweet spot between 100 and 1,500 milliseconds.

然而，作曲家可以有意地玩弄这些限制。二十世纪艺术家康隆·南卡罗（Conlon Nancarrow）创作了一首名为《卡农X》（Canon X）的自动钢琴曲，其中一个声部以每秒4个音符的合理速度开始，而另一个声部则以每秒39个音符的略微不合理的速度开始。随着乐曲的进行，快速声部逐渐减慢，较慢声部加快，最终达到每秒120个音符的速度——这个速度对于人类的手指来说不可能达到，但对于自动钢琴的机械结构来说却完全没有问题。

Composers can purposefully toy with these limitations, however. Twentieth-century artist Conlon Nancarrow wrote a piece for player piano called Canon X in which one voice starts at the reasonable rate of 4 notes per second and the other starts at the somewhat less reasonable rate of 39 notes per second. Gradually across the course of the piece, the fast voice slows down and the slower voice speeds up, ultimately reaching a speed of 120 notes per second—a speed physically impossible for human fingers to execute but no problem at all for the mechanics of a player piano.

人们通常能清晰地感知到自己正在听的音乐是快是慢。这种毫不费力的感知不仅源于每分钟的节拍数，也源于每拍发生的事件数。现实世界中身体运动的体验也会影响对节奏的判断。儿童比成年人更喜欢快节奏的音乐。而对节奏的偏好会随着成年和老年而逐渐减弱。

People usually have a clear sense of whether the music they are listening to is fast or slow. This effortless perception originates not only from the number of beats occurring per minute, but also from the number of events occurring per beat. Experiences of physical movement in the world also influence tempo judgments. Children prefer faster tempos than adults. Tempo preference slows gradually across adulthood and into old age.

除了对节拍和速度的感知之外，音乐时间最显著的方面是节奏。节奏的定义极其困难，它涉及对音乐事件持续时间（长短）彼此之间以及与它们展开的韵律框架之间关系的感知。事件开始的时间比其他属性（例如事件持续的时间）的时间对节奏的影响更大。对于100到1500毫秒窗口内的事件，连续性（先发生什么，后发生什么）对感知至关重要，事件开始之间的持续时间也同样重要。为了理解这些特征的重要性，想象一下一首熟悉的曲子，比如“生日快乐”。打乱音符的时间顺序会使曲调变得难以辨认。标准化音符开始之间的持续时间也是如此——将节奏打磨得更均匀，使得“你”的音符持续时间不超过“开心”的音符。

Aside from the perception of meter and tempo, the most salient aspect of musical time is rhythm. Notoriously difficult to define, rhythm involves perceptions about how the durations of musical events—short or long—relate to one another and to the metric framework within which they unfold. The timing of event onsets influences rhythm more than the timing of other attributes (how long the events are sustained, for example). For events within the 100 to 1,500 millisecond window, succession—what came before what, and what came after—is critically important to perception, as is the duration between event onsets. To get a sense of the importance of these features, imagine a familiar tune like “Happy Birthday.” Scrambling the temporal order of the notes would make the tune unrecognizable. So would standardizing the duration between note onsets—ironing out the rhythm so that the note for “you” lasted no longer than the notes for “hap-py.”

但决定乐曲节奏感的不仅仅是事件的顺序或事件开始之间的时间间隔。这些时值如何与基础节拍相联系也同样重要。例如，较长的音符通常与强拍对齐，较短的音符与弱拍对齐——逆转这种模式会产生独特的能量。单个音乐事件凝聚成更大的事件组：片段、乐句、乐段和乐曲。这些组不一定整齐地覆盖节拍网格。它们可能从强拍开始，也可能在强拍之前倾斜。它们可能以节拍重音的轰鸣结束，也可能在弱拍上轻轻淡出。事件和组相对于基础节拍的位置使节奏充满活力和生气。

But it is not just the order of events or the temporal interval between event onsets that determines the rhythmic feel of a piece. It is equally important how these durations hang on the underlying meter. For example, longer notes typically align with strong beats and shorter notes with weak ones—reversing this pattern generates a distinctive energy. Individual musical events cohere into larger groups of events: segments and phrases and sections and pieces. These groups do not necessarily neatly overlay the metric grid. They might start on a strong beat, or before it, leaning in. They might end with a bang on a metric accent or fade out gently on a weak beat. Events’ and groups’ position with respect to the underlying meter enlivens and animates rhythm.

旋律和声音的瞬间出现

The temporal emergence of melody and voices

尽管心理学家从语言研究中借鉴了许多理解音乐的模型，但他们仍然依赖于视觉感知的研究来理解群体是如何从一系列音乐事件中涌现出来的。根据20世纪早期的格式塔心理学，当物体彼此靠近、相似或似乎遵循相同的路径时，人们倾向于将它们归为一类。例如，一排被较大间隙隔开的点往往会被感知为两组；一排前半部分为白色，后半部分为黑色的点也往往会被感知为两组。一个充满移动点的视野，其中一半向上移动，一半向下移动，往往会被感知为两个复合单元，一个向上，另一个向下。

Although psychologists have borrowed many of their models for understanding music from the study of language, they rely on work from visual perception to understand how groups emerge out of sequences of musical events. According to early-twentieth-century Gestalt psychology, people tend to group objects together when they are close to one another, when they are similar, or when they seem to follow the same path. For example, a row of dots separated by a large gap tends to be perceived as two groups, and a row of dots where the first half are white and the second half are black also tends to be perceived as two groups. A visual field full of moving dots where half are moving up and half are moving down tends to be perceived as two composite units, one directed upward and the other downward.

这些原理有助于解释更大实体的感知形成，例如由时间上连续出现的单个音符组成的旋律。一系列被静音间隙分隔的音符往往会分为两个不同的部分：停顿前和停顿后。一系列小步向上移动的音符比跳跃式移动的音符更容易被听成一个统一的整体。心理学家阿尔伯特·布雷格曼运用这些见解来帮助解释听觉场景分析的问题：人们如何将他们的声景分解成各个组成部分，如何分辨出房间里水滴声或地板的吱吱声，或者交响乐中的小提琴旋律或打击乐节奏。研究心理声学的机制有助于阐明为什么这个问题首先需要解决。

These principles can help explain the perceptual formation of larger entities such as melodies out of individual notes that occur in temporal succession. A series of notes separated by a silent gap will tend to divide into two distinct segments, pre- and post-pause. A series of notes that moves upward by small steps is easier to hear as a unified entity than one that jumps all over the place. Psychologist Albert Bregman applied these insights to help explain the problem of auditory scene analysis: how people parse their soundscape into its constituent parts, picking out the sound of water dripping or a floorboard creaking in a room, or a violin melody or percussive rhythm within a symphony. Examining the mechanisms of psychoacoustics helps clarify why this problem needed solving in the first place.

声音从一个声源（例如父母的声音或录制的长笛声）通过振动的气柱传入人耳。这些振动代表了空间内所有声源的综合活动。没有单独的气流承载着声音，没有单独的气流承载着长笛声，也没有单独的气流承载着空调的嗡嗡声；所有这些作用都混合在气柱的复合运动中，形成最终到达耳膜。这些膜振动，将能量传递到中耳的微小骨骼，进而在耳蜗（基底膜沿着卷曲的结构伸展）内的液体中产生波。基底膜的不同部分会根据特定频率选择性地振动。这种运动会扰动毛细胞，在听觉神经中产生电活动，并启动信号链，最终导致皮层高级处理中心的活动和声音感知。

Sound is transmitted from an originating source—a parent’s voice or a recorded flute, for example—to human ears via vibrating columns of air. These vibrations represent the combined activity from all the sound sources within a space. There is not a separate stream of air carrying the voice and another carrying the flute and another the hum of the air conditioner; their contributions all mix together in the composite movement of air columns that ultimately reaches the eardrums. These membranes vibrate, transmitting energy to the tiny bones in the middle ear, which, in turn, generate waves in the fluid inside the cochlea—a curled-up structure along which the basilar membrane is stretched. Different portions of this membrane vibrate selectively in response to specific frequencies. This movement perturbs hair cells, generating electrical activity in the auditory nerve and beginning the signaling chain that ultimately leads to activity in higher processing centers in the cortex and perceptions of sound.

因此，进入耳朵的信号由单一波组成，代表了语音、笛声和空调产生的所有频率的总和，但最终的听觉感知包含三个不同的声流。听觉场景分析旨在探究耳朵如何轻松地区分单个声流和缺乏这种区分的物理信号。正如格式塔心理学家用点的图像来说明感知原则对分组的影响一样，布雷格曼用声音录音来说明相似的原则如何影响它们被归类为不同的声流。

The signal that enters the ear, then, consists of a single wave, representing the sum of all the frequencies generated by the voice and the flute and the air conditioner, but the ultimate auditory perception contains three distinct sound streams. Auditory scene analysis tackles the question of how the ear differentiates individual sound streams with seeming effortlessness from a physical signal that lacks this separation. Just as Gestalt psychologists used images of dots to illustrate the influence of perceptual principles on grouping, Bregman used recordings of sounds to demonstrate how similar principles influence their categorization into distinct streams.

例如，布雷格曼证​​明，如果以中等速度演奏，高音和低音之间的交替听起来就像一个声音在来回跳跃，但如果演奏得非常快，就会变成两个不同的声音——一个由高音组成，另一个由低音组成。此外，当所有音符的时值模式听起来都属于一个声音时，由这些音符产生的节奏印象会在它们分成两股流时消失。当声音分离时，人们对高低音连续产生的节奏关系失去敏感性，转而关注每个声音中的节奏关系。改变单个音符的音色——例如，使一些音符听起来更清脆，像管乐器一样，而另一些听起来更刺耳——也会触发感知到分成两股流，每种音色一股。

For example, Bregman showed that an alternation between a high pitch and a low pitch can sound like one voice jumping back and forth if played at a moderate speed, but morphs into two distinct voices—one composed of high notes and the other of low ones—if played very fast. Furthermore, the rhythmic impression generated by a pattern of note durations when they are all heard to belong to a single voice disappears when they separate into two streams. When the voices separate, people lose their sensitivity to the rhythmic relationships generated by the succession of high and low notes and orient instead to the rhythmic relationships within each individual voice. Changing the timbre of individual notes—so that some sound reedier, like a wind instrument, for example, and others brassier—can also trigger perceived separation into two streams, one for each timbre.

5.慢速演奏时，一连串的高低音听起来像一个跳跃的声音，但快速演奏时，它会分成两股流，一股由高音组成，一股由低音组成。

5. When played slowly, a series of high and low pitches sounds like one leaping voice, but when played quickly, it separates into two streams, one made up of high notes and one made up of low notes.

通过大量此类演示，布雷格曼揭示了人类会运用格式塔原则，例如音高或时间上的接近度和音色上的相似度，将听觉场景分析成独立的信息流。他推测，这些用于听觉场景分析的启发式方法——这些在足够长的时间里有效并具有优势的基本规则——源于进化压力；现代人类的祖先必须快速解析声景，才能判断巨大的噪音是否来自捕食者。

Through numerous demonstrations of this sort, Bregman revealed that people use Gestalt principles such as proximity (in pitch or in time) and similarity (of timbre, for example) to analyze the auditory scene into individual streams. He theorized that these heuristics—basic rules that work enough of the time to be advantageous—for auditory scene analysis arose out of evolutionary pressure; ancestors of modern-day humans would have had to quickly parse a soundscape to determine whether a loud noise came from a predator.

早在科学家研究这些感知壮举背后的机制之前，作曲家们就利用它们创作音乐。十八世纪早期的作曲家，如巴赫、亨德尔和维瓦尔第，追求巴洛克式的美学理想，力求在作品中展现令人眼花缭乱的精湛技艺。对于小提琴等通常一次只能演奏一个旋律的独奏乐器来说，华丽的装饰似乎有限。但这些作曲家巧妙地运用了听觉场景的特性。分析，使多个声部听起来像是从同一件乐器中旋转而出。例如，他们会在快速乐段中插入单独的高音，而原本这些高音会占据中音区。高音并非与其他音符紧密相连，而是倾向于聚集在一起，听起来像第二个声部，与第一个声部形成对位。巴赫《B小调小提琴帕蒂塔》（BWV 1002）中阿勒曼德舞曲的开头很好地展示了这种技巧。

Long before scientists studied the processes that make these perceptual feats possible, composers exploited them to create music. Early-eighteenth-century composers such as Bach, Handel, and Vivaldi pursued Baroque aesthetic ideals by striving for dazzling virtuosity in their work. In works for solo instruments like the violin that can ordinarily play only one melody at a time, the potential for ornate filigree might seem limited. But these composers brilliantly manipulated properties of auditory scene analysis to make it seem as though multiple voices were swirling out of a single instrument. For example, they would insert isolated high notes into a fast passage that otherwise occupied a middle register. Rather than adhere to the rest of the notes, the high ones tended to group together and be heard as a second voice sounding in counterpoint to the first. The beginning of the Allemande from Bach’s Violin Partita in B Minor, BWV 1002 serves as a good demonstration of this technique.

东非木琴音乐通过在二重奏中巧妙地控制高低音的顺序，也达到了同样令人印象深刻的效果。由于这些音符在连贯和分离之间来回切换，形成不同的音流，两位演奏者分别演奏简单的节奏，却能营造出错综复杂的节奏感。

East African xylophone music accomplishes a similarly impressive effect by manipulating the order of high and low pitches in duet performances. Because of how these notes move back and forth between cohering and decoupling into separate streams, two performers playing individually simple rhythms can generate an impression of intricate rhythmic complexity.

与节拍一样，音乐的分组也发生在多个层级上。几个音符可能组成一个独特的音段；几个小节组成一个乐句；几个乐句组成一个乐段；等等。人们感知这些分组的能力因其所依赖的记忆系统而异。由于听觉记忆的持续时间不会超过五秒，因此很难直接体验超出这个时间尺度的节奏关系。更大规模的时间关系——例如曲式——往往以一种感知性更低、认知性更强的方式被感知。

Like meter, musical grouping occurs at many hierarchic levels. A few notes might group into a distinct segment; a few measures into a phrase; a few phrases into a section; and so forth. People’s capacity to perceptually apprehend these groups varies according to the memory system they depend on. Because auditory sensory memory does not extend past about five seconds, it is difficult to directly experience rhythmic relationships that extend beyond this timescale. Larger-scale temporal relationships—such as form—tend to be perceived in a less sensory, more cognitive way.

为了说明这种区别，不妨想象一下你最喜欢的歌曲中副歌部分（那个反复出现的朗朗上口的段落）的节奏与副歌部分重复出现的节奏之间的区别。副歌部分不超过五秒，由一系列长短不一的事件组成，它们的节奏关系似乎更多地是被感知而不是被思考。而歌曲的形式，跨越三分钟左右，可能是由主歌和副歌交替构成。虽然我们有可能回想一首歌，并感受到它们的时间关系。在合唱部分和其周围素材的出现之间，各部分的持续时间关系不太容易通过感官获得，而更多地依赖于外显记忆、认知和听觉想象（回想并尝试重新听取之前听到的内容）。

To illustrate this distinction, think about the difference between the way you hear the rhythm in the hook of your favorite song—that catchy bit that recurs in multiple places—and the way you hear the rhythm of the chorus’s reappearances. The hook, no more than five seconds long, is made up of a succession of short and long events whose rhythmic relationships seem as though they are felt more than thought about. The form of the song, on the other hand, spanning more like three minutes, might be composed of verses alternating with choruses. Although it is possible to think back over a song and have a sense of the temporal relationship between occurrences of the chorus and the material surrounding it, the durational relationships of sections are less sensorially available and more reliant on explicit memory, cognition, and auditory imagination (thinking back on and trying to rehear something you heard earlier).

乐曲开头发生的音乐事件在多大程度上影响听众对乐曲结尾的体验，这一直存在争议。一方面，听过两遍古典乐曲后，无论是否受过音乐训练，都能粗略地辨别出各个片段是来自开头、中间还是结尾。另一方面，听过贝多芬奏鸣曲后，大学音乐系的学生无法回忆起乐曲的呈示部（第一主要部分）是否重复过。他们根本不知道自己是否把整个部分听过一遍还是两遍。此外，当奏鸣曲在最后两个和弦结束前停顿时，学生们预测它会继续一两分钟。由于缺乏标志性的双和弦结尾模式，时间比例或形式都无法表明乐曲已经到达了尾声。音乐系的学生学习了大量关于奏鸣曲式的明确知识——这种曲子中通常会发生的具体事件顺序——这些知识可能让他们意识到乐章即将结束，但他们似乎无法将这些概念知识与他们聆听音乐的感官体验结合起来。

The extent to which musical events that occur at the beginning of a piece influence the way listeners experience musical events near the end is a matter of some controversy. On the one hand, after listening twice to pieces of classical music, people with and without musical training were able to roughly identify whether individual segments had come from the beginning, the middle, or the end. On the other hand, after listening to a Beethoven sonata, university music students were unable to recall whether the exposition (the first major section) of the piece had been repeated or not. They simply did not know whether they had heard that entire section once or twice. Moreover, when the sonata was paused before the final two concluding chords, students predicted that it would continue another minute or two. In the absence of the signature two-chord ending formula, nothing about temporal proportion or form signified the piece had arrived at its final moments. Music students learn lots of explicit knowledge about sonata form—the specific sequence of events that typically happen in this sort of piece—that might have clued them in to the fact that the movement’s end was imminent, but they seemed unable to integrate this conceptual knowledge with their sensory experience of listening to the music.

类似这样的发现促使哲学家杰罗德·莱文森提出，音乐依赖于当下专注的注意力——即对刚刚发生的音符如何引导即将发生的音符的感觉——而非对更大规模形式的任何明确意识。尽管这种观点可能夸大了小尺度的重要性而非大尺度的重要性，但它对强调高层次结构的音乐理论传统提供了有益的纠正，这种传统有时甚至忽略了能够吸引和感染众多听众的瞬间活力。从心理学的角度来看从这个角度来看，它表明，随着音乐的进展，思考概念知识与实时聆听行为之间的关系是进一步研究的重要课题。

Findings like these led philosopher Jerrold Levinson to argue that music depends on present-focused attention—the sense of how the notes that just happened are leading into the notes about to happen—rather than any explicit awareness of larger-scale form. Although this position probably overstates the importance of the small over the large timescale, it offers a useful corrective to music-theoretic traditions that emphasize high-level structure, sometimes to the exclusion of the momentary dynamism that grips and compels so many listeners. From a psychological perspective, it suggests that thinking about the way conceptual knowledge relates to the real-time act of listening, as the music progresses, is an important topic for further study.

如果说关于音乐时间感知的概念在最高层次上变得模糊不清，那么在最低层次上也是如此。虽然任何学过西方式节奏符号的人都知道二分音符的持续时间是四分音符的两倍，但除了计算机之外没有人真正以这种方式演奏它们。人类表演者使用富有表现力的节拍，将音符缩短或延长几十毫秒以达到表现效果。即使被要求直接演奏，完全不带任何表现力的变调，表演者也无法达到乐谱所暗示的精确整数比。听众能够察觉到20到50毫秒左右的表现力变化，这种微小的节拍细微差别，可以决定一场表演是让观众热泪盈眶，还是让他们无动于衷。

If ideas about the perception of musical time get murky at the highest levels, they do the same at the lowest levels. Although anyone who has learned about Western-style rhythmic notation knows that a half note lasts twice as long as a quarter note, no one aside from a computer actually plays them that way. Human performers use expressive timing, shortening or lengthening notes by tens of milliseconds for expressive effect. Even when asked to play straight, with no expressive inflection at all, performers do not achieve the exact whole-number ratios implied by music notation. Listeners are able to detect expressive alterations on the order of 20 to 50 milliseconds, and microtiming nuances of this magnitude can make the difference between a performance that brings its audience to tears and one that leaves them unmoved.

两个音符之间的实际时长关系是连续的——一个音符可能比下一个音符稍长，或者稍微长一点，等等。超过 20 到 50 毫秒的阈值，听众可以听出这些关系是富有表现力的细微差别。但是当听到节奏关系时，分类感知就会介入，将关系捕捉到我们熟悉的小整数比率箱中：例如 1 比 2 或 1 比 3。两个音符之间所有可能的时长关系往往被认为是这些小整数比率的更准确或更不准确的再现。当一个音符的持续时间是后续音符的 2.2 倍时，这感觉就像是表现力拉长的 2:1 比率，而不是精确的 2.2:1 比率。当要求听众拍手说出他们刚刚听到的时长时，他们往往会将其校正回这些感知到的小整数类别。

The actual relationships between two durations are continuous—one can be slightly longer than the next, or slightly slightly longer, and so forth. Past the 20- to 50-millisecond floor, listeners can hear these relationships as expressive nuance. But when it comes to hearing rhythmic relationships, categorical perception intervenes to snap relationships into familiar small-integer ratio bins: 1 to 2, or 1 to 3, for example. All the myriad possible durational relationships between two notes tend to be perceived as more accurate or less accurate renditions of these small integer ratios. When an initial note lasts 2.2 times as long as a subsequent one, that feels like an expressively stretched 2:1 ratio rather than a precise 2.2:1 ratio. When listeners are asked to clap the durations they have just heard, they tend to correct them back toward these perceived small integer categories.

早期接触的声音环境——我们儿时听的音乐——很可能催生了这些明确的类别。用语言学的类比来说，对于接触英语的婴儿来说，“r”音和“l”音会分成两个不同的类别，但对于接触日语的婴儿来说，它们会合并成一个类别，其中不存在单独的“r”和“l”音素。同样，西方音乐中大量使用小整数时值比（例如，一个音符的长度是另一个音符的两倍或三倍），这很可能导致了我们倾向于将复杂的节奏听成这些简单类别的不同实例。

Early exposure to the acoustic environment—the music we listen to as children—likely gives rise to these defined categories. To invoke a linguistic parallel, the continuum between the “r” sound and the “l” sound divides into two separate categories for babies exposed to English, but merges into a single category for babies exposed to Japanese, in which separate “r” and “l” phonemes do not exist. Similarly, the fact that so much Western music uses small-integer duration rations (with one note twice or three times as long as another, for example) likely drives our tendency to hear complex rhythms as varied instances of these simple categories.

节奏模式本身蕴含着它们所起源的更广泛的声音文化的痕迹。有些语言，例如英语，是重音节制的，导致单个音节的时长变化很大。其他语言，例如法语，是音节节制的，导致音节时长的顺序更为均匀。事实证明，英国和法国的音乐主题都带有其创作语言环境的痕迹：英语主题在连续音符之间包含更多的时长变化，而法语主题的时长则更为均匀。

Rhythmic patterns themselves contain the traces of the broader sonic culture out of which they emerge. Some languages, like English, are stress-timed, resulting in a highly variable succession of durations of individual syllables. Other languages, such as French, are syllable-timed, resulting in a more uniform succession of syllable durations. Musical themes from England and France, it turns out, bear the marks of the linguistic environment in which they were composed: English themes contain more durational variability between successive notes, but durations in French themes are more uniform.

聆听音乐时的动作和感知

Action and perception in music listening

人们不仅通过敲击研究来研究人类动作与音乐同步的方式，还利用动作捕捉技术来追踪更复杂的音乐引发的动作模式，包括舞蹈。这些研究表明，节奏层次的不同层级通常反映在身体不同部位的同时运动模式中：更深的层级涉及躯干运动所表达的节拍间隔时间更长，而更表层的层级涉及肢体运动所表达的节拍间隔时间更短。然而，这些节奏层次的可察觉性并不相同；脑电图研究表明，即使听众没有注意音乐，他们也能捕捉到节奏和基本的节拍感，但欣赏节奏层次的更深层级需要持续的注意力。表达这些更深层级的动作可能会将注意力吸引到定义它们的音乐部分。事实上，针对我们当中最年轻的人的研究表明，运动模式可以影响听觉感知。

The way human movements synchronize with music has been studied not only using tapping studies, but also using motion capture technology that can track more complex patterns of music-invoked movement, including dance. These studies reveal that different levels in the metric hierarchy are often reflected by simultaneous movement patterns in different parts of the body, with deeper levels involving more time between beats articulated by torso movements, and more surface levels involving less time between beats articulated by limb movements. Yet these metric levels are not equally noticeable; EEG studies suggest that listeners register rhythm and a basic sense of the beat even when they are not paying attention to the music, but that appreciating deeper levels of the metric hierarchy requires sustained attention. Movements that articulate these deeper levels likely draw attention to the parts of the music that define them. Indeed, studies with the very youngest among us show that movement patterns can influence auditory perception.

杰西卡·菲利普斯-西尔弗和劳雷尔·特雷纳给七个月大的婴儿播放了一种模糊的节奏，这种节奏可以用二拍子（每两拍重音）或三拍子（每三拍重音）来听。他们重复这个节奏两分钟，同时每两拍或每三拍摇晃婴儿一次。所有的婴儿都听到了相同的听觉节奏，但他们体验到的动觉重音是通过运动而不是通过声音来暗示二拍子或三拍子的。后来，婴儿表现出对新版本的节奏的偏好，其听觉重音与之前由动作建立的模式相匹配——每两拍摇晃一次的婴儿更喜欢每两拍重音一次的节奏，而每三拍摇晃一次的婴儿更喜欢每三拍重音一次的节奏。他们似乎很轻松地将有关运动时间模式的信息转化为有关音乐时间模式的信息。后续研究表明，成年人在聆听模糊节奏时弯曲膝盖，当新的听觉重音与运动所建立的节拍相匹配时，他们会识别出新的版本与他们之前听到的节奏更相似。运动系统和听觉系统之间的紧密联系始于发育早期，并持续一生。

Jessica Phillips-Silver and Laurel Trainor played seven-month-old infants an ambiguous rhythm that could be heard in duple meter (with accents every two beats) or in triple meter (with accents every three beats). They repeated this rhythm for two minutes while either bouncing the baby every two beats or every three beats. All the babies heard the same auditory rhythm, but they experienced kinesthetic accents implying a duple or triple meter through movement instead of through sound. Later, the babies showed a preference for a new version of the rhythm with auditory accents that matched the pattern previously established by the movements—the babies who had been bounced every two beats preferred the version with auditory accents every two beats, and the babies who had been bounced every three beats preferred the one with accents every three beats. With apparent ease, they had translated information about timing patterns in movement into information about timing patterns in music. Subsequent work showed that adults who bent their knees while listening to the ambiguous rhythm later identified a new version as more similar to the rhythm they had previously heard when the new auditory accents matched the timing established by the movement. Tight links between the motor and auditory systems start early in development and persist throughout the lifespan.

节奏会激活一系列大脑区域，这些区域传统上被认为是运动区域：辅助运动区、运动前皮质、小脑和基底神经节。关于这些区域在聆听音乐时如何相互沟通的研究表明，节拍（即节拍的存在）能够增强听觉区域和运动区域之间的连接。然而，仅仅看到节拍——例如闪光——并不能引发如此快速、准确的运动系统映射。事实上，与声音呈现的节奏相比，人们对视觉呈现的节奏的点击准确度较低。

Rhythm activates a host of brain regions traditionally characterized as motor regions: the supplementary motor area, premotor cortex, cerebellum, and the basal ganglia. Studies of how these regions communicate with each other during music listening demonstrate that meter—the presence of a beat—enhances connectivity between auditory and motor areas. Simply seeing a beat, however—for example, a flashing light—does not elicit such swift, accurate mappings to the motor system. Indeed, people tap less accurately to rhythms presented in the visual domain compared to rhythms presented in sound.

世界各地的音乐体验大多是主动参与式的，即使在西方古典音乐等传统音乐中，人们通常要求安静聆听，聆听音乐也能引发深刻的想象运动体验。这种同步的感觉运动参与在音乐的社会意义中扮演着至关重要的角色，它劫持了与他人同步运动的一些强大后果。例如，约会时人们之间动作的同步程度可以预测他们对约会后夜晚的评价。那些参与唱歌、敲击或行走等同步行为而非不同步行为的成年人，在约会后更有可能相互合作，并认为他们的同伴更讨人喜欢。在实验室环境中，如果人们与伴侣同步唱歌或敲击，而不是彼此不同步，他们会更好地合作，并报告更喜欢他们。14个月大的幼儿在与实验者同步弹跳后，更有可能无私地帮助实验者，而不是不同步弹跳。

Much musical experience throughout the world is active and participatory, but even in traditions like Western classical music where conventions mandate quiet listening, hearing music can elicit profound experiences of imagined movement. This synchronized sensorimotor attending plays a crucial role in music’s social importance, hijacking some of the powerful consequences of moving in time with other people. The degree of synchrony in movements between people on a date, for instance, can predict how positively they will rate the evening afterward. Adults who engage in synchronized behavior such as singing, tapping, or walking rather than an unsynchronized behavior are more likely to cooperate with each other afterward, and to rate their companions as more likable. In laboratory settings, people cooperate better with partners and report liking them more if they sing or tap in synchrony rather than out of phase with each other. Toddlers as young as fourteen months are likelier to altruistically assist an experimenter after they have been bounced in synchrony with her, compared to if they have been bounced out of synchrony.

音乐节拍提供了一个框架，不仅可以与单个伴侣同步时间定位，还可以与一大群人同步。音乐能够培养与陌生人深度同步的感觉，这可以成为其愉悦感的重要来源。同步时间定位所产生的社会联系也被认为是音乐成为治疗工具的要素之一，甚至是推动人类音乐能力进化的益处之一。许多宗教利用音乐的力量来创造这些强大的状态，有些宗教将这种体验延伸到恍惚状态和其他各种扩展意识状态。音乐节拍以无数种或明或暗的方式源于社会体验，并反过来构建了新的社会理解。

Musical meter provides a scaffold for synchronizing orientation in time not just with a single partner, but also with large groups of people. Music’s capacity to foster a sense of deep synchronization with strangers can serve as an important source of its pleasure. The social bonding that arises out of synchronized temporal orientation has also been cited as one of the elements that makes music useful as a therapeutic tool, and even as one of the benefits that drove the evolution of the human capacity for music. Many religions harness the power of music to create these powerful states, some extending the experience to trancing and other varieties of extended consciousness. Musical timing, in myriad overt and subtle ways, arises out of social experiences and, in turn, constructs new kinds of social understanding.

第五章

Chapter 5

音乐表演心理学

The psychology of music performance

在当代西方音乐文化中，表演者占据着特殊的地位。流行乐迷高呼他们最爱的歌手，而不是他们最爱的词曲作者。专业管弦乐队往往年复一年地演奏相同的核心曲目，他们通过突出明星客座表演者来推销自己的作品。一位吉他手可以演奏出与另一位让观众感到无聊的相同音符，但他却能让观众起立鼓掌。音乐表演心理学试图理解这种表现力。由于两个人演奏相同的音符可能会产生截然不同的反应，因此，乐谱显然无法捕捉音乐交流中一些最关键的维度。这些维度是什么？如何才能获得顶级表演者所拥有的那种驾驭这些维度的专业知识？听众是如何感知和回应这些维度的？

Performers occupy a special role within contemporary Western musical culture. Pop fans shout the name of their favorite singer, not their favorite songwriter. Professional orchestras, which tend to program the same core repertoire year after year, market their offerings by highlighting star guest performers. One guitarist can play the same notes as another who left the audience bored, but instead bring them to their feet. The psychology of music performance tries to understand this expressive power. Since two individuals can produce markedly different responses by playing the same notes, it is clear that notation fails to capture some of the most critical dimensions of musical communication. What are these dimensions? What does it take to acquire the kind of expertise in manipulating them that top-notch performers possess? How do listeners perceive and respond to them?

表演表现力

Expressivity in performance

演奏者可以操控的维度包括：时间——拉伸一些音符，压缩其他音符，抵抗乐谱所暗示的音符之间的精确整数比；力度——使一些音符更响亮，而另一些音符更柔和，这种变化比强音（响亮）或弱音（柔和）等力度标记所暗示的更微妙、更连续；清晰度——改变起音和单个音符的衰减，一些音符同时开始，但其他音符则慢慢进入，一些音符突然终止，但其他音符逐渐消失；速度——演奏一段曲子或一段音乐时速度更快或更慢；语调——在保持在标记音高的一般类别内的情况下，巧妙地提高或降低音高（例如，演奏稍微升或降的 C），或滑入或滑出一个音符；音色——演奏得更明亮或更暗淡，或以其他方式改变音符或乐段的音质。

The dimensions available for performers to manipulate include timing—stretching some notes and compressing others, resisting the precise integer ratios between durations implied by notation; dynamics—making some notes louder and others softer in more subtle, continuous increments than dynamic markings like forte (loud) or piano (soft) imply; articulation—altering the attack and the decay of individual notes, starting some all at once, but easing into others, and terminating some suddenly, but letting others fade out; tempo—performing a piece or a section faster or slower; intonation—subtly raising or lowering the pitch while remaining within the general category of the notated pitch (e.g., playing a slightly sharper or flatter C), or gliding into or away from a note; and timbre—playing more brightly or darkly or otherwise changing the sound quality of a note or passage.

其中一些变化似乎以一种系统性、近乎规则的方式发生在音乐结构的特定时刻。例如，世界各地的表演者通常会在乐句边界处放慢速度，其速度与边界的层级意义成正比（如果是一段乐段的结束，速度会慢一些；如果是整首乐曲的结束，速度会慢一些）。这种做法在对话中也体现了类似的趋势。人们倾向于在话语结束时放慢速度，其速度与边界的层级意义成正比（如果是某个想法的结束，速度会慢一些；如果是就某个特定话题进行长时间交流的结束，速度会慢一些）。这些表演倾向会对感知产生影响：在乐句的不同时刻插入相同的减速模式，在大多数地方可能都很明显，但在乐句边界处却无法察觉。表演者如此规律地在那里放慢速度，使得这种模式几乎难以察觉。

Some of these alterations seem to occur in a systematic, almost rule-based fashion at particular moments in the musical structure. For example, it is common for performers around the world to slow down at phrase boundaries, in proportion to the hierarchical significance of the boundary (less if it ends a section and more if it ends an entire piece). This practice mirrors a parallel tendency in conversation. People tend to slow down at the end of utterances, in proportion to the hierarchical significance of the boundary (less if it ends an individual thought and more if it ends a prolonged exchange on a particular topic). These performance tendencies have perceptual ramifications: the same pattern of deceleration, inserted at different moments within a musical phrase, might be quite noticeable in most places, but undetectable at a phrase boundary. The fact that performers slow down there so regularly renders the pattern almost imperceptible.

类似的基于规则的变化也会随着节拍结构的变化而发生。演奏者在音符落在强拍上时，往往会将音符演奏得更响亮一些，并延长一些时间。基于规则的变化也会随着音乐的调性结构而发生——即各个音高如何根据一个主导的中心音高或主音进行组织。当一个音高表现为一个不稳定音符，即将转变为一个更高音高时，演奏者往往会提高它——演奏得略微尖锐；而当一个音高表现为一个不稳定音符，即将转变为一个更低音高时，演奏者往往会降低它——演奏得略微低沉。其他富有表现力的音调变化标志着分组的界限。演奏者经常改变音调的动态或新乐段开头的音色，进一步勾勒出边界。它们往往会延迟新乐段中第一个音符的开始，实际上拉长了前一组乐段的结束与新一组乐段的开始之间的间隔。

Similar sorts of rule-based changes occur in response to metric structure. Performers tend to play notes a little bit louder and sustain them a little bit longer when they fall on strong beats. Rule-based changes also occur in response to the tonal structure of the music—the way that individual pitches are organized in response to a governing central pitch, or tonic. Performers tend to raise a pitch—play it slightly sharp—when it functions as an unstable note about to resolve to a higher pitch, but they tend to lower it—play it slightly flat—when it functions as an unstable note about to resolve to a lower one. Other expressive inflections mark grouping boundaries. Performers often alter the dynamics or timbre at the start of a new section, further delineating the boundary. They tend to delay the onset of the first note in the new section too, in effect lengthening the gap between the end of the previous group and the start of the new one.

这些规则可以应用于计算机系统，使机械演奏的音乐听起来不那么令人反感。然而，尽管机器已经能够击败世界上最优秀的国际象棋选手，但要掌握人类在大提琴上的表达，却显得更加困难。尽管20世纪中期人们开始投资计算机音乐技术，旨在防止人类演奏者即将被淘汰，但至今仍未出现“深蓝”计算机能够与马友友相提并论。

These rules can be implemented in computer systems to help mechanical performances of music sound less repellently inhuman. But although machines have been able to dispatch the greatest chess players in the world, mastering human expression on the cello, for instance, has proven more elusive. Despite mid-twentieth-century investments in computer music technology intended to preempt the imminent obsolescence of human performers, there is still no Deep Blue equivalent of Yo-Yo Ma.

从某种程度上来说，这反映了大量的表现力变化，而这些变化并非直接归因于基于规则的对音乐结构的反应。毕竟，如果能够输入某种音乐结构并炮制出理想的演奏，那么世界各地活跃而多元的专业大提琴家群体就不再需要了。我们可以直接给马友友或他的电脑替身演奏一段音乐，然后录制下来。但人们渴望同一曲目听到各种不同的演奏——今天欣赏马友友演奏的巴赫大提琴组曲，明天又由艾丽莎·韦勒斯坦或帕布罗·卡萨尔斯演奏。

In some ways, this reflects the amount of expressive variation that is not straightforwardly attributable to rule-based responses to musical structure. After all, if it were possible to feed in a musical structure and churn out the ideal performance, there would be no need for the lively and diverse community of professional cellists the world over. We could just give Yo-Yo Ma, or his computer stand-in, a piece of music and record the performance. But people crave a variety of different performances of the same repertoire—enjoying a Bach Cello Suite played by Ma one day but performed by Alisa Weilerstein or Pablo Casals on another.

心理学家布鲁诺·雷普 (Bruno Repp) 试图测量不同演奏者所运用的表达性音调变化。他比较了 24 位享有国际声誉的专业钢琴家和 10 位尚未进入国际舞台的学生钢琴家对同一首钢琴曲的演奏。学生在节拍和力度变化上的改变比专业钢琴家的改变更为相似。当将所有表演的节拍和力度变化平均以得出一个假设的典型表演时，最受赞誉的钢琴巨星所运用的表达性变化实际上往往是与此平均值最显著的差异在于。经济因素可能是导致学生表演趋同和专业表演多变的一个驱动因素。学生试图证明自己能够熟练地演绎传统曲目，从而被认可为专业人士，而专业人士则试图在演奏相同曲目的众多专业人士中脱颖而出。一种不那么愤世嫉俗的解释认为，知名艺术家之所以出名，正是因为他们运用了不为人知的音乐结构层次和不为人知的音乐传播渠道。

Psychologist Bruno Repp sought to measure the expressive inflections made by different performers. He compared performances of the same piano piece by twenty-four professional pianists with international reputations, and ten student pianists who had not yet broken into the international performance circuit. The students’ alterations in timing and dynamics were much more similar to each other’s than were the alterations made by the professionals. When timing and dynamic variation across all the performances were averaged to generate a hypothetical typical performance, the expressive modifications by the most acclaimed superstars of the piano were, in fact, often the ones most pronouncedly different from this average. One possible engine driving conformity in student performances and variability in professional performances is economic. Students try to prove they can execute conventional interpretations skillfully enough to be accepted as a professional, and professionals try to individuate themselves from phalanxes of other professionals playing the same repertoire. A less cynical explanation holds that renowned artists are renowned precisely because they tap into non-obvious levels of musical structure and non-obvious channels of musical communication.

后续研究考察了听众对表演的偏好，结果表明，这些偏好差异中只有一小部分（低至10%）可以归因于表达节奏和力度的差异。这是一个至关重要的见解，因为它表明音乐表演心理学研究中测量的维度可能并不正确。一个简单的思维实验可以强化这一假设。想象一下，一位著名的女中音歌唱家演唱一个音符，或者一位著名的小提琴家用斯特拉迪瓦里小提琴演奏一个音符。这个音符不足以引发通常被认为是审美反应基础的节奏和力度模式，但却能呈现出扣人心弦的表现力。

Follow-up work examining listener preferences for performances suggested that only a small part—as small as 10 percent—of the variance in these preferences could be attributed to differences in expressive timing and dynamics.
