This is a critical insight, because it suggests that the dimensions being measured in research on the psychology of music performance might not be the right ones. A simple thought experiment reinforces this supposition. Imagine a single note sung by an acclaimed mezzo-soprano or played on a Stradivarius by a renowned violinist. This single note, insufficient to give rise to the patterns of timing and dynamics typically thought to underlie aesthetic response, can seem grippingly expressive.

声音信号中其他更难测量的部分，例如音色（即演奏者从乐器中演奏出的独特声音品质），其作用可能比当前研究表明的更大。为了更好地理解“音色”一词所指的声音方面，想象一下如果汤姆·韦茨和布莱恩·威尔逊唱相同的音调，听起来会有多么不同；韦茨的声音听起来沙哑而喉音，而威尔逊的声音听起来圆润纯净。演奏者可以使用不同的技巧从他们的乐器中演奏出更像韦茨或威尔逊的音色。音色操控的强大效果代表了实际音乐实践对人类交流提出的众多问题之一，这些问题目前尚无法用科学来解答。

Other, more difficult-to-measure parts of the acoustic signal, like timbre—the distinct sound quality an individual performer can draw out of an instrument—likely play a bigger role than current research suggests. To get a better sense of what aspects of sound the term “timbre” refers to, think of how different it would sound if Tom Waits and Brian Wilson sang the same pitch; Waits’s voice sounds gravelly and guttural, but Wilson’s sounds round and pure. Performers can use different techniques to draw out a timbre that is more Waits- or Wilson-like from their instrument. The powerful effects of timbral manipulation represent one of the many ways that actual musical practice poses questions about human communication that science cannot yet address.

演奏者运用的表达工具往往依赖于对声音中极其细微、微妙之处的专业操控——例如将起始音提前或后移几十毫秒，或者将一个音符的音量略高于另一个音符。如此精准地控制声音的能力令人难以信服。然而，大量研究表明，这些音调的变调是有意为之。同一位乐器演奏家演奏同一首乐曲，即使相隔数月或数年，也能展现出极其一致的表达变化模式。

The expressive tools performers use often depend on expert manipulation of very subtle, nuanced aspects of sound—pushing an onset tens of milliseconds forward or back, or playing one note slightly louder than another. The capacity to control sound with this precision strains believability. Yet numerous studies have shown that these inflections are intentional. Performances of the same piece by the same instrumentalist show remarkably consistent patterns of expressive variation, even when they are separated by months or years.

6.这些线条展现了同一位钢琴家在三次不同演奏肖邦练习曲选段时节奏的起伏。它们如此紧密地衔接在一起，表明细微节奏的表达变化是有意为之。

6. These lines show fluctuations in tempo across three different performances by the same pianist of an excerpt from a Chopin étude. The fact that they track each other so closely suggests that expressive variation in microtiming is intentional.

正如作曲家试图精心设计预期，引导听众期待特定的延续，然后转向一些不同的、富有表现力的内容，表演者也试图运用自己的力量来增强对预期的操控。例如，表演者可能会延迟一个意想不到的音符的出现，或者巧妙地改变其音色。这些富有表现力的改变能否令人信服地执行，取决于表演者对音乐结构的直觉，以及他或她在相关音乐风格中的经验。多年来沉浸于特定音乐的人与初次接触该风格的人会产生不同的预期。因此，那些以富有表现力的方式强调某种预期的表演者某种音乐风格可能更能吸引特定类型的听众。因此，理解富有表现力的表演，与其说是理解表演者与乐谱（乐曲的记谱版本）之间的关系，不如说是理解听众体验与表演者决策之间的动态相互作用。

Just as composers seek to choreograph expectations, leading listeners to expect particular continuations and then deviating to something different and expressively charged, performers try to marshal their powers to enhance this manipulation of expectations. For example, a performer might delay the onset of an unexpected note, or subtly alter its timbre. The convincing execution of such expressive alterations depends on the performer’s intuition about musical structure, and on his or her experience within the relevant musical style. People who have spent years immersed in a particular body of music generate different expectations than people new to the style. Accordingly, performers who expressively emphasize one kind of expectation over another might grip a particular kind of listener more persuasively. In this way, understanding expressive performance is more about understanding the dynamic interplay between listener experiences and performer decisions than about understanding how performers relate to a score (the notated version of a piece).

尽管许多研究已从心理学的角度探讨了富有表现力的演奏，但其中大部分研究都与西方古典音乐相关。这些沟通策略在不同文化中的共通程度在很大程度上仍不得而知。当音乐传统以口述而非记谱形式传承时，由于缺乏方便的无变调乐谱作为比较对象，因此概念化和考察演奏者细微的差别会更加困难。有时，在一种风格中被视为富有表现力的变调的演奏选择（例如，改变语调，使C音略微升调或降调）在另一种风格中可能具有完全不同的类别（例如，在某些传统的印度音乐中，西方算作C音的音高范围被划分为几个不同的类别）。同样，时间的类别也因文化而异。对于熟悉传统西方音乐均匀节拍的听众来说，由一个稍长的音符和一个稍短的音符组成的演奏时长比，可能被理解为两个双拍音符，其中第一个音符富有表现力地持续。然而，对于熟悉传统巴尔干音乐不均匀节拍的听众来说，它可能被理解为一个三拍音符后跟一个两拍音符。

Although much research has examined expressive performance from the perspective of psychology, the bulk of it relates to Western classical music. The degree to which these communicative strategies are shared across different cultures is largely unknown. When musical traditions are oral rather than notated, it can be more difficult to conceptualize and examine performer nuance because the convenient comparative case of an uninflected score does not exist. Sometimes performance choices that count as expressive inflections in one style (for example, altering intonation so that a C is played slightly sharp or flat) can function as entirely different categories in another (for example, in some traditional Indian music, where the pitch range that counts as a C in the West is divided into several distinct individual categories). Similarly, timing categories can vary from culture to culture. To listeners familiar with the even meters of traditional Western music, a performed durational ratio consisting of a slightly longer note followed by a slightly shorter note might be understood as two two-beat notes with the first expressively sustained. To listeners familiar with the uneven meters of traditional Balkan music, however, it might be understood as a three-beat note followed by a two-beat note.

体验性能

Experiencing performance

在一个研究听众对表演者语调反应的模型中，表演者被要求多次演奏一段旋律，每次都试图传达不同的情感。然后，人们聆听这些录音，并尝试将表演与预期的情感进行匹配。这类实验通常表明，表演者对诸如因为节奏、力度和发音能够准确地传达诸如快乐、悲伤或愤怒等基本情绪。音乐中用来表达情绪的表达工具与情绪化言语的习惯相似：愤怒演奏的乐段，就像愤怒说出的话语一样，往往节奏更快、音量更大，并且使用更尖锐、更突兀的开头。然而，这类研究受限于其对基本情绪类别的依赖；人们往往重视音乐，因为它能够传递复杂、微妙、难以表达的表达状态。

In one model for studying listener responses to performer inflection, performers are instructed to play a melody multiple times, aiming to convey a different emotion each time. People then listen to these recordings and attempt to match the performance with the intended emotion. Experiments like this generally show that performer manipulations of dimensions such as timing, dynamics, and articulation can reliably convey basic emotions such as happiness, sadness, or anger. The expressive tools used to convey emotions in music parallel the habits of emotive speech: passages played angrily, just like utterances spoken angrily, tend to be faster and louder and use sharper, more abrupt onsets. Yet studies of this sort are limited by their reliance on basic emotion categories; people often value music for its capacity to transmit complex, nuanced, difficult-to-articulate expressive states.

研究人员还使用电生理测量方法来评估听众对富有表现力的表演的反应，考察表演者语调变化对心率和皮肤电导反应（唤醒指标）等现象​​的影响。然而，研究人员最常见的做法是直接询问听众他们对表演的体验。例如，当听众听到在节奏和力度方面更接近或远离平均水平的富有表现力的表演时，他们会将平均水平的表演评为更高质量，而将不太平均的表演评为更具个性。其他研究也揭示了听众觉得愉悦的表演类型和他们觉得有趣的表演类型之间存在类似的分离。表演的平均性与其感知质量之间的联系与其他领域关于审美偏好的研究一致；例如，当对多张人脸图像进行平均以形成合成图像时，当对更多人脸图像进行平均以生成合成图像时（当这些人脸图像更接近于一个庞大群体的真实平均值时），人们会将生成的合成图像评为更美丽。表演者的语调也被证明会影响听众对音乐结构的理解，使他们听到不同的节奏、乐句界限和高潮。

Researchers also assess listener responses to expressive performance using electrophysiological measures, examining the effect of performer inflections on phenomena like heart rate and skin conductance response (indications of arousal). Most frequently, however, researchers simply ask listeners directly about their experience of a performance. For example, when presented with expressive performances that were closer to or further from average in terms of timing and dynamics, listeners rated the average performances as higher quality, but they rated the less-average performances as more individual. Other studies have revealed a similar disassociation between the kinds of performances listeners find enjoyable and the kinds they find interesting. The link between a performance’s averageness and its perceived quality is consistent with research about aesthetic preferences in other domains; for instance, when multiple faces were averaged to form composites, people rated the resultant faces as more beautiful when more faces had been averaged to produce them (when the faces were closer to the true average of a large population). Performer inflections have also been shown to influence listeners’ understanding of musical structure, persuading them to hear different meters, phrase boundaries, and climaxes.

但操纵听觉信号并非表演者与听众沟通的唯一方式。大量研究表明，视觉信息——尤其是表演者演奏时的动作不仅对表演的整体评价有很大的影响，而且对听众实际听到的内容也有很大的影响。听觉和视觉领域之间的这种紧密结合也是语音的特征。麦格克效应是指一种知觉错觉，即将某人说“ba-ba-ba”的录音叠加在“ga-ga-ga”唇形动作的视频录像上。观看视频的人往往会听到中间的音节，如“da-da-da”，只要他们闭上眼睛，这个音节就会纠正为“ba-ba-ba”。即使知道这是一种错觉的人也倾向于听到“da-da-da”，这表明视觉和听觉信息会自动整合，不受意识控制。一个人看到的内容可以从根本上塑造他听到的内容。

But manipulations of the auditory signal are not the only way the performer communicates to the listener. Numerous studies show that information in the visual modality—particularly the movements of performers as they play—has a powerful effect not just on the overall evaluation of the performance, but also on what listeners actually hear. This tight coupling between the auditory and the visual domains also characterizes speech. The McGurk effect refers to a perceptual illusion where an audio recording of someone saying “ba-ba-ba” is superimposed on a video recording of the lip movements for “ga-ga-ga.” People looking at the video tend to hear an in-between syllable such as “da-da-da,” which corrects to “ba-ba-ba” as soon as they close their eyes. Even people who know it is an illusion tend to hear “da-da-da,” indicating that visual and audio information integrate automatically, outside of conscious control. What a person sees can fundamentally shape what a person hears.

大量例子证明了视觉在音乐体验中的重要性。一项研究表明，人们能够通过观看音乐比赛的无声表演视频准确预测获胜者，但听录音则不然。同一个音符，其起始音的起伏程度，取决于伴奏的是拨弦视频（拨弦的动作通常会产生起伏），还是拉弦视频（拉弦的动作通常会产生平缓的起伏）。同一个音程（两个音高之间的距离），其起始音的长短，取决于伴奏的是演唱者演唱短音程还是长音程的视频。事实上，即使音频被静音，人们完全听不到任何声音，他们也能很好地根据演唱者演唱的视频图像来判断音程的大小。

Numerous examples demonstrate the importance of the visual modality in musical experience. One study suggests that people are able to accurately predict music competition winners by viewing silent videos of their performances, but not by hearing audio recordings of them. The same musical note can be heard as having a more or a less abrupt onset depending on whether it is accompanied by video of a string being plucked (a gesture that typically produces an abrupt onset) or bowed (a gesture that typically produces a more gradual one). The same interval (the distance between two pitches) can be heard as smaller or larger depending on whether it is accompanied by video of a person singing a small or large interval. In fact, people are quite good at judging the size of an interval from video images of people singing them, even when the audio is muted so that they are not hearing anything at all.

看过MTV音乐视频或近距离见证过精彩现场表演的人都知道，这些跨模态效应远不止对起始时间和音程大小的判断，还会影响音乐的表现力。心理学家威廉·汤普森和弗兰克·鲁索的研究表明，人们会评价BB布鲁斯表演中的不和谐时刻（即音符之间似乎发生冲突或无法协调的时刻）。当金演奏时，伴有他以视觉方式凸显冲突（例如眯起眼睛和摇晃躯干）的视频片段，会让他感觉更加不和谐，而伴有他以更中性的面部表情演奏的视频片段时则不然。对不和谐音的感知本质上会影响对音乐的情感反应。学者们曾尝试用人耳结构和基本的心理声学原理来解释这种不和谐音，但研究表明，即使是像抬眉或低眉这样的动作也能发挥作用。

People who have watched music videos on MTV or witnessed powerful live performances from close proximity know that these cross-modal effects extend well beyond judgments of onset timing and interval size and into the expressive character of the music. Psychologists William Thompson and Frank Russo showed that people rated dissonant moments (when notes seemed to clash or fail to harmonize with each other) in blues performances by B. B. King as more dissonant when accompanied by video footage of him visually highlighting the conflict (by narrowing his eyes and shaking his torso, for example) then when they were accompanied by video of him playing with a more neutral facial expression. Perceptions of dissonance contribute essentially to affective responses to music. Scholars have tried to explain them in terms of the structure of the human ear and basic psychoacoustic principles, but research suggests that even something like the raising or lowering of an eyebrow can play a role.

当人们被要求评价音程的表现特征时，大三度（歌曲“Kumbaya”的开头音程）通常被认为是最快乐的音程之一，而小三度（歌曲“Greensleeves”的开头音程）被认为是最悲伤的音程之一——尽管它们只相差一个半音。但是，当人们唱这些音程的音频和视频互换时，人们会感受到声音传达出不同程度的情感。歌手在唱大三度时往往会扬起眉毛，睁大眼睛，并张开嘴角露出一丝微笑。当人们看到有人唱大三度的视觉图像，同时听到有人唱小三度的音频信号时，他们会认为声音本身更快乐。

When people are asked to rate the expressive characteristics of musical intervals, the major third (the interval that starts the song “Kumbaya”) is often rated as one of the happiest, and the minor third (the interval that starts “Greensleeves”) as one of the saddest—despite that they differ by only one semitone. But when audio and video of people singing these intervals are swapped, people experience the sound as conveying different degrees of emotionality. Singers tend to raise their eyebrows, widen their eyes, and spread their mouth into a faint smile when singing a major third. When people see the visual imagery of someone singing a major third while hearing the audio signal from someone singing a minor third, they rate the sound itself as happier.

音乐学家简·戴维森（Jane Davidson）利用运动追踪技术捕捉小提琴演奏家在富有表现力或面无表情的演奏中的动作——试图尽可能地减少表演的表达性。听众判断演奏者的表现意图（无论他们是有意还是无意地演奏）有时在观看动作的点光源显示时比实际聆听声音时更准确，这表明音乐的表现力有时更容易从视觉而非听觉领域解读。其他涉及单簧管演奏家的研究表明，将极具表现力的表演视频叠加在面无表情的演奏音频上，可以让听众相信声音本身就充满了情感的交流。相比于通过iPod聆听，现场音乐会丰富、多维的语境或许能为听众提供更多途径，带来引人入胜的体验。

Musicologist Jane Davidson used motion tracking to capture the movements of violinists while they played either expressively or in a deadpan manner—attempting to convey as little expressivity as possible. Listeners judging the expressive intent of the performer (whether they meant to play with or without expression) were sometimes more accurate when looking at point light displays of the movements than when actually listening to the sound, suggesting that musical expressivity can sometimes be more easily decoded from the visual than the auditory domain. Other work involving clarinetists showed that superimposing video of highly expressive performances on audio from deadpan renditions could convince listeners that the sound itself was full of communicative emotionality. The rich, multidimensional contexts of live concerts likely provide listeners with additional paths to engaging experiences compared to listening over iPods.

视觉信息并非唯一能够影响演奏评价的非听觉体验。人们是否事先阅读过一段音乐的描述，也会影响他们对音乐的欣赏程度。此外，当欣赏到同一首乐曲的两场演出时，人们往往会更喜欢第二场。如果人们之前听过同一首乐曲，他们就能更有效地处理它。他们往往会将这种认知流畅度的提升错误地归因于音乐本身的某些积极特质，从而对第二场演出的欣赏评分更高。即使两场演出在声学上完全相同，但如果被告知是由不同的演奏者演奏，人们通常也会声称它们听起来截然不同，并主张第二场演出更胜一筹。

Visual information is not the only non-auditory aspect of experience that can influence performance evaluation. Whether or not people read a description of a musical excerpt beforehand can influence how much they enjoy the music. Additionally, when presented with a pair of performances of the same piece, they tend to prefer the second. When people have heard a piece before, they can to process it more efficiently. They tend to misattribute this increased cognitive fluency to some positive characteristic of the music itself, resulting in higher enjoyment ratings for performances that come second. Even when both performances in the pair are acoustically identical, if told they are played by different performers, people will often claim that they sound markedly different, and argue in favor of the second one’s superiority.

如果被告知演奏者是世界知名的专业钢琴家，而不是音乐学院的学生，人们往往会更欣赏他们的个人表演。告知听众他们将要聆听的是专业钢琴家的演奏，会激活奖励回路，这种回路会持续整个音乐片段的播放。克服描述带来的偏见——例如，选择更喜欢标有学生身份的演奏——需要调动大脑中负责执行控制的区域。这些发现与关于品质信息在其他领域的影响的研究相似，例如，有实验表明，如果葡萄酒价格更高，人们会更喜欢它。音乐表演存在于复杂、多维的社会文化背景中，音乐心理学的研究反复证明，聆听并非对单个声音事件产生可预测的反应，而是运用人类的多种能力来引发丰富而有意义的体验。体验。表演者对这个网络至关重要，不仅在于他们如何弯曲和拉伸声音，还在于他们在空间中的移动方式以及与听众的互动方式。

People also tend to enjoy individual performances more if told they come from of a world-renowned professional pianist rather than a conservatory student. Informing listeners that they are going to hear a professional activates reward circuitry that can persist throughout the duration of a musical excerpt. Overcoming the bias introduced by the description—choosing to prefer a performance labeled as coming from a student, for example—requires the recruitment of brain regions devoted to executive control. These findings parallel work on the impact of information about quality in other areas, for example experiments showing that people enjoy wine more if accompanied by a higher price tag. Music performance exists within a complex, multidimensional, sociocultural context, and research in the psychology of music has repeatedly demonstrated that listening is not a matter of churning out predictable responses to individual acoustic events, but rather of drawing on myriad human faculties to elicit rich, meaningful experiences. Performers are critical to this network, not just in the ways they bend and stretch the sound, but also in the ways they move in space and relate to their listeners.

音乐表演的机制

The mechanics of music performance

一首钢琴曲的演奏可能需要数千个音符以精准的节奏连续演奏，音量和双手同步等属性需要精心控制，有时速度高达每秒十个音符，完全凭记忆演奏，错误率低于3%。这似乎令人惊叹。从另一个角度来看，同样令人震惊的是，没有接受过正规音乐训练的孩子能够凭记忆唱出熟悉的歌曲，并以正确的顺序发出几分钟音符的正确音高。这两项技能都需要准确的记忆表征和精细的运动控制。

The performance of a single piano piece might entail thousands of notes executed in precise rhythmic succession, with attributes such as loudness and inter-hand synchrony carefully controlled, sometimes at a speed of over ten notes per second, from memory, with an error rate of under 3 percent. This seems astounding. It is similarly astounding, from another perspective, that children who have had no formal training in music can sing familiar songs from memory, producing the correct pitches in the correct order for several minutes worth of notes. Both of these feats require accurate memory representations and meticulous motor control.

音乐序列中一系列事件的产生机制可以通过运动捕捉技术追踪手指运动，或通过录制经过数字增强处理的乐器演奏来研究，这些乐器可以捕捉按键和其他演奏行为的即时信息。一种常见的方法是研究演奏错误。错误发生的时间和地点可以揭示有关运动计划过程的信息。

The circuitry behind the production of the strictly timed series of events characteristic of musical sequences can be studied by using motion capture to track finger movements, or by recording performances on instruments that have been digitally augmented to capture moment-to-moment information on key presses and other performance behaviors. One common methodology involves studying performance errors. When and where they occur can reveal information about the motor planning process.

例如，如果我的任务是演奏ABCDE音符，而我演奏的是ABECD，这可能表明当我演奏完B音符时，我已经计划好了E音符。这类预期错误在言语中也很常见——比如不经意地说“我把牛奶给了宝宝”而不是“我把牛奶给了宝宝”——也表明了类似的计划过程。大多数研究表明，演奏者在演奏时会计划未来三到四个音符。随着经验的积累，这个跨度会越来越大；一个人学习乐器的时间越长，他们犯的预期错误就越多。或许，在经历了一段……之后，这能带来一些安慰。拙劣的表演需要精心训练才能避免？表演者还会系统性地在音乐织体的内声部犯更多错误，而不是在通常包含旋律的更突出的高声部或通常提供和声基础的低声部。巧合的是，这些内声部错误最难被听众察觉。

For example, if my job is to play the notes ABCDE, and I play ABECD, it might indicate that I was already planning as far out as note E by the time I finished note B. These kinds of anticipatory errors are common in speech as well—inadvertently saying “I gave my milk the baby” instead of “I gave my baby the milk”—and indicate similar planning processes. Most studies suggest that performers plan three to four notes into the future as they play. This span increases as people gain experience; the longer someone has studied an instrument, the more anticipatory errors they make. Perhaps it can be some consolation after a botched performance that the error required elaborate training to make? Performers also systematically make more errors in the inner voices of a musical texture, rather than in the more salient top voice, which often contains the melody, or in the bottom voice, which often provides the harmonic foundation. Conveniently, these inner voice errors are the hardest for listeners to detect.

演奏者经常会被要求演奏他们从未见过的乐谱，这种技能被称为视奏。这项技能可以通过眼动追踪技术来研究，该技术可以动态测量人们在进行活动时注视点的变化。眼动追踪研究表明，优秀的视奏者注视的时间更短——快速一瞥就足以理解任何特定时刻的信息。这种快速性来自于经验丰富的视奏者能够将单个音符分解成熟悉的模式，例如和弦或刻板的旋律音型。由于优秀的视奏者依赖于对部分信息的预期来执行动作，因此当音乐可预测地保持在主调上、以小步移动并使用常规模式时，他们的表现会更好。尽管人们对优秀的视奏者有着广泛的猜测，但预测视奏技巧的最佳指标是此人过去视奏的乐曲数量。对于一项依赖于预测接下来会发生什么的任务，没有什么可以替代视奏足够多的乐曲，这样你的双手就可以在演奏时跳到可能的后续乐曲。

Circumstances often call on performers to play from a score they have never seen before, a skill termed sight-reading. This skill can be studied using eye-tracking technology that dynamically measures changes in the point of gaze while people perform an activity. Eye-tracking studies show that better sight-readers fixate for shorter periods of time—a quick glance is sufficient to apprehend the information at any particular moment. This speediness comes from the ability of experienced sight-readers to chunk individual notes into familiar patterns, such as chords or stereotypical melodic figures. Because of their dependence on expectations to execute movements based on partial information, good sight-readers perform better when the music stays predictably in its home key, moves by small steps, and uses conventional patterns. Although people speculate broadly about what makes a good sight reader, the single best predictor of sight-reading skill is the number of pieces the person has sight-read in the past. For a task that depends on anticipating what is going to come next, there is simply no substitute for sight-reading enough pieces that your hands can leap to likely continuations as you play.

实践出真知

Practice makes a difference

关于视奏流畅性作用的研究，有力地证明了努力练习的价值——而关于练习在演奏中的作用的研究，则更加有力地证明了这一点。西柏林音乐学院的教授们找到了一群代表该校最优秀小提琴学生。一组是演奏家，另一组只是表现不错。对这两组小提琴手的详尽调查显示，他们有不同的生活经历：最优秀组的小提琴手到 18 岁时积累了超过 7,000 小时的练习时间，而优秀组的小提琴手到 18 岁时只积累了大约 5,000 小时。其他针对刚开始学习乐器的小学生的研究表明，音乐表演任务的成功可以通过学生的动机（以在实验室任务失败后仍坚持不懈来衡量）和练习乐器的时间来解释。其他任何衡量标准，包括智力和一般音乐能力倾向测试，都无法预测他们的成功。研究还表明，更多的练习可以使钢琴家更快地从一个调转换到另一个调，并使表现力更加一致。

Research on the role of fluency in sight reading makes a compelling case for the merits of hard work—and research on the role of practice in performance makes an even stronger case. Professors at the Music Academy of West Berlin identified a group of violin students who represented the institution’s very best performers and another group of violin students who were merely good. Exhaustive surveys of violinists in these two groups revealed that they were distinguished by different life experiences: violinists in the best group had accumulated more than 7,000 hours of practice by the age of eighteen, but violinists in the good group had accumulated only about 5,000 by the same age. Other research on elementary school children just beginning to play an instrument showed that success on a music performance task could be explained by a student’s amount of motivation (as measured by persistence despite failure on a laboratory task) and the amount of time they practiced their instrument. No other measure, including intelligence and a general musical aptitude test, was able to predict their success. More practice has also been shown to lead to faster transitions from key to key in pianists and more consistency in expressive performance.

研究还强调，高质量的练习比仅仅在乐器上花费的时间更重要。反复弹奏一首曲子，虽然对于那些父母为练习设定了计时器的孩子来说，可能是一种消耗时间的诱惑，但这并非有效的练习。相反，研究表明，高质量的练习是刻意的，包括精心的自我管理、注意力、目标设定和专注力。一项针对一万多对双胞胎的研究表明，基因不仅直接影响音乐能力，还会通过影响练习的意愿间接地影响音乐能力。因此，一些目前归因于练习的发现最终可能被证明源于生物学。

Research also argues for the importance of quality practice over the mere number of hours spent at the instrument. Playing through a piece repeatedly, although a tempting salvo to run out the clock for kids whose parents have set a timer for their practice session, does not qualify as effective practice. Research suggests, instead, that quality practice is deliberate, involving careful self-management, attention, goal-setting, and focus. A study of more than 10,000 twins argued that genetics affects musical ability not only directly, but also indirectly, by influencing the inclination to practice. Thus, some of the findings currently attributed to practice may ultimately prove to have their roots in biology.

当人们开始练习时，他们无法有效地激活大脑感觉运动区域的大量神经元。当他们学习演奏一首曲子时，来自听觉、视觉和其他中枢的信息会被整合成可以自动执行的运动模式。在这个学习过程中，大脑皮层（高级认知的中心）的活动会减少，而控制运动的皮层下区域（如基底神经节）的活动则会增强。和小脑也会增大。对于那些无法持续使用乐器的人来说，一个好消息是，心理练习激活的大脑区域与实际练习激活的大脑区域高度相似。多项研究表明，当心理练习与乐器练习相结合时，它可以成为一种非常有效的工具。音乐表演中至关重要的听觉-运动联系也影响着音乐训练。世界各地的许多教学并非涉及表演讲座或口头提示，而是简单的模仿，即老师演奏一段乐曲，学生尝试模仿。

When people begin practicing, they inefficiently activate wide swaths of neurons in sensorimotor areas of the brain. As they learn to play a piece, information from auditory, visual, and other centers is integrated into movement patterns that can be executed automatically. Across the course of this learning process, activity in the cortex—the seat of higher cognition—decreases and activity in movement-controlling subcortical areas like the basal ganglia and cerebellum increases. One piece of good news for people who may not be able to consistently access their instrument is that mental practice activates brain regions that are highly similar to the ones activated by actual practicing. Multiple studies show that when combined with practice on the instrument, it can be a highly effective tool. The critical auditory-motor link that underlies music performance also influences music training. Much instruction around the world involves not lectures about performance, or verbal tips, but rather simple imitation, where the teacher plays a passage and students attempt to replicate it.

然而，无论一位表演者在练习室里待了多久，都无法完全做好准备，面对满怀期待的观众，走上舞台时的压力。尤其是在西方古典音乐传统中，音乐表演会引发焦虑，包括躯体焦虑（忐忑不安、口干舌燥、呼吸急促）和认知焦虑（演出前的负面想法、过度担忧）。尽管β受体阻滞剂已被证明可以缓解某些躯体焦虑，但音乐表演焦虑总体上是出了名的难以治疗。研究表明，最好的策略是尝试预防它，尽早将公开表演引入音乐学生的生活中，在低风险、低压力的环境中进行。

No matter how much time a performer spends in a practice room, however, nothing quite prepares her for the pressure of walking out onto a stage before an expectant audience. Especially in Western classical traditions, music performance can elicit anxiety, both somatic (butterflies in the stomach, dry mouth, shallow breathing) and cognitive (negative thoughts before a performance, excessive worry). Although beta blockers have been shown to alleviate some aspects of somatic anxiety, musical performance anxiety is overall notoriously difficult to treat. Research suggests that the best strategy is to attempt to prevent it by introducing public performance into the lives of music students early, in low-stakes, low-pressure settings.

创造力和即兴创作

Creativity and improvisation

表演、作曲和即兴创作的创造力程度各不相同。心理学中一个活跃的研究方向假设创造力是一种稳定的个人特质——例如，一个人可能普遍比另一个人更有创造力。为了衡量创造力，这项研究使用了诸如远程联想测试之类的任务——参与者看到三个看似不相关的词（例如馅饼、运气和肚子），必须找出与所有词都相关的第四个词（在本例中是锅）——以及流畅性评估，参与者必须列出他们能想到的一件常见家居用品的所有可能用途。研究人员利用神经影像技术来检查这类创造性解决问题背后的大脑活动。

Performances, compositions, and improvisations can be creative to varying extents. One active line of research in psychology assumes that creativity is a stable personal characteristic—that one person might be generally more creative than another, for example. To measure creativity this research uses tasks like the Remote Association Test—in which people see three seemingly unrelated words (such as pie, luck, and belly) and must identify a fourth that relates to all of them (in this case, pot)—and fluidity assessments, in which people must list all the possible uses they can think of for a common household item. Researchers employ neuroimaging to examine the brain activity that underlies creative problem solving of this sort.

另一种观点认为创造力是一种源自社会体系而非个体的特质。心理学家米哈里·契克森米哈赖（Mihaly Csikszentmihalyi）提出了这种观点，认为创造力需要一个由离散规则和约束所定义的领域，在这个领域内，专家群体才有可能识别创新。关于音乐与创造力的研究通常将爵士乐即兴演奏作为这一领域。由于神经影像学显示在创作爵士乐即兴演奏和创作新颖的、从未说过的句子时，大脑中被激活的区域相似，因此，关于音乐创造力的研究可以被视为更广泛意义上的创造力过程的代表。

Another perspective looks at creativity as a property that emerges out of a social system, rather than a property that arises out of an individual. In this view, promulgated by psychologist Mihaly Csikszentmihalyi, creativity requires a domain characterized by discrete rules and constraints within which it is possible for a community of experts to recognize innovation. Research about music and creativity often uses jazz improvisation as this domain. Since neuroimaging shows that similar brain regions are activated when producing jazz improvisation and when producing novel, never-before-said sentences, work about musical creativity can be taken as representative of creative processes more broadly construed.

一项研究利用神经成像技术对爵士乐演奏家在键盘上即兴演奏的情况进行了观察（这要归功于一个巧妙的装置，使得在功能磁共振成像扫描仪内进行演奏成为可能）。最有趣的发现并非在于哪些大脑区域在成功的即兴演奏中被激活，而是在于哪些大脑区域被关闭了。在这些时期，大脑中负责自我监控的区域——背外侧前额叶皮层——的活动会关闭，这意味着演奏者需要抑制某些执行功能成分，以便为新的联想的出现创造空间。

One study used neuroimaging to examine expert jazz performers as they improvised at the keyboard (thanks to a clever setup that made it possible to play inside an fMRI scanner). What emerged as most interesting was not so much which brain areas were activated during successful improvisation, but which ones were switched off. During these periods, activity in the part of the brain responsible for self-monitoring—the dorsolateral prefrontal cortex—shut down, implying that a performer needs to silence some components of executive function to create the space for novel associations to emerge.

在音乐心理学领域，哲学问题和科学问题常常交织在一起。创造力研究也不例外。什么才算音乐创造力？具有音乐创造力的人是否也必然在其他领域具有创造力？诸如此类的问题需要深思熟虑的哲学思考和严谨的实验探究。音乐创造力的心理学研究将受益于理论、定义性描述与实证方法之间更紧密的联系。音乐创造力领​​域与人类一样，根植于文化，错综复杂。创造力需要多个学科的持续参与才能取得进展。

Philosophical and scientific problems often intermingle in the psychology of music. Work on creativity is no exception. What counts as musical creativity? Is a musically creative person necessarily creative in other domains as well? Questions like these require both careful philosophical thought and rigorous experimental inquiry. Psychological work on musical creativity would benefit from closer relationships between theoretical, definitional accounts and empirical approaches to the topic. A domain as culturally embedded and complex as human creativity requires sustained engagement from multiple disciplines for headway to occur.

虽然探究哪些表达特质才能成就一场精彩的表演似乎是心理学研究的终极目标，但这个问题并非完全局限于心理学领域。诸多社会文化因素可能导致一个人觉得碧昂丝的表演动人心弦、令人震撼，而另一个人则可能因此换台。大众媒体刊登的标题宣称科学发现了一首好歌的要素，这应该引起人们的怀疑。我的好歌可能是你的烂歌，这并非毫无道理。音乐心理学领域的认真研究会划定研究问题的边界，并明确其研究结果可能适用的人群。音乐表演模型并非直接从声学信号到听众体验；相反，它涵盖了社会环境的各个方面的影响，从表演的视觉效果到表演的地点，以及表演与听众以往体验的关联。正是这种动态的相互作用，使得音乐成为如此引人入胜的人类活动，值得持续研究。

Although it may seem like the holy grail of psychological research on performance and improvisation to ask which expressive characteristics make a performance good, this question cannot lie entirely in the domain of psychology. A whole host of sociocultural factors may lead one person to find Beyoncé’s performances moving and transformative, and another to change the station. Headlines that emerge in the popular press announcing that science has discovered the ingredients for a good song should raise suspicions. My good song might be your terrible song, and for good reason. Responsible work in the psychology of music delineates the borders of its questions and specifies the population to whom its findings might generalize. A model of music performance does not go straight from acoustic signal to listener experience; rather, it embraces at all sides the influence of the social context, ranging from what the performance looks like to where it takes place and how that relates to the listener’s previous experiences. This dynamic interplay is precisely what makes music such a fascinating human endeavor, worthy of such sustained study.

第六章

Chapter 6

人类的音乐性

Human musicality

拥有音乐天赋意味着什么？有些人把所有空闲时间都花在听音乐会和制作复杂的播放列表上；有些人则喜欢听脱口秀电台节目。有些人认真学习乐器，研读教学书籍，刻苦钻研乐谱；有些人拿起乐器，弹奏自己喜欢的曲子，自学如何凭耳朵演奏。有些人对音乐反应敏锐——很容易发现自己跟着音乐摇摆，沉浸在音乐中；而有些人则对扬声器里传来的音乐毫不在意。每个人演奏和欣赏音乐的能力差异如此之大，这不禁让人思考音乐天赋的本质及其后天习得的方式。人们天生就拥有什么样的音乐天赋？这种天赋是如何以如此多样化的方式发展的？

What does it mean to be musical? Some people spend all their free time going to concerts and crafting intricate playlists; others prefer talk radio. Some people apply themselves earnestly to the enterprise of learning an instrument, working through method books and diligently studying notation; others pick one up and sound out their favorite tunes, teaching themselves how to play by ear. Some people respond sensitively to music—easily finding themselves swaying along, engrossed by what they hear; others could not care less what is coming from the speakers. The fact that the ability to perform and appreciate music varies so substantially from person to person raises questions about the nature of musical capacity and how it is acquired. What kind of musicality are people born with, and how does it develop in such diverse ways?

音调感知

Pitch perception

音乐性的核心要素之一是音高感知。频率更快（每秒周期数更多）的声波听起来是“高”而不是“低”——这是一种文化背景中特有的隐喻，在印度尼西亚部分地区，它被体验为“小”与“大”，在中非的巴什人中，它被体验为“弱”与“强”。但音高感知也可能包括对……的敏感度正在播放的确切频率——是 B 吗？是 C 吗？——以及这个音符在周围音调环境中的位置。

One central aspect of musicality is pitch perception. Sound waves with faster frequencies (featuring more cycles per second) are heard as “high” rather than “low”—a culturally contingent metaphor experienced as “small” versus “large” in parts of Indonesia and “weak” versus “strong” among the Bashi people in central Africa. But pitch perception can also include sensitivity to the exact frequency being played—is it a B? Is it a C?—and to the position of this note within the surrounding tonal context.

调性是指听到的音高与中心主音（主音）之间的关系。如果我用C调唱一首曲子——C音是中心主音——那么B音听起来会很不稳定，给人一种它应该最终达到C音的感觉。然而，如果我用B调唱一首曲子，那么同样的B音现在听起来会非常稳定，这并不意味着需要最终达到C音——事实上，它现在可以相当令人信服地作为歌曲的最终音。

Tonality refers to the sense that pitches are heard in relation to a central, governing tonic. If I sang a tune in the key of C—where C functions as this central tonic—the pitch B would sound unstable, conveying a sense that it should resolve up to C. If I sang a tune in the key of B, however, that same pitch B could now be heard as highly stable, not implying any need for resolution—in fact, it could now serve quite convincingly as the final note of the song.

在一项经典实验中，康奈尔大学心理学家卡罗尔·克鲁姆汉斯尔（Carol Krumhansl）为听众播放简短的音调环境，例如音阶或和弦进行，然后播放一个探测音。每次探测之后，她都会问一个简单的问题：这个探测音与之前的环境的契合度如何？她根据听众的回答创建了音调曲线。这些曲线沿 x 轴绘制探测音，沿 y 轴绘制拟合优度评级。如果从当前环境的主音开始按顺序列出探测音，则曲线在每个调上看起来都大同小异。人们听到的主音与环境的契合度最高，而走调的音符则最不契合。他们的回答揭示了音高的相关关系：任何单个音符的体验都由其在主导音调图式中的位置所塑造。

In a classic experiment, Cornell psychologist Carol Krumhansl played listeners brief tonal contexts, such as a scale or chord progression, followed by a single probe tone. After each probe, she asked a simple question: how well did it fit with the preceding context? She created tone profiles out of the responses. These profiles plot probes along the x-axis and goodness-of-fit ratings along the y-axis. If the probes are listed in order starting with the tonic of the prevailing context, the profiles look more or less the same in every key. People hear the tonic as fitting the context best, and out-of-key notes as fitting worst. Their responses reveal that pitch relationally: the experience of any individual note is shaped by its position within the governing tonal schema.

7.这张图表的 y 轴表示拟合优度，x 轴表示音高。它被称为音调曲线，只要 x 轴从音阶的第一个音符开始排列，每个大调的曲线看起来都一样。绘制该大调乐曲中每个音符出现频率的图表也看起来惊人地相似，这表明追踪音乐中常见情况的统计数据有助于理解音乐对调性的感知。

7. This chart plots goodness-of-fit ratings on the y-axis and pitches on the x-axis. Called a tone profile, it looks the same for every major key, so long as the x-axis is ordered starting at the first note of the scale. Charts that plot the frequency of occurrence of each note in pieces written in the key also look strikingly similar, suggesting that tracking the statistics about what tends to happen in music feeds into perceptions of key.

后来，研究人员发现，只需统计某个特定调中每个音高在音乐中出现的次数，就能绘制出与音调曲线极其相似的曲线图。例如，B音高在B调中出现的频率远高于在C调中。出现频率图与拟合优度图之间的相似性，使得人们相信，对音符频率统计数据的隐式追踪有助于形成对调性的感知。

Later, researchers discovered that simply by counting up the number of times each pitch occurred in music in a particular key, they could produce plots remarkably similar to the tone profiles. The pitch B occurred much more frequently in the key of B, for example, than in the key of C. The similarity between the frequency-of-occurrence plots and the goodness-of-fit plots made it possible to believe that the implicit tracking of statistics about note frequency helps give rise to perceptions of tonality.

能够超越特定音高，并根据中心音调进行感知的能力被称为相对音高。这种音高主导着大多数人的音高感，但对某些人来说（估计少则万分之一，多则百分之一），绝对音高——即无论上下文如何，所演奏音符的识别——更为重要。对这些听众来说，C音的C性比它在周围音调环境中如何发挥作用更为明显。

The ability to abstract beyond specific pitches and hear in relation to a central tonic is called relative pitch. Relational perceptions of this sort dominate most people’s sense of pitch, but for some people (with estimates ranging from as few as 1 in 10,000 to as many as 1 in 100), absolute pitch—the identity of the actual note being played, regardless of context—is more salient. To these listeners, the C-ness of C is more noticeable than how it functions within the surrounding tonal context.

拥有绝对音感的人能听到吸尘器的嗡嗡声，并辨认出那是升F调。这种能力看起来不可思议。尽管绝对音高在普通人群中并不常见，但一些估计表明，近一半作品常位列古典音乐排行榜前四十名的作曲家都拥有绝对音高。然而，与音乐心理学中的许多其他主题一样，实际情况要更加微妙。首先，相对音高可以说是更复杂的感知技能，需要听众透过声音的表面特征，理解其内在的模式。其次，绝对音高并非非此即彼的现象。有些人拥有极其精湛的绝对音高——例如，音乐制作人里克·比托在YouTube上发布的他儿子迪伦的视频，视频中的孩子能够说出只听过一次的厚重和弦中的各个音符。但新的绝对音高测试绕过了标注的需要，通过巧妙的设计，揭示了一些从未接受过能够识别音高的音乐训练的人的增强音高记忆。一些研究甚至表明，大多数听众都存在各种潜在的绝对音高。人们被要求唱出一首耳熟能详的歌曲的第一句，通常都是从原音开始，或者非常接近原音。听过电视主题曲的人，无论是播放原音还是略微移调的版本，都能很好地辨别出哪个版本是节目中的原版。虽然大多数人即使问他们也唱不出C调，但他们或许只需唱出《辛普森一家》主题曲的第一个音符就能达到同样的效果。

People with absolute pitch can hear the hum of a vacuum cleaner and identify it as an F-sharp. This ability can seem prodigious. Despite its rarity in the general population, some estimates claim that nearly half of composers whose works typically find themselves in the classical music top 40 possessed absolute pitch. Yet like many other topics in the psychology of music, the reality of the picture is more nuanced. First, relative pitch is arguably the more complex perceptual skill, requiring listeners to hear beyond the surface features of sound and understand it in terms of patterns. Second, absolute pitch is not an either/or phenomenon. Some people have extraordinarily refined absolute pitch—music producer Rick Beato’s videos of his son Dylan on YouTube, for example, show a child who can name individual notes within thick chords he has heard only once. But new tests for absolute pitch bypass the need for labeling, using clever designs to reveal enhanced pitch memory in some people who have never had the kind of musical training that would allow them to identify pitches by name. Some studies even suggest that a variety of latent absolute pitch exists in most listeners. People asked to sing the first line of highly familiar tunes often start at or very close to the actual pitch. People exposed to television theme songs played either at their original pitch level or in a slightly transposed version are good at detecting which was the original version featured in the show. Although most people could not sing a C if you asked them, they might be able to perform the functional equivalent simply by singing the first note of the theme song from The Simpsons.

另一种思考音高感知频谱的方式是假设所有这些听觉方式在某种程度上都是可以被感知的。在整个发展过程中，接触典型的音乐练习会鼓励孩子们运用各种过滤机制，因为孩子们会逐渐认识到，声音的某些方面比其他方面更具有音乐相关性。虽然他们一开始是用音高高度来描述旋律，但随着年龄的增长，他们开始关注旋律的轮廓——它们是如何上下移动的。最终，他们会更加关注与中心音调的关系。

Another way of thinking about the spectrum of pitch perception is to assume that all these ways of hearing are perceptually available to some extent. Exposure to typical musical practices across the span of development encourages the application of various filters, as children come to learn that certain aspects of sound are more musically relevant than others. Whereas they start out describing melodies in terms of pitch height, as they get a little older they start focusing on the melodies’ contours—how they move up or down. Eventually, they focus more on relationships with a central tonic.

音乐素养的发展

The development of musicality

要了解音高感知等音乐基本要素是如何产生的，以及它们在个体之间是如何差异的，研究人们获得音乐技能的发展阶段将大有裨益。没有什么比将婴儿视为音乐白板来研究更有潜力了，在婴儿的音乐能力受到文化和经验影响之前，我们能够确定婴儿音乐能力的轮廓。然而，婴儿在子宫内已接触过复杂的声景，从母亲规律的心跳到周围环境中的声音和音乐。新生儿不仅能识别母亲的声音，还能识别他们在子宫内经常听到的旋律。出生前接触到的声音塑造了婴儿的音乐能力——因此，音乐白板并不存在。

To understand how basic elements of musicality such as pitch perception emerge and how they vary from person to person, it can be helpful to examine the stages of development across which people acquire musical skills. No prospect offers quite so much potential as the notion of studying infants as if they were musical blank slates, capable of defining the contours of their musical capacity before it is influenced by culture and experience. But infants have already been exposed to a complex soundscape in utero, ranging from the regular pulses of the mother’s heartbeat to voices and music in the surrounding environment. Newborns not only recognize their mother’s voice, but also melodies they heard frequently while in the womb. The sounds to which they have been exposed before birth shape infant musicality—thus no musical blank slate exists.

音乐能激发婴儿的兴趣。父母可以提供亲身经历，见证许多婴儿对音乐做出的全神贯注的凝视反应。大量研究表明，给婴儿唱歌可以减少烦躁。婴儿的感知系统使他们能够抽象出关于周围音乐环境的大量信息。六个月大的婴儿在乐句之间特定位置出现停顿时，会比在乐句中间随机出现停顿时，听音乐的时间更长——他们在一定程度上知道音乐应该如何进行。

Music intrigues infants. Parents can provide firsthand reports of the transfixed stare with which many babies respond to music, and numerous studies have shown that singing to babies reduces fussing. Infants’ perceptual systems allow them to abstract substantial information about their musical surroundings. Six-month-old infants listen longer to music when pauses occur in their typical location between phrases rather than at random midphrase moments—they know, to a certain extent, how the music should go.

但它们也具有极强的可塑性，能够适应不同的音乐体系。尽管在两个月大的婴儿身上就发现了对许多成年人认为悦耳的辅音音程的偏好，但其他研究表明，只要音乐不熟悉，六个月大的婴儿并不特别在意歌曲使用的是辅音还是不协和音程。在成年人中，对辅音的偏好很普遍，但并非普遍现象。一些克罗地亚乡村地区的民歌手会用平行二度音程互相伴奏，许多西方传统认为八度是最不和谐的音程之一。齐曼尼人（Tsimane'）是亚马逊地区的原住民部落，很少接触西方文化，他们认为协和音程和不协和音程同样悦耳。虽然西方成年人在使用西方音阶创作旋律时能更好地察觉旋律的变化，但婴儿同样擅长察觉使用西方音阶、爪哇佩洛格音阶或人工发明的音阶创作旋律的变化——只要它保留了将八度划分为不等音阶的特性，就像世界上大多数音阶系统一样。

But they are also remarkably malleable and able to adapt to different musical systems. Although a preference for the consonant intervals many adults identify as pleasant has been detected in infants as young as two months old, other studies show that so long as the music is not familiar, six-month-old babies do not particularly care whether a song uses consonant or dissonant intervals. Among adults, a preference for consonance is widespread, but not universal. Some Croatian folk singers in rural regions accompany one another using parallel seconds, considered by many Western traditions one of the most dissonant intervals. The Tsimane’, a native Amazonian tribe with little exposure to Western culture, rate consonant and dissonant intervals as equally pleasant. Although Western adults detect changes to melodies much better when they are composed using Western scales, infants are equally good at detecting changes to melodies composed using Western scales or the Javanese pelog scale or an artificial invented scale—so long as it retains the property of dividing the octave into unequal scale steps, as do most scale systems around the world.

婴儿的思维在音乐节拍方面同样具有可塑性。心理学家艾琳·汉农（Erin Hannon）和桑德拉·特雷胡布（Sandra Trehub）使用两种节拍类型评估了这种多样性。一种在西方大部分地区流行的是等时节拍——两个节拍之间的时间间隔相同；另一种在巴尔干民间音乐中常见的是非等时节拍——两个节拍之间的间隔在短时和长时之间交替变化。西方六个月大的婴儿能够轻松地察觉等时节拍和非等时节拍的变化，但西方成年人却无法察觉不熟悉的非等时节拍的变化。

Baby minds are equally plastic when it comes to musical timing. Psychologists Erin Hannon and Sandra Trehub assessed this versatility using two types of meter. One type, prevalent in much of the West, is isochronous—the same amount of time separates one beat from the next—and the other, common in the folk music of the Balkans, is nonisochronous—the distance between beats alternates between a shorter and a longer duration. Western six-month-old infants can detect changes just as easily in isochronous as nonisochronous meters, but Western adults are incapable of detecting changes in the unfamiliar nonisochronous meters.

在六个月到十二个月大的时候，婴儿会持续沉浸在他们自己的音乐文化中，感知系统也会开始自我修剪，重新分配未使用的感知能力，以便更专注于他们最常遇到的声音结构。因此，当西方十二个月大的婴儿接受同样的测试时，他们表现出与成年人一样的无力，无法察觉非等时节拍的变化。

Between six and twelve months of age, babies’ immersion in their own musical culture continues, and the perceptual system starts to prune itself, reallocating unused perceptual capacities to permit more specialization in the sound structures they encounter most frequently. Accordingly, when Western twelve-month-olds are tested on the same task, they demonstrate an adult-like inability to detect changes in nonisochronous meters.

然而，事情远比这复杂得多。这些12个月大的婴儿的父母拿到了一张10分钟的巴尔干民间音乐CD，并被要求在两周内每天给婴儿播放两次。两周后再次测试时，十二个月大的婴儿再次能够察觉等时和非等时节拍的变化。短期被动接触足以让他们重新获得处理非等时节拍所需的感知技能。另一方面，西方成年人即使认真听了同一张CD一两周，仍然无法察觉非等时节拍的变化。

Yet the story is a little more complicated. Parents of these twelve-month-olds were provided a ten-minute CD of Balkan folk music and instructed to play it for the babies twice a day over a two-week period. When retested at the end of this time, the twelve-month-olds were once more able to detect changes in both the isochronous and the nonisochronous meters. Short-term, passive exposure was sufficient for them to regain the perceptual skills necessary for handling nonisochronous meters. Western adults, on the other hand, even after they had diligently listened to the same CD for a week or two, remained unable to detect changes in nonisochronous meters.

婴儿期似乎展现了音乐可塑性的一个特殊窗口。正如婴儿能够学习他们接触到的任何语言一样，他们也能适应周围的任何音乐体系。正如成年人在可塑性窗口期过后学习新语言会更加困难一样，他们适应新的音乐体系也会更加困难。讽刺的是，那些想从音乐心理学研究中汲取经验教训的父母，可能不会像该领域的普遍观点那样，认为整天给宝宝播放莫扎特的音乐有益，而是认为接触各种各样的音乐风格或许能更好地利用婴儿大脑吸收不同音乐体系的能力。

Infancy seems to present a special window of musical plasticity. Just as babies can learn whatever language they are exposed to, they adapt to whatever musical system surrounds them. And just as adults have a harder time learning a new language once the window of plasticity has passed, they also have a harder time adjusting to a new musical system. Ironically, parents looking for a take-home lesson from research about music psychology might conclude not that it is beneficial to play your baby Mozart all day, as popular conceptions of the field might suggest, but rather that exposure to a wide range of musical styles might best take advantage of the infant mind’s capacity to absorb different musical systems.

其他音乐能力领域在发展过程中逐渐显现，其中较为普遍的音乐属性，例如节奏，通常较早习得；而那些在世界少数音乐体系中出现的音乐属性，例如和声，通常较晚习得。如果更多普遍的音乐属性能够充分利用感知系统的约束和可供性，那么这种模式是可以预料的——发育中的心智就能更早、更容易地适应这些特征。然而，几乎不可能从影响音乐实践普遍性程度的众多政治和历史因素中梳理出感知约束可能发挥的作用。

Other areas of musical competence emerge over the developmental span, with more universal musical attributes, such as rhythm, generally learned earlier, and musical attributes that appear in fewer of the world’s musical systems, such as harmony, generally learned later. This pattern would be expected if more of the universal musical attributes took the best advantage of the constraints and affordances of the perceptual system—the developing mind would then tune into these characteristics earlier and more easily. But it is almost impossible to tease out the possible role of perceptual constraints from the myriad political and historical factors that influence the degree of universality in musical practices.

与感知限制相关时预测的轨迹一致，儿童在他们培养对和声的敏感度。世界各地的音乐文化通常都以中心音高和音阶为特征，它们合在一起可能被认为构成一个调，但很少有西方音乐特有的和声结构（例如和弦的规则或音高一起演奏时的发音）。当接触到明显以错误调结尾的片段时，西方的四岁儿童认为它们听起来和以正确调结尾的片段一样好。然而，五岁儿童却一致认为它们更差。唱歌时，幼儿往往会在保持轮廓的同时从一个调游移到另一个调（他们会在适当的时候上下移动，但移动的幅度与调所要求的不一样）。对和声以及传统旋律所暗示的和弦的敏感度通常要到接近八岁才会形成。

Consistent with the trajectory predicted if perceptual limitations were relevant, children develop sensitivity to key before they develop sensitivity to harmony. It is common for musical cultures around the world to feature a central pitch and scale that together might be thought of as constituting a key, but rarer for them to feature the kind of harmonic structures (such as rules governing chords or the way pitches sound when played together) that are characteristic of Western music. When exposed to excerpts that flagrantly end in the wrong key, Western four-year-olds think they sound just as good as excerpts that end in the right key. Five-year-olds, however, consistently rate them as worse. When singing, young children tend to wander from one key to another while preserving the contour (they move up or down when appropriate, but by a different amount than mandated by the key). Sensitivity to harmony and the chords implied by conventional melodies does not generally develop until closer to the age of eight.

与节拍同步的能力甚至比表现调性与和声的能力出现得更早。幼儿经常跟着音乐跳舞，但他们的身体动作直到学龄前才能够始终与节拍保持一致。一些研究要求儿童跟着录制的音乐打拍子，结果表明，同步要到四岁才能稳定地实现。但随后的研究要求儿童与人类同伴一起打鼓而不是跟着录音打拍子，结果显示两岁半的儿童实际上已经能够同步。儿童与录音和与人类同伴同步成功率之间的差异凸显了使用切合实际、具有社会性且足够激励儿童以激发最佳表现的任务的重要性。一些人认为，这些不同的发现并非由于所呈现的任务不同，而是由于用于建模同步的统计数据和数学方法不同。这场争议指出，研究设计的各个方面在决定从中得出的结论方面都至关重要。

The ability to synchronize with a beat appears even earlier than the ability to represent key and harmony. Toddlers often dance along to music, but their body movements do not consistently align with the beat until the preschool years. Studies that asked children to tap along to recorded music suggested that synchronization does not happen reliably until age four, but subsequent studies that asked children to drum along with a human partner rather than tap to a recording revealed that two-and-a-half- year-old children actually can synchronize. The discrepancy between children’s synchronization success with recordings versus human partners underscores the importance of using tasks that are realistic, socially embedded, and sufficiently motivating to elicit top performance. Some people attribute the divergent findings not to a difference in the tasks presented, but to a difference in the statistics and mathematics used to model synchronization. This controversy points to the importance of all aspects of a study’s design in determining the conclusions that can be drawn from it.

关于幼儿情感体验音乐能力的研究也存在类似的限制。实验室研究系统地改变音乐特征并要求儿童标记所表达的情绪，结果表明学龄前儿童（3 至 4 岁）能够将节奏和响度与类似成人提供的情绪标签联系起来。然而，儿童要到 6 至 8 岁左右才能将调式变化（从小调到大调）与传统的情绪标签联系起来。但无论是在实验室中聆听音乐的体验，还是选择特定情绪标签的体验，都无法反映儿童通常与音乐互动的方式。例如，儿童在 3 至 4 岁之前就能对摇篮曲做出适当的反应。缓慢、安静的音乐能够抚慰他们，这很容易被认为是一种情绪反应。同样，身处自然社交环境中的幼儿，即使无法明确地标记情绪联想，他们也能获得听音乐时通常出现的情境线索，从而展现出比迄今为止研究结果更细致入微的面部表情，从而对音乐的表现力产生更深刻的理解。

Similar constraints hold for studies about the capacity of young children to experience music emotionally. Laboratory studies that systematically vary musical features and ask children to label the emotion being expressed demonstrate that preschoolers (ages three to four) can associate tempo and loudness with emotion labels similar to the ones adults provide. Not until children are closer to the age of six to eight, however, can they associate changes in mode (switching from minor to major) with conventional emotion labels. But neither the experience of listening to music in a laboratory nor of selecting a specific emotion label reflects the ways children ordinarily interact with music. Children exhibit appropriate responses to lullabies, for example, well before the age of three or four. The capacity of slow, quiet music to soothe them might easily be thought about as a kind of emotional response. Similarly, young children situated in natural social environments and given the kinds of contextual cues normally present when listening to music—even if they are unable to label emotional associations explicitly—might show facial expressions that indicate a more nuanced appreciation of music’s expressive character than studies have captured to date.

音乐训练的效果

The effects of musical training

音乐训练的概念涵盖了各种各样的体验，从正式的小提琴课和理论课，到凭听觉学习吉他、参加鼓圈演奏或参加音乐会。但第一种——古典传统的正式训练——是研究最深入的，部分原因是许多音乐心理学家都出身于这一传统，部分原因是它是一项独立且定义明确的活动，部分原因是它涉及一系列高要求、耗时的体力和脑力活动，与未进行这些活动的对照组相比，这些活动更有可能产生可衡量的认知变化。

The notion of musical training spans all kinds of experiences, from formal violin lessons and theory classes to learning the guitar by ear, playing in a drum circle, or attending concerts. But the first kind—formal training in the classical tradition—is the one that has been best studied, partly because it is the tradition out of which many psychologists of music emerged, partly because it is a discrete and well-defined endeavor, and partly because it involves a set of demanding, time-consuming physical and mental activities that make it likely to generate measurable cognitive changes in contrast to a control group that does not undertake them.

研究正规音乐训练的研究经常面临的挑战是，如何区分训练本身的影响和寻求音乐训练的人的影响，坚持下去，并且从一开始就有机会接触到它。大多数实验都是通过随机分配参与者到特定的治疗组来进行的，以避免选择性偏差。但是，将一些婴儿随机分配到一组，让他们在出生后的前十年接受音乐课程，而将其他婴儿随机分配到另一组，让他们明确禁止接受音乐课程，这既不道德（更不切实际）。

Studies investigating formal musical training often confront the challenge of disentangling the effects of the training itself from the effects of being the sort of person who seeks out musical training, sticks with it, and has access to it in the first place. Most experiments work by randomly assigning participants to a particular treatment group, to avoid selection bias. But it would not be ethical (let alone practical) to randomly assign some babies to a group that received music lessons over the first ten years of life and other babies to a group that was expressly not permitted to receive them.

相反，研究人员通常会尝试将两组儿童组成一个小组，让这些儿童在最有可能相关的特征上相匹配。在一项典型的研究中，他们会选取两组具有可比社会经济特征、基线智商得分和性格类型的儿童，并让其中一组儿童上音乐课，另一组儿童则进行某种控制活动。（事实证明，这种控制活动非常重要，因为与成人教师一起专注学习可以产生积极的影响，无论互动中是否存在音乐因素。）但即使在控制了参与者特征并选择了合适的控制活动后，两组之间仍有可能存在一些未被控制的未知的第三因素，从而导致这种影响，或者音乐课中除了音乐内容之外的某些方面导致了差异。

Instead, researchers often try to form two groups composed of children who are matched on the characteristics likeliest to be relevant. In a typical study, they take two groups of children with comparable socioeconomic characteristics, baseline IQ scores, and personality types and provide one group with music lessons and another with some kind of control activity. (This control activity turns out to be important, since focused time with an adult instructor can have a positive impact, independent of any musical component to the interaction.) But even when controlling for participant characteristics and even when selecting a good control activity, it is possible that some unknown third factor not controlled for between the groups is driving the effect, or that some aspect of the music lesson other than its particularly musical content is responsible for any differences.

尽管研究存在这些局限性，但研究往往发现音乐课可以提高多项非音乐能力，包括听觉工作记忆和执行功能、阅读理解、智商和学习成绩。最有力的证据支持音乐训练对言语感知的影响。接受过音乐训练的人更善于在嘈杂的环境中听清言语，更善于判断外语中的两句话是否相同，更善于仅从韵律（实际音素内容模糊后残留的语音旋律，使单词不再清晰）来直觉说话者的情感。接受过音乐训练的儿童表现出更好的语音意识——即集中注意力和操纵的能力构成语言基础的声音单位。这些已报道的对语音感知的影响，得到了关于其潜在机制的清晰理论的进一步支持。西北大学尼娜·克劳斯实验室的研究表明，接受过音乐训练的人的脑干神经元能够更准确地追踪音高。不难想象，更忠实的音高表征可能会增强语音意识，进而影响阅读技能。

Studies—albeit ones that suffer from these limitations—have tended to find that music lessons can result in improvements on several nonmusical tasks, ranging from auditory working memory and executive functioning to reading comprehension, IQ, and school performance. The strongest body of evidence supports the impact of music training on speech perception. People who have had musical training are better at hearing speech in a noisy environment, at determining whether two sentences in a foreign language are the same or different, and at intuiting a speaker’s emotion purely from the prosody (the speech melody left over when the actual phonemic content is blurred so that the words are no longer distinct). Children with musical training show better phonological awareness—the ability to focus on and manipulate the sound units that form the basis of a language. These reported effects on speech perception are further supported by clear theory about the mechanisms that underlie them. Work in Nina Kraus’s lab at Northwestern University has demonstrated that neurons in the brainstem track pitch more accurately in people with musical training. It is easy to imagine how more faithful representations of pitch might enhance phonological awareness, which, in turn, influences reading skills.

人们常常从数学的角度来研究音乐——例如，建立音高和节拍的量化模型。追溯到毕达哥拉斯，关于音乐与数字之间关系的近乎神秘的观念一直影响着许多人的想象力，促使大量研究旨在探究音乐训练对数学能力的影响。然而，所有这些研究几乎没有找到证据表明正规的音乐课程能够影响数学敏锐度。同样，尽管有大量研究，但几乎没有证据表明音乐训练能够影响情商。

Music has often been studied from the perspective of mathematics—generating quantitative models of pitch and timing, for example. Stretching back to Pythagoras, quasi-mystical notions about the relationship between music and numbers have held sway over many an imagination, prompting a significant body of research aimed at identifying the impact of musical training on mathematical ability. Yet all this work has produced little evidence that formal lessons in music affect mathematical acumen. Similarly, despite numerous studies, little evidence exists that musical training affects emotional intelligence.

个体差异

Individual differences

尽管早期许多关于音乐训练效果的研究都将“音乐家”与“非音乐家”进行了对比，但这些术语似乎并不理想。大多数研究中提到的“音乐家”指的是“接受过西方古典传统正规训练的人”。“非音乐家”仅仅指未接受过此类训练的人。这些分类掩盖了一个事实：许多被贴上“非音乐家”标签的人其实以其他方式深入地参与音乐——例如，管理精心收藏的唱片，自学斯卡音乐（Ska），或者以音乐评论家或DJ等职业音乐人的身份赚钱。

Although much of the early work on the effect of musical training contrasted a group termed “musicians” with a group termed “nonmusicians,” these terms do not seem ideal. By “musician,” most of these studies meant “person with formal training in the Western classical tradition.” “Nonmusician” simply meant someone without such training. These categories obscured the fact that many people labeled “nonmusicians” engage deeply with music in other ways—stewarding elaborate record collections, for example, teaching themselves everything there is to know about ska, or actually earning money as a music professional, for instance as a music critic or DJ.

音乐能力和行为的个体差异远远超出了正规训练（或缺乏正规训练）的范围。音乐心理学只有通过对比其他类型的差异才有可能取得进步——例如，通过耳朵训练的人和通过乐谱训练的人之间的差异，或者贪婪聆听的人和不寻求音乐体验的人之间的差异。

Individual differences in musical abilities and behaviors extend far beyond the categories of formal training (or the lack thereof). The psychology of music is likely to progress only by contrasting other kinds of difference—between people trained by ear and people trained with notation, for example, or between people who listen voraciously and people who do not seek out musical experiences.

自2010年以来，研究人员开始开发工具，以更精细的分辨率表征这些个体差异。音乐吸收量表（AIMS）通过测量个体对以下陈述的认同程度来评估他们被音乐吸引的总体易感性，例如“我会停下手头的一切，去聆听一首特别的歌曲/乐曲”以及“有时听音乐时，我感觉我的思维仿佛能理解整个世界”。研究表明，个体的AIMS分数可以预测他们对音乐的情绪反应强度，以及他们在听音乐时想象叙事的倾向。

Since 2010, researchers have begun developing tools for characterizing these individual differences with finer resolution. The Absorption in Music Scale (AIMS) scores individuals on their general susceptibility to being captivated by listening to music by measuring their agreement with such statements as, “I will stop everything that I’m doing in order to listen to a special song/piece of music that is playing,” and “Sometimes when listening to music I feel as if my mind can understand the whole world.” An individual’s AIMS score has been shown to predict the intensity of their emotional response to music and their tendency to imagine narratives while listening.

金史密斯音乐素养指数 (Gold-MSI) 采用类似的自评量表，并辅以一系列听力测试，以评估个体在音乐素养方面的差异，其评估方式远超个体是否接受过正规训练。Gold-MSI 的评估内容包括：个人在音乐上投入的时间和资源；感知能力的自评评估；以及听力测试，用于评估音乐记忆、节拍感知、同步性和感知声音变化的能力；音乐训练；歌唱能力；以及与音乐产生情感共鸣的能力。在一篇题为《非音乐家的音乐性》的论文中，心理学家 Daniel Müllensiefen 及其同事使用 Gold-MSI 展示了未接受过正规训练的人们在音乐行为和天赋方面的广泛差异。

The Goldsmiths Musical Sophistication Index (Gold-MSI) uses a similar self-report inventory, supplemented by a battery of listening tests, to assess individual differences in musical sophistication in ways that move beyond whether a person has been formally trained. The Gold-MSI includes questions about the extent of time and resources the individual commits to music; self-report assessments about perceptual abilities, as well as listening tests that assess musical memory, beat perception, synchronization, and the capacity to detect changes in sound; musical training; singing ability; and the capacity for engaging emotionally with music. In a paper provocatively titled “The Musicality of Non-Musicians,” psychologist Daniel Müllensiefen and colleagues use the Gold-MSI to demonstrate the vast range of musical behaviors and aptitudes that differentiate people without formal training.

心理学对音乐才能个体差异的研究历史表明，那些看似客观、纯科学的研究，其根源在于文化音乐的概念。如果正规的乐器演奏训练不被优先考虑作为音乐才能的试金石，我们或许会看到大量的研究，探讨的是沉迷于聆听音乐的效果，而不是练习乐器的效果。被编码成变量并被研究的行为和倾向，取决于社会对它们的观念和评价。因此，如果没有人文学者的深入参与，音乐心理学的发展就无法进行。深入思考音乐理念、实践和假设如何影响音乐心理学家研究的主题和变量，以及如何解读和理解音乐心理学的研究结果，至关重要。

The history of psychology’s treatment of individual differences in musicality reveals the degree to which studies that might appear objective and purely scientific have their origin in cultural conceptions of music. If formal training in playing an instrument were not prioritized as a litmus test for musicianship, we might have seen a bevy of studies investigating the effects of avid musical listening rather than the effects of practicing an instrument. The behaviors and dispositions that get encoded into variables and studied are dependent on society’s conceptions and valuations of them. For this reason, the psychology of music cannot proceed without the deep involvement of humanists. It is imperative to think deeply about the ways that musical ideas, practices, and assumptions affect the topics and variables music psychologists study and the ways that findings in the psychology of music are interpreted and understood.

特殊的音乐能力

Special musical abilities

音乐领域个体差异的极端例子尤其引人入胜。那些年纪轻轻便达到惊人造诣的音乐神童，或许能够挑战人们对音乐思维运作方式的种种假设。阿尔玛·多伊彻出生于2005年，十岁时便创作了一部完整的小提琴协奏曲和一部完整的歌剧，这不禁让人想起250年前最著名的神童沃尔夫冈·阿马德乌斯·莫扎特，他七岁时就创作了他的第一部交响曲。

The extreme ends of the spectrum of individual differences in music make especially interesting cases. Musical prodigies, who attain startling mastery at a young age, can challenge assumptions about the workings of the musical mind. Born in 2005, Alma Deutscher had composed a full-length violin concerto and a full-length opera by the age of ten, calling to mind that most famous of child prodigies, Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart, born 250 years earlier, who wrote his first symphony at the age of seven.

多伊彻和莫扎特都拥有绝对音高，早年通过热爱音乐的父母接触音乐，早年接受作曲和即兴创作的训练，早年积累了大量的音乐创作时间（多伊彻在家接受教育），并且似乎对音乐创作有着真正的热爱。除了在孩提时代创作或演奏冗长复杂的音乐所需的惊人的感知、认知、执行和运动技能之外，创作出富有表现力、令人信服的音乐的能力似乎对音乐运作的一般概念构成了极大的挑战。如果音乐能够表达一些最微妙、最难以表达的情感体验层次，那么孩子们又如何能够创作出动人的乐章呢？没有几十年的狂喜和失望，怎么可能写出这样的作品？像诗歌这样依赖成熟度的领域，天才并不多见。

Deutscher and Mozart share the capacity for absolute pitch, early exposure to music through a parent who is an avid musician, early training in composition and improvisation, the early accumulation of many hours devoted to music (Deutscher is homeschooled), and an apparently genuine delight in music making. Aside from the astounding perceptual, cognitive, executive, and motor skills required to compose or perform lengthy, sophisticated music as a child, the ability to create expressively convincing music seems particularly challenging to ordinary conceptions of how music works. If music articulates some of the subtlest and most difficult to express layers of emotional experience, how can children compose moving passages without the benefit of decades of ecstasies and disappointments? Prodigies do not readily emerge in fields like poetry that rely on this kind of maturity.

音乐天才——认知功能低下却能展现出掩盖其其他缺陷的音乐才华的人——展现出一种截然不同但同样令人惊叹的音乐天赋。钢琴家雷克斯·刘易斯-克拉克和德里克·帕拉维奇尼都是盲人，并且都患有严重的认知障碍，导致日常活动困难，但他们却拥有极其精准的绝对音感和音乐天赋，这让他们不仅能够弹钢琴，还能即兴演奏，甚至可以听一首歌，然后像练习多年一样弹奏出来。一些研究人员认为，语言和视力缺陷可能使更多的大脑区域被分配用于听觉处理。此外，在缺乏其他刺激的情况下，音乐天才可能从很小的时候就开始投入异常多的时间在乐器上。网上的视频显示，雷克斯·刘易斯-克拉克蹒跚学步时，在键盘旁睡着了，一只小胳膊继续抓着琴键，试图摆脱这种感觉。

Musical savants—individuals with low cognitive functioning who can nevertheless perform the kind of musical feats that would seem to belie their other disabilities—exhibit a different but equally stunning kind of musical aptitude. Pianists Rex Lewis-Clack and Derek Paravicini are blind and share serious cognitive disabilities that make every day functioning difficult, yet they also possess an extremely accurate sense for absolute pitch and the kind of musical ability that enables them not just to play the piano, but also to improvise, and to hear a song once and play it back as if they had studied it for years. Some researchers have suggested that speech and vision deficits might permit more brain areas to be co-opted for auditory processing. Moreover, in the absence of other kinds of stimuli, savants may spend a truly unusual amount of time at an instrument from a very young age. Videos online show Rex Lewis-Clack as a toddler, falling asleep next to his keyboard, one little arm resisting oblivion by continuing to grasp at the keys.

威廉姆斯综合征是一种遗传性发育障碍，患者通常智商低下、学习困难、数学和空间推理能力下降，但语言和音乐能力却异常出色，并且对他人表现出热情外向的性格。患有威廉姆斯综合征的儿童通常对音乐非常感兴趣，尤其对音乐的情感内容敏感。

One genetic developmental disorder, Williams syndrome, tends to involve low IQ, learning difficulties, and problems with math and spatial reasoning, but carries with it heightened performance in language and music, as well as an exuberant, extroverted orientation to other people. Children with Williams syndrome are often highly interested in music, and especially sensitive to its emotional content.

这些音乐天赋的闪光点出现在意想不到的地方——无论是在年幼时出现，还是伴随其他类型的缺陷——都为理解音乐思维的局限性和潜力提供了机会。它也提醒我们，音乐天赋涵盖了一系列不同的行为和态度。一个自闭症儿童能够说出一个音符中的所有音符，十三音和弦却演奏出很少的富有表现力的音调，这与患有威廉姆斯综合症的孩子在听到舒伯特的歌曲时流泪相比，是音乐性的不同部分。

The appearance of these streaks of musical ability in unexpected places—emerging at a young age or alongside other kinds of deficits—provides opportunities for understanding the limits and potential of the musical mind. It also serves as a reminder that musicality encompasses a range of different behaviors and attitudes. The autistic child who can name all the notes in a thirteen-voice chord yet plays with little expressive inflection is tapping into a different part of musicality than the child with Williams syndrome who finds herself tearing up in response to a Schubert song.

特殊的音乐缺陷

Special musical deficits

人们更有可能抱怨自己缺乏音乐天赋，而不是吹嘘自己拥有特殊的音乐天赋。超过15%的人声称自己五音不全，尽管根据对失乐症最宽泛的定义——一种影响音调处理的临床疾病——仅占总人口的不到5%。

People are more likely to complain that they suffer from a musical deficit than brag that they are gifted with a special musical ability. More than 15 percent of the population alleges that they are tone deaf, even though the most liberal definition of amusia—a clinical disorder affecting pitch processing—implicates less than 5 percent of the population.

是什么导致了这种过度悲观的自我诊断？一方面，西方文化比世界上大多数文化更倾向于将音乐表演归为专家的领域。在西方古典音乐传统之外，音乐创作更常见的是让每个人都参与其中，而不是将表演者和观众分成不同的群体。人们倾向于否认自己的音乐能力，这可能源于这种对专业人士的盲目崇拜。另一方面，人们称自己为五音不全，可能不是因为他们在感知音高方面有问题，而是因为他们在发出音高方面有问题——当他们觉得自己“唱不出来”的时候。唱得不好可能是由于与音高感知完全无关的运动计划问题造成的。

What accounts for the overly pessimistic self-diagnoses? On the one hand, Western culture relegates music performance to the domain of specialists more so than most cultures around the world. Outside the Western classical tradition, it is more common for music making to involve everyone as participants, rather than to divide the performer and the audience into separate groups. People’s tendency to disavow their own musical competence might stem from this fetishization of the professional. On the other hand, people may refer to themselves as tone deaf not when they have a problem perceiving pitch, but when they have a problem producing it—when they feel they “can’t hold a tune.” Poor singing can arise from problems with motor planning that do not relate to pitch perception at all.

失乐症的临床测试需要聆听几段旋律，其中一些旋律的音调发生了变化，普通听众会觉得这些变化非常明显。失乐症患者被要求判断这些旋律是否相同或不同，但却无法正确回答。有趣的是，这种精细音调感知的缺陷与失语症（一种言语处理障碍）是分开发生的。失乐症患者通常能够很好地理解语言的韵律——他们知道什么时候例如，句子用作疑问句或表达不赞同。然而，当语音被模糊处理，只剩下话语的旋律时，失乐症患者就会出现困难。这种对比表明，他们可能依赖音高之外的平行信息流在现实世界的语音环境中发挥作用。虽然对语音感知的影响微乎其微，但他们在音高处理方面的困难确实会带来其他重要后果。它会影响更广泛的认知能力，例如音乐记忆，并可能产生强大的社会效应，因为失乐症患者无法识别熟悉的曲调，也无法依靠朋友的面部表情来判断是否弹错了音符。

The clinical test for amusia involves listening to pairs of melodies, some of which include a change to one pitch that ordinary listeners find egregious. Tasked with saying whether the melodies are the same or different, amusics find themselves unable to answer correctly. Intriguingly, this deficit in fine-grained pitch perception occurs separately from aphasia, a speech processing disorder. People with amusia can generally understand the prosodic aspects of language just fine—they know when a sentence is serving as a question or expressing disapproval, for example. Yet when the speech sounds are blurred out, leaving only the melody of the utterance, amusics struggle. This contrast suggests that they probably rely on parallel information streams outside of pitch to function in real-world speech contexts. Although the consequences for speech perception are minimal, their struggle with pitch processing does have other important consequences. It affects broader cognitive abilities such as musical memory, and can have powerful social effects, as people with amusia fail to recognize familiar tunes or rely on friends’ facial expressions to know whether a wrong note was played or not.

虽然失乐症会导致音乐享受感下降，但音乐快感缺乏症（即无法从音乐中获得愉悦感）也可能独立于音调处理问题而发生。患有音乐快感缺乏症的人能够正常感知音乐，并且拥有完整且未受损的奖赏回路。他们能够从其他活动中获得愉悦，但却无法被音乐感动或愉悦。他们不会表现出典型的生理反应，并且普遍缺乏对音乐的兴趣——他们不会在Spotify上创建播放列表，也不会收听广播。最近的神经影像学研究表明，对音乐特别热爱的人，其听觉皮层和皮层下奖赏网络之间的连接性更强，而患有音乐快感缺乏症的人，这两个区域之间的连接性则较弱。换句话说，无法从音乐中获得愉悦感的人，尽管他们拥有功能齐全的声音处理中心和愉悦中心，但可能缺乏这两个区域之间的联系，而这种联系使得他们无法感受到音乐带来的兴奋。

Although amusia can result in diminished musical enjoyment, musical anhedonia—a general failure to derive pleasure from music—also occurs independent of any problem with pitch processing. People with musical anhedonia perceive music normally, and possess intact, undamaged reward circuitry. They are able to derive pleasure from other activities, but find themselves incapable of being moved or pleased by music. They do not show typical physiological responses to it, and report a general lack of musical interest—they do not create playlists in Spotify or listen to the radio. Recent neuroimaging work showed that people who are especially passionate about music possess greater connectivity between the auditory cortex and the subcortical reward network, whereas people with musical anhedonia show reduced connectivity between these regions. In other words, people unable to derive pleasure from music, although they have perfectly competent sound processing centers and pleasure centers, may lack the linkage between the two regions that would enable feeling thrilled by music.

第七章

Chapter 7

对音乐的渴望

The appetite for music

音乐似乎引人入胜，是我们生活中不可或缺的一部分，然而，这些情感维度恰恰是最难以理解的。研究音乐记忆之类的东西相对简单，只需在各种情境下处理音乐片段，测试人们是否记得住它们；而研究音乐如何触动我们，则需要更深入的思考。这也为音乐心理学的研究提供了一个独特的机遇。

Music can seem captivating and integral to our lives, yet these affective dimensions are precisely the ones for which under-standing remains most elusive. It is relatively straightforward to study something like musical memory by manipulating excerpts in various situations and testing whether people remember them; studying the way music moves us requires deeper thought. It also represents a unique opportunity for the psychology of music.

描述音乐体验中引人入胜、感人至深和情感丰富的方面，这一挑战超越了心理学的范畴；音乐学和哲学一直在努力寻找合适的概念来构建这些体验，就像日常听众难以描述他们在音乐会上的强烈体验一样。音乐心理学对这个问题的普遍处理方式或许令人失望——研究通常会操纵音乐体验的各个方面，并测量一些不太令人满意的情绪反应指标。例如，一项典型的研究可能会改变某些音乐特征，例如一首曲子是大调还是小调，或者听众是在挤满其他人的房间里还是独自一人聆听，并要求参与者以1到7的等级来评价这段片段的快乐或悲伤程度。显然，促成深刻音乐体验的主要因素并非情态（无论是深度音乐体验的本质并不在于判断乐曲是大调还是小调，也不在于是否有其他听众，而在于它能否将乐曲判定为快乐或悲伤。但正是这些研究提供了细小、不完整但易于理解的洞见，才使得它们能够展开对话，从而加深理解。当一位试图阐明音乐体验的哲学家遇到这样的研究时，她可以利用它来挖掘原本难以探索的负面空间。通过反驳“深度音乐体验可以通过询问快乐和悲伤的标签来衡量”的观点，她为自己的论点提供了素材——这些研究又可以激发心理学家进行进一步的研究，而这些研究又反过来启发哲学家提出更精细的理论，如此反复，直到一个看似无法克服的问题通过从两端逐步解决而得到解决。

The challenge of characterizing the engrossing, moving, and emotional aspects of musical experience extends beyond psychology; musicology and philosophy have struggled to find adequate concepts for framing them, just as everyday listeners can struggle to describe a powerful experience they had at a concert. Music psychology’s general approach to this problem might seem disappointing—studies often manipulate individual aspects of the musical experience and measure some unsatisfactory proxy for emotional response. For example, a typical study might alter some musical feature, like whether a piece is in a major or a minor key, or whether the listener heard it in a room filled with other people or in isolation, and ask participants to rate how happy or sad the excerpt seemed on a scale from 1 to 7. Clearly, the primary factors that conspire to generate deep musical experiences are not modality (whether a piece is in major or minor) or the presence or absence of other listeners, and the primary characteristic of a deep musical experience is not identifying a piece as happy or sad. But it is precisely the way that these studies offer small, incomplete, and yet tractable nuggets of insight that can propel them into a dialogue that drives understanding forward. When a philosopher seeking to illuminate musical experience encounters a study like this, she can use it to carve into negative space that is otherwise difficult to explore. By pushing back against the notion that a deep musical experience can be assayed by asking about happy and sad labels, she provides grist to her own arguments—which then can spark psychologists to do additional studies, which, in turn, inspire even more finely hewn theories from the philosopher, and so on until a seemingly insurmountable problem has been solved by working it, incrementally, from both ends.

对音乐的情感反应

Emotional responses to music

并非所有难以言喻的音乐体验都与情感相关。一个人可能会发现自己被一段音乐深深吸引——变得警觉、专注、充满兴趣——但实际上并没有体验到任何情感。但对许多人来说，音乐能够触及内心深处，激发出复杂而真实的情感，这在他们生活中占据着重要的地位。

Not all difficult-to-articulate musical experiences are emotional. A person might find herself gripped by a piece of music—alert, attentive, and interested—without experiencing an emotion per se. But for many people, music’s capacity to reach inside of them and coax out complex, real emotions is an important part of its place in their lives.

8.孩子在听《彼得与狼》时有强烈的情感反应。

8. A child has a strong emotional response while listening to Peter and the Wolf.

区分两种体验至关重要。一方面，音乐可以唤起情感。听歌可以让人悲伤落泪，或体验到无比的喜悦。但有时，听歌并非真正体验某种情绪状态，而可能仅仅让人意识到音乐表达的是悲伤或喜悦。虽然这两种反应都很有趣，但第一种反应在音乐心理学中受到了更多关注，因为它本身就令人费解。情绪通常由与个人目标相关的明确事件激发。例如，被抛弃的前景可能会引发悲伤，而和解的希望则可能引发喜悦。音乐无法抛弃他人，也无法与他人和解。它似乎没有携带任何与目标相关的物体，因此无法引发情感反应。

It is important to distinguish between two kinds of experiences. On the one hand, music can evoke emotion. Listening to a song can lead a person to weep in sorrow or to experience great joy. But sometimes, rather than actually experiencing an emotional state, listening to a song might lead a person merely to recognize that the music is expressive of sorrow or joy. Although both of these responses are interesting, the first has received more attention from music psychology because it is so puzzling. Emotions are usually inspired by clear events relevant to a person’s goals. For example, sorrow might be elicited by the prospect of abandonment and joy by the hope of reconciliation. Music cannot abandon someone or reconcile with them. It seems to carry no goal-relevant object that would render it capable of triggering an emotional response.

这一根本谜团激发了人们探索音乐引发情绪的机制。瑞典心理学家帕特里克·尤斯林（Patrik Juslin）和丹尼尔·瓦斯特菲耶尔（Daniel Västfjäll）对此进行了简明扼要的总结。最基本的原理是，突然出现、响亮或令人不快的声音能够触发脑干反射，这种反射旨在调节对可能构成迫在眉睫威胁的事件的觉醒。即使听众可能很清楚响亮的弦乐不会带来危险，但这种固有的系统会提前发挥作用，让人们做好应对的准备，即使在最终可能无害的情况下也能做出反应——这类似于跑步者发现一根散落的树枝，会引发惊吓反应，然后反应更迟钝、更理性的认知系统才会介入，判断它不是蛇。

This fundamental mystery has inspired an effort to specify the mechanisms through which music might elicit emotion, an effort summarized concisely by Swedish psychologists Patrik Juslin and Daniel Västfjäll. Most basically, sounds that are sudden, loud, or unpleasant can trigger a brainstem reflex meant to modulate arousal in response to events that could pose an imminent threat. Even though a listener may well be aware that a loud chord presents no danger, this hardwired system works pre-attentively, readying a person to respond even in situations that might ultimately prove innocuous—similar to the way a stray stick spotted by a runner can evoke a startle response before slower, more reasoned cognitive systems intervene to register that it is not a snake.

除了利用原始神经系统发出危险信号外，音乐还能唤起现实世界中的某种联想——并非音乐本身——这种联想可能通过评价性条件反射和情景记忆引发情感。青少年时期每年夏天在篝火旁播放的歌曲，多年后会引发强烈的怀旧之情。偶然听到一首在过去的恋情中占据重要地位的曲子，会将与那个人相关的所有情感涌上心头。在这些情况下，情感的对象并非音乐本身，而是它所唤起的现实生活中的人或事。由于这种音乐之外的来源，音乐心理学家往往对音乐情绪的评价性条件反射机制不太感兴趣，认为音乐本身只起着边缘作用。但这种假设忽略了两个值得进一步研究的有趣方面。

Aside from harnessing primitive neural systems to signal peril, music can conjure up the kind of real-world association—not of itself musical—that might elicit emotion via evaluative conditioning and episodic memory. Songs played around a campfire every summer during a person’s teenage years can elicit powerful nostalgia years later. Casually overhearing a tune that figured prominently in a past relationship can bring all the emotions associated with that person flooding back. In these cases, the object of the emotion is not the music itself, so much as the real-life person or event it conjures up. Because of this extramusical source, music psychologists have tended to be less interested in the evaluative conditioning mechanism for musical emotions, thinking that the music itself plays only a peripheral role. But this assumption overlooks two intriguing aspects worthy of further study.

首先，声音为何如此轻易地与它所处的生活境遇产生如此强烈的关联？最近的研究表明，音乐比熟悉的面孔更能唤起生动的自传体记忆。加州大学戴维斯分校的心理学家 Petr Janata 给受试者播放他们青春期的热门歌曲时，受试者报告称，特定的自传体记忆与大多数熟悉的歌曲产生了联系。神经影像学显示，聆听青少年时期的流行歌曲并回忆相关记忆的行为依赖于内侧前额叶皮质的活动，而这个区域的功能往往在阿尔茨海默病进展到晚期时仍能保留。该区域在音乐与记忆关联中的核心地位或许有助于解释为什么播放阿尔茨海默病患者青春期的音乐有时能够改善这些患者的记忆力和注意力。

First, how does sound so easily take on such powerful associations with the life circumstances in which it was encountered? Recent work shows that music evokes more vivid autobiographical memories than familiar faces. When University of California at Davis psychologist Petr Janata played people chart-topping songs from their adolescence, they reported associating specific autobiographical memories with most of the familiar songs. Neuroimaging showed that the act of listening to popular songs from their teenage years and recalling associated memories depended on activity in the medial prefrontal cortex, a region whose functioning tends to be preserved even late into the progression of Alzheimer’s disease. This region’s centrality in the music-memory link may help explain why playing music from the adolescence of a person with Alzheimer’s can sometimes elicit improved memory and attention in these patients.

其次，音乐如何放大这些联想所引发的情绪，从而创造出一种特殊的、高度唤醒的状态，使情绪比其他情况下更加强烈地表现出来？我最喜欢的例子是这源于他们在密歇根州一个为期八周的音乐营因特洛肯度过的初中和高中暑假。营员们在暑假的最后一晚总会演奏李斯特的《前奏曲》，然后指挥家会放下指挥棒，宣布该学年的营结束。所有营员过去常常挤在一起度过演出，为即将离开而哭泣。几十年来，尽管明确地想到因特洛肯已经不再能唤起任何怀旧之情，但当收音机里不请自来地播放出它独特的主题曲时，仍然会让人感到寒冷和流泪。当公开地回忆青春期的暑假只会让人耸耸肩，而音乐引起的间接联想却能引发充分的情感时，音乐显然不仅仅是指向一段人生经历。

Second, how does music amplify the emotions elicited by these associations to create a special, high-arousal state in which the emotions manifest themselves even more powerfully than they might in other circumstances? My own favorite example of this comes from junior high and high school summers spent at Interlochen, an eight-week music camp in Michigan where the final night was always marked by a performance of Liszt’s Les Preludes, after which the conductor broke the baton to signal the end of that year’s session. All the campers used to spend the performance huddled together, weeping at the prospect of leaving. For several decades, well past the point when thinking explicitly about Interlochen could conjure up any nostalgia, the emergence of its distinctive theme, unbidden on the radio, could still trigger chills and tears. When overt thoughts about adolescent summers elicit only shrugs, but oblique associations raised by music elicit full-blown emotions, the music is clearly contributing more than merely pointing to a life experience.

除了脑干反射和评估性条件反射之外，Juslin 和 Västfjäll 提出的第三种机制是情绪感染。当人们看到表情流露出特定情绪的面孔时，他们自己的面部肌肉常常会不由自主地扭曲，形成一个微妙的共鸣镜像。当他们听到表达特定情绪的声音（例如，低沉、缓慢、间或停顿）时，他们会想象自己的声音也以这种方式移动，这可能会诱发相关的潜在状态（悲伤）。在猴子运动前皮层中发现的镜像神经元——这种神经元不仅在动物做出某个动作时会激活，而且在它看到或听到其他人做同样的事情时也会激活——支持了这样一个假设：大脑中存在一个网络，用于将感知到的人类行为转化为想象或执行的人类行为。音乐可以利用这个系统，通过创造夸张表达性声音特征的声音（例如，播放速度比人类说话时更低沉、更慢的声音），从而诱发一种特别激动的情绪状态。

In addition to brainstem reflexes and evaluative conditioning, a third mechanism proposed by Juslin and Västfjäll is emotional contagion. When people see faces expressive of a particular emotion, their own facial muscles often contort themselves involuntarily into a subtle sympathetic mirror.
