When they hear voices expressive of a particular emotion (low, slow, and punctuated by pauses, for example), they imagine their own voice moving this way, potentially inducing the associated underlying state (sadness). The discovery of mirror neurons in the monkey premotor cortex—neurons that fire not only when the animal performs an action, but also when it sees or hears someone else do it—bolsters the hypothesis that a brain network exists to support translating perceived human action into imagined or performed human action. Music may take advantage of this system by creating sounds that exaggerate the characteristics of the expressive voice—playing lower and slower than a human could speak, for example—inducing an especially charged emotional state.

音乐也可能通过触发视觉意象来引发情绪。人们很容易在音乐的刺激下产生视觉意象和想象的故事。最近的一项研究表明，近60%的观看管弦乐片段的受试者表示，他们想象出了一个故事或故事的某些元素。这些图像和故事反过来又能引发情感。与评价性条件反射类似，这种机制依赖于音乐唤起音乐之外的联想的能力，而这些联想可以触发情绪反应。这引出了一系列重要的研究问题。这些联想是如何产生的？它们是源于一种固有的倾向，即倾向于用图像和故事来理解抽象领域，还是特定的文化体验促使听众以这种方式聆听音乐？电影中无处不在的音乐与影像的搭配在塑造这种反应方面扮演了什么角色？当听众体验到音乐之外的联想时，这种联想在多大程度上倾向于视觉化？

Music may also elicit emotions by triggering visual imagery. People generate visual imagery and imagined stories easily in response to music. In a recent study, almost 60 percent of people presented with excerpts of orchestral music reported imagining a story or elements of a story. These images and stories can, in turn, elicit emotion. Like evaluative conditioning, this mechanism relies on music’s capacity to conjure up extramusical associations that can serve as triggers for emotional response. It raises a host of important research questions. How do these associations emerge? Do they stem from an inherent tendency to understand abstract domains in terms of images and stories or do particular cultural experiences encourage listeners to hear music this way? What role does film’s pervasive pairing of music and imagery play in shaping this response? When listeners experience an extramusical association, to what degree does the association tend to be visual?

这些机制大多依赖于音乐与非音乐实体的纠缠——音乐能够指涉特定的体验、事物或社会群体。然而，有一种机制——音乐预期——更依赖于纯粹的声音层面。该理论由伦纳德·迈耶于20世纪50年代首次提出，将音乐中的惊喜时刻与情感和表达体验联系起来。即使没有接受过正规训练的听众，也会随着音乐的进展预期到特定的延续。通过偏离这些预期——跳到一个遥远的音符或跳出调性——音乐可以产生张力和强烈的表现力。

Most of these mechanisms rely on music’s entanglement with nonmusical entities—the way music can reference particular experiences or objects or social groups. However, one mechanism—musical expectancy—depends more exclusively on the purely sonic aspects. This theory, first developed by Leonard Meyer in the 1950s, links moments of musical surprise with experiences of emotion and expressivity. Even listeners without formal training anticipate particular continuations as the music progresses. By deviating from these expectations—leaping to a far-away note or stepping out of the key—music can generate tension and expressive intensity.

音乐带来的情绪反应多种多样，从短暂的辛酸到强烈而持久的蜕变。大约50%的人表示，他们在听音乐时体验过寒意。寒意指的是一种愉悦的、脊背发凉或刺痛的感觉。鸡皮疙瘩会蔓延到整个躯干，手臂上的汗毛也会竖起来。容易产生音乐寒意的人通常不会被过山车、跳伞或极限运动所吸引。似乎对一些人来说，换个调就足以产生一种狂喜的感觉，而对另一些人来说，可能需要跳伞才能达到这种程度。

Emotional responses to music can range from a momentary sense of poignancy to a powerful and long-lasting transformative state. About 50 percent of people say that they have experienced chills while listening to music. Chills involve a pleasurable sense of shivers down the spine or tingling. Goosebumps spread across the torso and arm hairs stand on end. People prone to musical chills do not tend to be drawn to roller coasters or skydiving or extreme sports. It seems that for some, a change of key suffices to generate a sense of ecstatic transport, while others might need to jump out of a plane.

虽然贝多芬的音乐或许能让一位听众感到毛骨悚然，而猫王的音乐又能让另一位听众感到毛骨悚然，但这些令人毛骨悚然的时刻往往具有一些共同的特征。最常见的情况是，音乐突然从轻柔转为响亮，或从一个调性突然切换到另一个调性，或者加入了一件新乐器，又或者音域突然发生变化（从低到高，或从高到低）。神经影像学研究表明，音乐带来的毛骨悚然取决于大脑中其他欣快体验背后的区域。

Although Beethoven might trigger chills reliably for one listener and Elvis for another, the chills-inducing moments tend to share certain characteristics. Most often, they involve a sudden change from soft to loud or from one key to another, or the addition of a new instrument, or a sudden shift in range (from low to high or vice versa). Neuroimaging studies show that musical chills depend on the brain regions that underlie other euphoric experiences.

欣快感似乎是一个强有力的描述，但人们可以维持真正令人欣喜的音乐体验。20世纪60年代，心理学家亚伯拉罕·马斯洛研究了高峰体验——一种罕见的、近乎神秘的极乐感，让体验者感到自己正在以一种令人振奋的新方式感知现实——并得出结论，音乐和性是通往高峰体验最简单的捷径。40年后，阿尔夫·加布里埃尔森继续探讨音乐与欣喜感之间的联系，并邀请一千多人自由描述他们经历过的最强烈的音乐体验。偶尔享受高峰音乐体验并不局限于特定的人群、性格类型或音乐类型，尽管更灵活、更开放的人往往更容易获得这种体验。在高峰聆听阶段，人们常常会报告情绪高涨，同时感觉身体的边界消融并融入音乐，并获得了新的、重要的洞见。

Euphoric may seem like a strong descriptor, but people can sustain truly ecstatic experiences of music. In the 1960s, psychologist Abraham Maslow studied peak experiences—rare, quasi-mystical sensations of bliss that lead the person sustaining them to feel they are perceiving reality in an exhilarating new way—and concluded that music and sex were the easiest shortcuts to them. Forty years later, Alf Gabrielsson took up this music-ecstasy connection and asked more than a thousand people to freely describe the strongest experience they had ever had with music. The occasional enjoyment of peak musical experiences was not restricted to certain demographics or personality types or to certain genres of music, although more flexible and open people tended to be more prone to them. During peak listening episodes, people often report heightened emotionality, along with a sense that their body’s borders have dissolved and merged into the music, and a perception that they have gained new and important insight.

虽然巅峰体验罕见，但人们对它们的记忆往往会挥之不去，并塑造人们对自身和世界的看法。由于它们的巨大影响力，一个问题随之而来：普通的音乐体验在多大程度上只是巅峰体验的简化版本，还是某种完全不同的体验。一项研究调查了人们反复聆听同一首歌曲的倾向，表明这种重复的功效之一就是将听众融入音乐之中，让他们几乎沉浸在音乐之中。因为重听让他们能够预测接下来的内容，并在内心想象在音乐发生之前的延续，熟悉的音乐能够将听众包裹在音乐的旋律中，产生一种与音乐融为一体的愉悦感，这种感觉似乎与人们在高峰体验中描述的那种消融感有关。这种联系表明，普通和极端的音乐愉悦感可能在程度上而非种类上有所不同。

Although peak experiences are rare, the memory of them tends to linger and shape the way people think about themselves and their world. Because of their substantial influence, a question arises about the degree to which ordinary experiences of music function as paler versions of peak episodes or rather as something entirely different in kind. Work examining people’s proclivity to listen and relisten to the same songs suggests that one of the things this repetition achieves is to fold listeners into the music, absorbing them in an almost participatory way. Because relistening allows them to predict what is coming next, and to internally imagine that continuation before it occurs, familiar music can wrap listeners into its course, generating a pleasurable sense of merging with the sound that seems related to the dissolution people describe during peak experiences. This connection suggests that ordinary and extreme musical pleasures might differ more in degree than in kind.

对音乐的审美反应

Aesthetic responses to music

“美学”一词含义多重，可以指西方（尤其是日耳曼）关于艺术之美的思考。但音乐心理学家倾向于更广泛地使用它来指代任何由音乐驱动的体验，尤其是在认知和情感属性得到解释之后所残留的体验。这使得美学不得不应对音乐中最难以用语言表达的方面。

The term “aesthetics” carries multiple meanings, and can refer to Western—especially Germanic—notions about the contemplation of beauty in art. But music psychologists tend to use it more broadly to refer to any music-driven experience, especially those residual aspects left over when the cognitive and emotional attributes are already explained. This leaves aesthetics to contend with the aspects of music that are most difficult to put into words.

当人们甚至不知道如何谈论他们试图进行科学研究的经历时，获得令人满意的洞察力的前景似乎渺茫。但事实证明，许多实证方法恰恰旨在揭示人们无法直接接触的心理过程。测量人们对某个音符（无论该音符是否调准，还是由小号或小提琴演奏）的任意问题的反应时间，可以揭示人们对该音符的预期程度，即使他们完全无法用语言表达这种预期——即使他们完全没有意识到自己正在维持对音符的预期。

When people do not even know how to talk about the experience they are attempting to study scientifically, the prospects for satisfactory insight might seem dim. But many empirical methods, it turns out, aim precisely to expose mental processes to which people lack direct access. Measuring people’s reaction times in responding to some arbitrary question about a note (whether it was in tune or played by a trumpet or a violin) can illuminate the degree to which people anticipated it, even when they are utterly unable to verbalize the anticipation—even when they are oblivious to the fact that they are sustaining anticipations about notes at all.

如果说审美体验的某些方面就像一间暗室，难以触及和探索，那么这类研究则可以理解为一盏手电筒，照亮一个狭窄的区域，根据照射的方向，它可能会揭示或遮蔽更广泛的特征。无论如何，它们为那些想要更深入地了解音乐聆听的人们提供了一种途径——一种易于追求或挑战的探索。

If some aspects of aesthetic experience might be considered a dark room, hard to feel out and explore, these kinds of studies can be understood to offer a flashlight, illuminating a narrow slice that might reveal or obscure the broader characteristics depending on where it shines. In either case, they provide a way in for people seeking to understand more about what musical listening is really like—something tractable to pursue or push against.

新兴的神经美学领域的研究人员利用功能磁共振成像（fMRI）来观察人们在进行审美体验时大脑中哪些区域参与活动。然后，通过研究依赖于这些区域激活的其他任务，他们提出了关于审美聆听的性质和范围的假设。一些研究表明眶额皮质参与了审美处理。该区域还参与编码与各种行为相关的预期奖励或惩罚，并在成瘾行为的形成中发挥作用。一个区域在执行两个不同的任务时活跃并不意味着这两个任务具有共同的基本属性，但它提供了一个起始假设。这项神经影像学研究或许可以解释，许多审美体验较少依赖于对抽象形式的冷静、疏离的思考，而更多地依赖于高度自我相关的评估，例如音乐代表哪个社会群体以及听众与该群体的关系。通过从这些具体而发人深省的出发点出发，实证方法可以激发关于审美体验的更丰富的理论。

Researchers in the burgeoning area of neuroaesthetics use fMRI to look at the areas of the brain that engage when people undergo an aesthetic experience. Then, by examining other tasks that rely on activation in these areas, they draft hypotheses about the nature and scope of aesthetic listening. Several studies implicate the orbitofrontal cortex in aesthetic processing. This region also helps encode the expected reward or punishment associated with various actions, and plays a part in the development of addictive behavior. Just because an area is active while performing two separate tasks does not mean that the tasks share fundamental attributes, but it provides a starting hypothesis. This neuroimaging work might be taken to suggest that much aesthetic experience relies less on the cool, distanced contemplation of abstract forms and more on highly self-relevant assessments, such as the question of what social group the music represents and how the listener relates to it. By working from such specific and provocative starting positions, empirical approaches can inspire richer theorizing about aesthetic experience.

喜欢音乐

Musical liking

即使那些不愿多谈音乐的人，也常常能自信地列举出自己喜欢和不喜欢的音乐。研究经常通过操纵音乐的特征或体验音乐的情境，并询问人们的喜欢程度来理解这些偏好。其他研究则对音乐进行了某些改变——例如，改变新部分的频率——并测量人们在转向其他部分之前的聆听时长，将聆听时间作为偏好的隐性衡量标准。

Even people who hesitate to talk much about music can often confidently list examples of music they like and music they do not. Studies frequently seek to understand these preferences by manipulating characteristics of the music or the context within which it is experienced and asking people how much they liked it. Other work varies something about the music—such as how frequently a new part enters—and measures how long people listen to before moving on it, taking listening time as an implicit measure of preference.

这些研究一次又一次地强化了这样一种观点：人们更喜欢复杂度达到最佳平衡的音乐——既不太简单也不太复杂。图9所示的冯特曲线以1874年首次提出该曲线的心理学家威廉·冯特的名字命名，它展现了这种趋势。纵轴表示偏好、喜欢或享受。横轴可以表示熟悉度或复杂性。广播播放习惯体现了曲线的轨迹。电台播放某首歌曲的最初几次，人们可能会不耐烦地等待，希望接下来播出的是他们最喜欢的歌曲之一。但随着电台将其纳入其前 40 首歌曲循环，一遍又一遍地播放，人们往往会发现自己越来越喜欢它，直到到达某个峰值点——由倒 U 的顶部表示——之后他们开始越来越厌倦这首歌，越来越不喜欢它，直到它最终从电台中退出。

Again and again, these studies reinforce the notion that people prefer music that occupies a sweet spot of complexity—music that is neither too simple nor too complex. Named after psychologist Wilhelm Wundt who first proposed it in 1874, the Wundt curve shown in Figure 9 displays this tendency. The vertical axis designates preference, liking, or enjoyment. The horizontal axis can represent familiarity or complexity. Habits of radio play exemplify the curve’s trajectory. The first few times the radio plays a song, people might wait through it impatiently, hoping one of their favorites will air next. But as the station works it into its top 40 song cycle, playing it again and again, people tend to find themselves enjoying it more and more, until the arrival of some peak point—represented by the top of the inverted U—after which they start to get increasingly sick of the song, liking it less and less until it eventually rotates out of radio play.

9.这条倒U形曲线描绘了人们最初听一首歌越多就越喜欢它。然而，超过某个点后，随着听歌次数的增加，他们往往对这首歌的喜爱程度会降低，有时甚至比第一次听的时候还要低。

9. This inverted-U-shaped curve traces the way people initially tend to like a song more as they hear it more. Past a certain point, however, they tend to like it less with increasing exposure, sometimes ultimately liking it even less than on the first hearing.

虽然这条曲线的基本形状倾向于捕捉广泛的音乐体验，但曲线两侧的斜率和峰值的高度都不是固定不变的。性格在其中起着重要作用——性格特征较高的人被称为“对新体验的开放性”。通常更喜欢更复杂的音乐，他们的偏好曲线会向右移动，与其他听众相关。在音乐吸收量表上得分高的人，可能会比其他听众持续获得更高的峰值享受体验，从而将他们的偏好曲线向上拉长。

Although the basic shape of this curve tends to capture a broad range of musical experiences, neither the slope of the sides nor the height of the peak are fixed. Personality plays a role—people high in an attribute referred to as “openness to new experience” generally prefer more complex music, shifting their preference curve to the right relevant to other listeners. People who score high on the Absorption in Music Scale may regularly sustain higher peak enjoyment experiences than other listeners, stretching their preference curve upward.

不仅性格会影响倒U型曲线的走向，一个人一生的音乐体验也会影响他的聆听体验。一首King Crimson的歌，对于初次接触该类型音乐的人来说，可能听起来复杂得令人难以接受，但对于前卫摇滚的忠实乐迷来说，却能立刻理解。正因为这首歌对不同的听众来说听起来复杂，而对不同的听众来说简单，即使是有着许多共同点的听众，对同一首歌的偏好也可能始于倒U型曲线的不同点。

Not only does personality influence the route through the inverted U, but so does the lifetime of musical experiences a person brings to the listening episode. A King Crimson song might sound alienatingly complex to someone new to the genre, but immediately digestible to a devoted fan of progressive rock. Because it sounds complex to one listener and simple to another, preferences for the same song can start out at different points on the inverted U even for listeners with much in common.

一个人一生的音乐经历与其性格并非完全独立的变量，因为性格会影响音乐类型偏好。对新体验开放度高的人往往偏好他们认为更复杂的音乐类型，例如古典、爵士和金属。外向的人则倾向于偏爱流行音乐等传统音乐类型，尤其是节奏明快、适合跳舞的音乐。此外，人们的偏好往往在青春期形成，这是他们听音乐最多的时期，而这种音乐似乎与他们正在萌芽的身份认同尤为相关。成年后，当被问及不同的歌曲时，他们往往会更喜欢自己青春期常听的歌曲，以及父母青春期常听的歌曲。据推测，父母对自己青少年时期音乐的挥之不去的喜爱转化为在家中更多地播放这些歌曲，让他们的孩子更多地接触这些歌曲，同时也塑造了新一代的偏好。

The lifetime set of a person’s previous musical experiences and that person’s personality are not wholly independent variables, because personality influences genre preference. People high on openness to new experience tend to prefer genres they view as more complex, such as classical, jazz, and metal. Extroverts tend to prefer conventional genres such as pop, especially when the music is fast and danceable. Moreover, people’s preferences tend to solidify during adolescence, the period when they listen to the most music and when this listening seems especially relevant to the definition of their burgeoning identity. Adults asked later in life about different songs tend to prefer the ones that were commonly played during their adolescence, as well as the ones that were played during their parents’ adolescence. Presumably, the parents’ lingering penchant for the music of their own teenage years translated into playing it more around the house, disproportionally exposing their children to these songs and simultaneously shaping the preferences of a new generation.

人们常常想知道音乐心理学家能否设计出一个公式来帮助创作热门歌曲。但音乐偏好取决于高度动态的过程。一首歌的乐趣不仅仅源于它的内在特征，以及先前的接触、对类似歌曲的熟悉程度、性格和人生阶段。似乎这些还不足以证明某个公式的不合理性，许多其他研究也证明了音符之外的因素在决定偏好方面所起的作用。

People often wonder if music psychologists could devise a formula to help write hit songs. But musical preferences depend on highly dynamic processes. Enjoyment of a song arises not just out of its intrinsic characteristics, but also out of prior exposure, familiarity with similar songs, personality, and stage in life. As if that were not sufficient evidence for the implausibility of a formula, numerous other studies document the role of factors far outside the border of the notes in determining preference.

听众在听过弦乐四重奏的简短选段后，如果事先阅读过选段的描述，会不太喜欢。虽然更多地了解一首曲子最终可能会带来更丰富的体验，但显然也会导致短期的缺失。将音乐声音与文字信息融合起来可能看起来很费力，因此令人不快。描述或许还能鼓励听众采取更客观、更反思的立场——这种立场与通常被认为是高度愉悦的音乐体验组成部分的那种想象中的参与截然相反。持续的学习或许能让听众更轻松地整合知识，在不受这种深思熟虑的疏离感干扰的情况下，以洞察力的方式体验音乐。

Listeners exposed to brief excerpts from string quartets liked them less when they had read a description of the excerpt beforehand. Although learning more about a piece might eventually lead to richer experiences, it can apparently also lead to a short-term deficit. Integrating musical sound with verbal information might seem strenuous, and therefore unpleasant. Descriptions might also encourage listeners to adopt a more objective, reflective stance—a position diametrically opposed to the kind of imagined participation often shown to be a component of highly pleasurable musical experiences. Sustained study may allow listeners to integrate the knowledge more effortlessly, experiencing the music in terms of its insights without the intervention of this thoughtful distancing.

信息的呈现方式不仅影响偏好，还会产生广泛的影响。当听众被告知作曲家创作管弦乐片段是为了某种快乐的理由（例如庆祝朋友的到来）时，他们会觉得这些片段更感人，而当听众被告知创作这些片段是为了某种中性或不愉快的理由（例如悼念朋友的去世）时，他们会觉得这些片段更感人。当听众被告知这些乐段来自悲伤或平淡的电影场景的配乐时，他们会觉得这些乐段本身听起来更悲伤。音乐体验和音乐偏好不仅取决于声音本身特征的复杂相互作用，还取决于听众的偏好和先前经验，以及聆听每首乐曲的背景和语境。

The presentation of information has wide-ranging effects beyond just preference. Listeners thought orchestral excerpts were more moving when told that the composer wrote them for some happy reason (to celebrate a friend’s arrival, for example) than when told they wrote them for a neutral or unhappy reason (such as mourning a friend’s loss). Listeners who were told that musical passages had come from a soundtrack accompanying a sad or a neutral film scene thought the passages themselves sounded sadder. Musical experience and musical preference depend on the complex interplay not only of the characteristics of the sound itself, but also of the predilections and prior experiences of the listener, as well as the setting and context within which each piece is heard.

音乐功能和动机

Musical functions and motivation

鉴于音乐在人类文化中无处不在，我们自然有理由探究，是什么驱使人们对音乐产生兴趣。然而，音乐的用途多种多样——从在音乐厅促进沉思，到在教堂增进社区联系，再到在健身房激励锻炼者——反对单一动机，而主张对不同的动机进行分类。为了设想这种分类法可能是什么样子，不妨先思考一下音乐能够提供或促成哪些体验。这些类别的六个基本候选类别可能包括：运动、游戏、交流、社会联系、情感和身份认同。

Given music’s ubiquity in human culture, it is reasonable to ask what drives people’s interest in it. Yet the variety of music’s uses—ranging from facilitating contemplation at a concert hall to encouraging community bonding at a church to pumping up exercisers at the gym—argues against a single motivation and in favor of a taxonomy of different ones. To start envisioning what this taxonomy might be like, it helps to think in terms of what kinds of experience music affords or makes possible. Six basic candidates for these categories might include movement, play, communication, social bonding, emotion, and identity.

音乐能够激发运动——尤其是协调运动——这不仅是其在舞蹈中应用的基础，也体现在运动中、各种康复治疗（例如帕金森病的治疗）以及同步工作（例如农耕或划船）中。早在神经影像学揭示音乐聆听过程中的运动激活之前，这种能力就已为人所知；中世纪的教会蔑视世俗，规定了一种避开与身体互动的时间规律的吟唱方式。另一方面，运动服公司设计了各种应用程序和播放列表，可以根据用户期望的跑步速度定制音乐。

Music’s capacity to spur movement—especially coordinated movement—underlies not only its use in dance, but also during exercise, in various rehabilitative contexts such as therapies for Parkinson’s disease, and during synchronized work efforts like farming or rowing. This capacity was known well before neuroimaging revealed motor activation during music listening; the medieval church, disdaining the earthly, prescribed a type of chant that eschewed the kind of temporal regularity that engages the body. On the other side, athletic wear companies have devised apps and playlists that tailor music to a user’s desired running pace.

音乐也可以广泛地用作游戏。牧羊人创作歌曲来消磨时间；复杂艺术音乐的爱好者则注重审美沉思。音乐可以吸引独处听众的注意力，或促进参与者之间的互动，例如在篝火旁即兴演奏或合唱。一些人甚至推测，音乐促进游戏的功能构成了其进化史的重要组成部分——通过让人们安全地消磨时间，音乐可以防止恶作剧和危险。

Music also can serve broadly as play. Shepherds invent songs to pass the time; aficionados of complex art music prioritize aesthetic contemplation. Music can capture attention from a solitary listener or facilitate interaction between participants, as in a campfire jam or singalong. Some people have even theorized that music’s facilitation of play formed an important part of its evolutionary history—by engaging people in safe time-passing, it prevented mischief and dangers.

人们也利用音乐来交流。刚果地区的姆布提人用歌声传递远距离的位置信息，而加那利群岛之一的戈梅拉岛的居民则传统上使用吹口哨的西班牙语来跨越陡峭的岛屿地形进行交流。追随理查德·瓦格纳的脚步，他用音乐的主导动机来表达歌剧中的人物、物体和思想，《星球大战》系列电影使用诸如死星主题之类的段落不仅是为了唤起某种情感，而且也确切地指代死星。

People also turn to music for its ability to communicate. The Mbuti of the Congo region use song to convey locational information across large distances, and residents of La Gomera, one of the Canary Islands, have traditionally used a whistled version of Spanish to communicate across the steep island landscape. Following in the footsteps of Richard Wagner, who used musical leitmotivs to denote characters, objects, and ideas in his operas, the Star Wars movies employ passages like the death star theme not only to conjure up a certain emotional register, but also quite literally to refer to the death star.

音乐的核心功能之一是社会联系，这在其进化起源理论中也占有重要地位。音乐在世界各地的仪式和典礼中扮演着重要的角色，它既能让两个人在亲密的爵士乐表演中，也能让十万个参加活动的人们产生一种共融感。音乐鼓励人们及时共同参与的能力，似乎对它所激发的分享感和联系感至关重要。

One of music’s central functions, also prominent in theories about its evolutionary origins, is social bonding. Music plays an important role in rituals and ceremonies the world over, and can conjure a sense of communion among two people sharing an intimate jazz performance or a hundred thousand people attending an event. Its ability to encourage joint attending in time seems critical to the sense of sharing and connection it can elicit.

音乐还能以多种方式调节情绪。人们普遍依赖音乐来调节自己的情绪，以至于Spotify和其他流媒体音乐服务上出现了专门为此设计的播放列表：“帮助你走出分手伤痛的音乐”或“在重要会议前增强自信的音乐”。音乐尤其擅长激发和吸收在非常紧张的情况下可能出现的过剩情绪。电影和电视经常依赖于这种能力。多项研究表明，切换汽车行驶在道路上等无害视觉场景的伴奏音乐，可能会使人们将这种情况视为不祥之兆、欢快之情或悲剧之情。

Music can also choreograph emotions in wide-ranging ways. People turn to it so commonly to regulate their own moods that playlists devoted to this purpose have begun cropping up on Spotify and other streaming music services: “music to help you survive a breakup” or “music to inflate your confidence before an important meeting.” Music is especially good at both sparking and absorbing the surfeit of emotions that can arise in very fraught circumstances. Film and television regularly rely on this capacity. Multiple studies show that switching out the music accompanying such innocuous visual scenes as a car traversing a road can lead people to view the situation as ominous, cheerful, or tragic for the car’s inhabitants.

最后，音乐可以塑造、定义或改变个人和群体的身份认同。这一功能或许在高中社交团体中体现得最为明显，这些团体通常至少在一定程度上以各自喜爱的音乐为特征——流行音乐爱好者、独立音乐爱好者和金属乐迷。某一年流行的歌曲似乎象征着那个时代，以及与之相关的人物和环境。熟悉教堂赞美诗定义了一种社群类型，熟悉抗议歌曲则定义了另一种社群类型。人们会在网上约会资料中列出自己喜欢的乐队，以此来表达自己的身份认同。音乐知识和偏好不仅体现了我们个人的特质，也体现了塑造我们的社群和时代时刻的痕迹。

Finally, music can serve to generate, define, or alter individual and group identities. This function is perhaps best exemplified by high school social groups, which are often characterized at least in part by the groups’ favorite music—pop junkies versus indie fans and metalheads. A song popular during a particular year can seem emblematic of that time, and the people and circumstances associated with it. Familiarity with church hymns defines one kind of community; familiarity with protest songs defines another. People list their favorite bands on online dating profiles as a way to communicate who they are. Musical knowledge and preferences bear traces not only of our individual characteristics, but also of the communities and moments that have shaped us.

第八章

Chapter 8

未来

The future

音乐心理学源于不同领域的不同根源，如今已凝聚成一个紧密相连的研究领域。然而，一些最引人入胜的音乐谜团仍然难以捉摸。例如，如何成就一场精彩的表演？音乐心理学无法解答这个问题。这种现状可以被看作是对该领域的控诉，对其未来潜力的描绘，或者暗示换个角度提出这个问题或许会更好。如果答案是一个将质量判断与特定的声学处理联系起来的普遍适用的公式，那么现有的音乐心理学研究就可以被理解为已经最终证明了这个问题是无法回答的。即使在相对狭窄的群体中——例如西方古典钢琴音乐专家演奏家群体——对于哪些表演才是最佳的也存在着显著的分歧。如果没有一个普遍适用的“好”标准，任何公式都无法将声学模式与质量联系起来；相反，必须考虑听众的背景和环境，以及表演发生的文化，这将这个问题推向更有趣也更具挑战性的领域。

From its disparate roots in diverse fields, the psychology of music has coalesced into a cohesive research area. Yet some of music’s most compelling mysteries remain elusive. Consider a question such as, what makes a good performance? The psychology of music cannot answer it. This state of affairs could be viewed as an indictment of the field, a sketch of its future potential, or an intimation that the question might benefit from being asked a different way. If what counted as an answer were a universally applicable formula connecting judgments of quality with specific acoustic manipulations, then existing work in the psychology of music can be understood to have conclusively demonstrated that the question is unanswerable. Even within relatively narrow communities—such as the community of expert performers of Western classical piano music—significant disagreement exists about which performances are best. Without a universally applicable standard for “good,” no formula can connect acoustic patterns with quality; rather, the background and circumstances of the listener and the culture within which the performance is happening must be considered, pushing the question into more intriguing but challenging territory.

音乐心理学的研究已经勾勒出这方面的一些轮廓。例如，它表明，一场表演的感知质量不能通过以下方式来评估：鉴于视觉通道中的信息对音乐的聆听和评判方式以及声音呈现环境的强大影响，单凭声音本身是不够的。每当音乐心理学研究音乐体验的某个方面，试图完全解释某些反应（例如对质量的判断）却失败时，它就会更清晰地定义问题的范畴。通过这种方式，音乐心理学可以继续探索人类音乐体验方面可通过实证方法解决的极限。通过挑战科学的边界，它可以提出新的问题，而这些问题如果没有实验项目的尝试和失败是不可能提出的。人文主义和科学的音乐方法可以齐头并进，相互激发，产生比任何一方单独能够获得的更深刻的洞察。

Work in the psychology of music has already mapped some of the contours of this landscape. It has demonstrated, for example, that a performance’s perceived quality cannot be assessed from the sound alone, given the fundamental contribution from information in the visual channel to the way music is heard and judged and the powerful impact of the context within which the sound is presented. Each time the psychology of music studies some aspect of musical experience, tries, and fails to account fully for some response (such as judgments of quality), it defines the topography of the problem a little more clearly. In this way, the psychology of music can continue to explore the limits of the aspects of human musical experience that are addressable by empirical methods. By running up against the borders of science, it can define new questions that would have been impossible to formulate without the attempt and failure of an experimental project. Humanistic and scientific approaches to music can proceed hand in hand, provoking each other into deeper insight than either would have been able to achieve alone.

音乐与大数据

Music and big data

大数据的力量已在预测传染病传播和购物行为等诸多领域显现。与音乐心理学相关的数据——例如，以记录的音符、演奏的音符和聆听的时长等形式存在——一直存在，但直到最近才被编码，使其易于进行大规模分析。如果50年前的一位研究人员想要找出一段旋律中第一个大跳跃通常发生在多远，那么这个项目将需要耗费大量时间，用纸笔进行统计：翻阅每首乐谱，目测跳跃，并计算其之前的节拍。如今，同一位研究人员可以使用数字搜索和操作工具包，这些工具包可以探测庞大的乐谱和表演数据库，并在不到一分钟的时间内回答同样的问题。

The power of big data has become apparent in areas as diverse as forecasting the spread of infectious disease and predicting shopper behavior. Data relevant to music psychology—in the form, for example, of notes written, notes played, and hours listened—have always existed but have only recently been encoded in ways that make them amenable to easy large-scale analysis. If a researcher fifty years ago wanted to find out how far into a melody the first large leap tends to occur, the project would have required an impractically time-consuming period of pen-and-paper tallying: paging through each score, eyeballing the leap, and counting the beats preceding it. Today, that same researcher has access to digital search-and-manipulation toolkits that can probe vast databases of scores and performances to answer the same question in less than a minute.

语料库研究利用数字工具的力量，在海量曲目中识别模式。20世纪60年代欧洲小提琴家的录音与……有何不同？20世纪60年代的美国小提琴家？20世纪90年代，东海岸嘻哈音乐与西海岸嘻哈音乐有何不同？数字化工具可以快速解答这些问题，提供具体且发人深省的见解。这些见解与广泛的人文研究相结合，可以更深入地阐释这些风格与其发展文化之间的关系。

Corpus studies harness the power of digital tools to identify patterns in large repertoires of music. How do recordings of European violinists from the 1960s differ from recordings of American violinists from the 1960s? What stylistic features distinguished East Coast hip hop from West Coast hip hop in the 1990s? Digital tools can dispatch with these questions quickly, providing specific, provocative insights that—in partnership with broad humanistic inquiry—can propel richer accounts of the relationship between these styles and the cultures within which they developed.

与大多数行为研究不同，语料库研究不需要参与者。它们不是测量为研究招募的某些样本的反应，而是分析已有信息（例如，人们之前书写和演奏的音符），以了解塑造他们的认知过程。但语料库研究的结果可以启发使用人类参与者的新实验。例如，语料库研究或许可以识别乡村音乐、摇滚乐或流行音乐等音乐类型最常见的特征。为了理解人们对音乐类型的认知，后续实验可以操纵歌曲来添加或删除这些特征，并要求参与者根据音乐类型对修改后的片段进行分类。在这种情况下，语料库研究和行为研究相互结合，阐明诸如对音乐风格的认知等广泛的主题。

Unlike most behavioral research, corpus studies do not require participants. Instead of measuring the responses of some sample of people recruited for a study, they analyze information that already exists—for example, notes people have previously written and played—to understand something about the cognitive processes that shaped them. But results from corpus studies can inspire new experiments that do use human participants. For example, corpus studies might identify the characteristics most common to genres like country or rock or pop. To understand perceptions of genre, subsequent experiments could then manipulate songs to add or remove these features, asking participants to classify the altered excerpts by genre. In scenarios like these, corpus studies and behavioral research partner with one another to illuminate broad topics, such as the perception of musical style.

语料库研究揭示的某些典型特征——例如，音乐织体中底部两个声部之间最常见的距离与顶部两个声部之间最常见的距离——可以理解为源于基本的感知原理，例如耳朵分辨低频和高频音程的能力不同。其他特征则随着文化影响的变化而因风格而异。语料库研究尤其成功地解答了风格如何发展的问题——19世纪80年代维也纳创作的音乐与19世纪50年代或19世纪10年代维也纳创作的音乐听起来有何不同。

Certain features that corpus studies reveal as typical—the most common distance between the bottom two voices in a musical texture versus the most common distance between the top two, to take one example—can be understood to stem from basic perceptual principles, such as the ear’s differing ability to resolve pitch intervals at low and high frequencies. Others can be seen to vary from style to style as cultural influences change. Corpus studies have been particularly successful at addressing the question of how styles develop—how music written in Vienna in the 1880s sounds different from music written in Vienna in the 1850s or 1810s.

语料库研究可以追溯作曲潮流在时间上的出现和消失，例如开始、高峰和流行音乐中自动调音的衰落，以及西方古典音乐中减七和弦使用的开始、鼎盛和衰落。通过将每年减七和弦使用情况的统计数据与当代对其表现力的描述相结合，可以确定一个发展弧。当减七和弦很少见时，它的表现力也很强——传达出一种神秘或危险的印象。但随着作曲家越来越多地利用它的情感影响力，它的一些表现力逐渐黯淡，使其效果越来越差，最终成为一种陈词滥调。减七和弦的统计和接受历史支持了这样一种观点，即期望违背有助于音乐的表现力。这些和弦在很少见的时候往往更能吸引听众，而随着它们变得越来越普遍，其表现力就逐渐减弱。

Corpus studies can trace the emergence and disappearance of compositional fads across time, such as the onset, peak, and decline of Auto-Tune in pop music or the onset, peak, and decline of the use of diminished seventh chords in Western classical music. By pairing statistics about diminished seventh chord usages per year with contemporary accounts of their perceived expressive quality, an arc can be identified. When the diminished seventh chord was rare, it was also expressively powerful—conveying an impression of mystery or danger. But as composers took advantage of its emotional sway, using it more and more, some of its expressive luster paled, rendering it less and less effective and ultimately something of a cliché. The statistical and receptive history of the diminished seventh chord supports the notion that expectancy violation contributes to musical expressivity. These chords tended to grip listeners more effectively when they were rare, relinquishing their expressive power as they became more common.

但很久以前书写或记录的笔记并非与音乐心理学相关的唯一大数据。或许最诱人的数据是对大量人群日常音乐使用情况、背景和反应的详细记录。直到最近，这似乎几乎不可能实现。然而，如今全球约有 75% 的人口使用手机，而且越来越多的手机也兼具音乐播放器的功能，使用 Spotify、Pandora 和 Apple Music 等服务播放流媒体音乐。这些手机通常还配备 GPS 追踪器，叠加丰富的数字地图信息，可以记录人们是在家中、健身房还是在散步时听音乐（如果是，则记录其速度）。它们还可以记录人们听音乐的时间以及同时使用的其他应用程序。

But notes written or recorded long ago are not the only type of big data relevant to music psychology. Perhaps the most tantalizing set of data would be a detailed account of the daily usage, context, and responses to music of large swaths of the population. Until recently, this seemed largely impossible to achieve. Now, however, about 75 percent of the world’s population uses a mobile phone, and an increasing number of those phones function as music players as well, streaming music using services such as Spotify, Pandora, and Apple Music. These phones also often carry GPS trackers, which, overlaid with rich information from digital maps, can record whether people are listening at home, in a gym, or on a walk (and if so, at what pace). They can also record the time of day people are listening and what other apps they are using concurrently.

似乎这还不够，手机也开始采用一系列生理传感器，从心跳监测器开始，但最终可能会扩展到各种各样的仪器，提供对皮肤电反应（运动过程中发生的汗腺激活）等现象的连续测量。情绪唤醒）和呼吸频率。不难想象，未来人们可以获得大量何时何地听什么音乐的信息，以及他们相关行为和情绪反应的信息。如此庞大的数据池可以让音乐心理学家解答关于音乐、参与度和情境的问题。这些问题在实验室环境中很难解决，因为在实验室环境中，聆听体验与许多嵌入的现实世界关联隔绝。但与其他同等规模的研究一样，它也提出了关于隐私、解读和公平的关键问题。音乐心理学的历史表明，这类陷阱比比皆是。

As if this were not enough, phones are also beginning to employ a host of physiological sensors, starting with heartbeat monitors but likely extending ultimately to a wide variety of instruments providing continuous measurements of phenomena like galvanic skin response (the sweat gland activation that occurs during emotional arousal) and respiration rate. It is easy to imagine a future in which information is available about what music vast numbers of people listen to when and where, along with information about their associated behavior and emotional response. This huge pool of data could enable music psychologists to answer questions about music, engagement, and context that are challenging to address in a laboratory setting, where listening experiences occur in isolation from so many of their embedded, real-world associations. But like other investigations of this scale, it raises critical issues about privacy, interpretation, and fairness. The history of the psychology of music demonstrates that pitfalls of this sort abound.

通过手机收集的数据也能提供以往因成本高昂且费力不讨好而难以获得的纵向证据。此前，想要了解音乐品味或能力如何在长期内发生变化的科学家必须招募大量参与者，并用金钱奖励吸引他们年复一年地回到实验室。尽管有激励措施，这类研究的退出率仍然很高。但如果参与者只需随身携带手机，并同意将部分信息发送给研究人员，那么进行多年的研究就变得更容易了。

Data collected from phones could also provide the sort of longitudinal evidence that has previously been too expensive and painstaking to obtain. Previously, scientists who wanted to understand how musical tastes or abilities change across long timespans had to enroll large numbers of participants and entice them with monetary rewards to keep returning to the laboratory year in and year out. Despite incentives, studies like these suffer from high dropout rates. But if all participants need to do is carry around their phone and agree to allow some of its information to be sent to researchers, multiyear studies become much more feasible.

似乎这些目标还不够宏大，谷歌的科学家和工程师们正试图利用大数据的力量，创作引人入胜的机器音乐。他们的项目名为 Magenta，旨在利用机器智能分析现有音乐，并利用由此获得的洞见创作自己的新作品，目标是通过音乐版的图灵测试。最初的图灵测试提出，对机器思考能力的终极考验是它能否在打字对话中模仿人类。而谷歌的目标是看看机器是否有一天能够通过创作歌曲来模仿人类。Magenta 的进展可以在网上追踪，虽然今天它与 Jimi Hendrix 毫无疑问，但它的表现很可能在未来几年大幅提升。

As if these aims were not grandiose enough, scientists and engineers at Google are attempting to harness the power of big data to create compelling machine-generated music. Their project, called Magenta, harnesses machine intelligence to analyze existing music and use the resulting insights to produce new compositions of its own, with an eye toward passing a musical version of the Turing test. The original Turing test proposed that the ultimate test of a machine’s ability to think would be whether it could pass itself off as human in a typed conversational exchange. Google aims to see instead whether a machine might one day be able to pass itself off as human by writing a song. Magenta’s progress can be traced online, and while there is no mistaking it for Jimi Hendrix today, it is likely that its performance will vastly improve in the coming years.

发明家吉尔·温伯格（Gil Weinberg）在佐治亚理工学院运用类似的机器智能策略打造了音乐家机器人。他利用塞隆尼斯·孟克（Thelonious Monk）演奏的统计分析，训练机器人马林巴琴演奏家西蒙（Shimon）聆听人类乐伴的演奏并做出令人信服的即兴演奏。此外，他还打造了一只可以挥舞鼓棒的假肢手臂，鼓手可以佩戴这只手臂，通过不断适应房间音乐的即兴演奏来增强演奏效果。实际上，这台设备让音乐家体验到了一种机器人演奏的感觉，他们控制着部分演奏内容，而假肢手臂控制着其余部分。许多音乐家都描述过一种身临其境的知识，他们的双手有时似乎比头脑“知道”得更多——有时他们的手指会飞快地弹奏出一系列恰到好处的音符，而他们当时根本来不及用明确的术语进行规划和概念化——因此，将部分控制权交给鼓棒的体验或许会让人感到异常熟悉。

Inventor Gil Weinberg has used similar machine intelligence strategies to build musician robots at Georgia Tech. He used statistical analyses of Thelonious Monk performances to train Shimon, a robot marimba player, to listen to a human musical partner and provide convincing improvised responses. Separately, he built a prosthetic, stick-wielding third arm drummers can wear to augment their performance with improvisations that continually adapt to the music in the room. In effect, this device allows musicians to experience a sense of cyborg performance, where they control some of what is happening, but the prosthetic arm controls the rest. Since many musicians describe a kind of embodied knowledge where their hands at times seem to “know” more than their heads—times when their fingers fly toward a sequence of just-right notes that they did not have time to plan and conceptualize in explicit terms—the experience of ceding some of the control to the stick might seem eerily familiar.

10. Shimon 是一个由 Gil Weinberg 设计的马林巴琴演奏机器人，它可以与人类表演者即兴创作爵士乐对话，聆听他们的表演并当场做出音乐回应。

10. Shimon, a marimba-playing robot designed by Gil Weinberg, can improvise jazz dialogues with human performers, listening to their contributions and creating musical responses on the spot.

耳虫和音乐记忆

Earworms and musical memory

自2000年以来，大量研究已发展出一种名为“耳虫”的现象，这种现象会萦绕在人们的脑海中。超过90%的人每周至少会经历一次所谓的“耳虫”，历史记录表明，这种现象的出现早于现代录音技术的出现。然而，由于反复播放和近期播放是预测“耳虫”的最佳指标，因此，能够频繁重听歌曲的技术很可能增加了“耳虫”的流行程度。

Since 2000, a body of work has developed on the phenomenon of tunes that get stuck in your head. So-called earworms affect more than 90 percent of people at least once a week, and historical records show that they predate the onset of modern recording technology. However, since repeated and recent exposure to a song are two of the best earworm predictors, technology that enables frequent relistening has probably increased their prevalence.

耳虫通常由短小的旋律片段组成，这些片段在人们的脑海中反复播放，不受意识控制。它们或许最能体现音乐如何俘获人心，让人们感觉仿佛置身于想象之中，即使他们只是坐在桌前，甚至根本没有音乐播放。未来几年，心理学家将基于近期研究，探究是什么让音乐如此容易触发这种回路，以及是什么让某些音乐比其他音乐更胜一筹。（人们总是认为某些歌曲，比如卡莉·蕾·杰普森的《Call Me Maybe》和迪士尼的《小小世界》，特别容易让人产生共鸣。）

Earworms tend to be composed of short melodic snippets that play again and again in people’s heads, outside of volitional control. They serve as perhaps the best demonstration of the way that music can capture people, making them feel as if they are imaginatively participating, even when they are really just sitting at a desk, and even when there is really no music playing at all. In the coming years, psychologists will seek to build on recent work to understand what makes music so especially well-suited to triggering this circuitry, and what makes some music even better at it than others. (People consistently rate certain songs, like Carly Rae Jepsen’s “Call Me Maybe” and Disney’s “It’s a Small World” as especially sticky).

耳虫也能很好地阐释记忆的神秘运作。它们可以通过非常间接的方式被触发；例如，瞥见一张海报，上面某个人看起来有点像虚构的加斯顿，半小时后就能引发一阵强烈的“没有人能像加斯顿那样打架”的念头。注意到这是一个特别快乐的下午，也能引发法瑞尔的歌曲不请自来地在脑海里重现。

Earworms also illuminate the mysterious workings of memory particularly well. They can be triggered in remarkably oblique ways; for example, glimpsing a poster of someone who looks vaguely likely the fictional Gaston can trigger an intense bout of “No one fights like Gaston” half an hour later. Noticing that it is a particularly happy afternoon can elicit unbidden mental replays of tunes by Pharrell.

同样令人惊奇的是，那些几十年来从未被听到过的歌曲，一提起，却能清晰地浮现在眼前。这些音乐怎么可能被储存了那么久，却完全不记得？这种音乐记忆的壮举可以作为其他类型信息的有用载体，因为大学生经常当他们意识到自己还能列出世界上所有国家时，会欣喜若狂，这多亏了儿时听过的《狂欢三宝》这首歌。营销公司一直在利用这种能力，把想要传达的信息搭上朗朗上口的旋律（“给我个机会……”）。

Similarly astonishing is the way that the entire course of songs that have gone unheard for decades can come rushing back in vivid detail when mentioned. How is it possible to have been storing all that music all that time without even remembering it was there? These feats of musical memory can serve as a useful vehicle for other types of information, as college students are often pleased to discover when they realize they can still list all the countries of the world thanks to childhood exposure to the Animaniacs song. Marketing companies exploit this capacity all the time, hitching a desired message to a catchy melodic wagon (“Gimme a break … ”).

这些效应源于音乐以序列形式存储的倾向，即在各个组别（例如乐句）中，一个事件按规定的顺序接连发生。人们通常只能从一组乐曲的开头开始，才能记忆乐段的后半部分。一旦开始记忆，他们通常就停不下来，直到听到一组乐曲的结尾。例如，如果我想思考《Ring Around the Rosie》中唱出“fall”这个词的音符，我必须从“we all”开始才能到达“fall”，然后我就很难忍住不继续唱“down”。

These effects depend on music’s tendency to be stored as a sequence, with one event following another in prescribed order within individual groupings, such as a phrase. People can often only access memory for the later part of a musical passage by starting at the beginning of a group. Once they have started remembering it, they often cannot stop until they get to the end of a group. For example, if I want to think about the note on which the word “fall” is sung in “Ring Around the Rosie,” I have to start at “we all” in order to get to “fall,” and then I have a hard time resisting continuing to “down.”

尽管语音也是由一个接一个的声音事件组成的，但人们记忆语音的方式却不尽相同。当被要求复述一段对话时，人们倾向于概括对话的基本内容，而不会重复特定的词语。然而，当被要求回忆一首歌时，人们倾向于逐个音符地唱出这首歌的旋律——事实上，很难想象一段音乐概要看起来或听起来会是什么样子。音乐记忆本质上往往非常忠实——被要求想象一首歌的人往往会以大致正确的音高和节奏来想象。未来几年，音乐心理学的研究可能会利用神经科学日益增强的力量，更详细地了解音乐记忆背后的神经回路。

Despite that speech is also made up of acoustic events following one another in time, people do not remember it in the same way. Asked to recap a conversation, people tend to provide a summary that captures the basic content of what was said without replicating the particular words. Asked to recall a song, however, people tend to sing the actual tune, note for note—in fact, it is hard to imagine what a musical summary might look or sound like. Musical memory tends to be quite faithful in nature—people asked to imagine a song tend to do so at roughly the correct pitch and tempo. Work in music psychology in coming years will likely harness the increasing power of neuroscience to understand the circuitry that underlies musical memory in greater detail.

跨文化方法

Cross-cultural approaches

心理学研究通常依赖于研究旨在代表总体的小样本人群。研究人员使用统计数据来评估以下因素对结果产生影响的可能性：在样本中发现的结论可以推广到更大的群体。但由于实际限制，心理学研究的大多数参与者都是西方大学的本科生。然而，这些研究的结果通常被认为代表了广义上的人类认知。

Psychological research typically relies on studying small samples of people intended to be representative of a general population. Researchers use statistics to assess the likelihood that effects found within their sample would generalize to the larger group. But because of practical constraints, most participants in psychology studies are undergraduates at universities in the West. Yet results from these studies are often taken to represent human cognition broadly construed.

除了过度依赖西方大学生作为参与者之外，音乐心理学也倾向于过度依赖西方古典音乐作为刺激。该领域不仅可能被指责为了理解人类的音乐认知而仅仅从具有特定文化经历的一小部分人群中概括，也可能被指责仅仅从世界音乐的一小部分中概括。

In addition to relying disproportionately on Western university students as participants, music psychology tends to rely disproportionately on Western classical music as stimuli. Not only might the field be accused of generalizing from a subset of people with specific cultural experiences in order to understand human music cognition, but also of generalizing from a small slice of the world’s music.

在很大程度上，这些局限性并非源于研究界的故意疏忽。相反，一系列社会和系统因素共同推动了研究朝着这个方向发展。首先，许多音乐心理学家都是从古典音乐家成长起来的——从古典吉他和钢琴到音乐学院的殿堂，有一条尤为常见的路径。像音乐心理学这样的跨学科工作要求从业者精通多个领域，因此，许多学者在掌握了西方体系的专业知识后，便着手将这些知识与认知科学的工具和技术相结合，而不是去学习新的音乐领域。

For the most part, these limitations did not arise out of willful negligence on the part of the research community. Rather, a series of social and systemic factors conspired to push research in this direction. First, many music psychologists grew up as classical musicians—there is a particularly well-worn path from classical guitar and piano into the hallways of music academe. Interdisciplinary work like music psychology requires its practitioners to master multiple fields, so with expertise in the Western system already under the belt, many scholars set off to integrate this knowledge with the tools and techniques of cognitive science rather than learn about new musical domains.

音乐学术界现有的分歧加剧了这一现状。非西方音乐的研究往往在名为“民族音乐学”的学科背景下进行，该学科拥有独立的会议、期刊和项目，有时令人遗憾的是，这些会议、期刊和项目与音乐学并行。民族音乐学家致力于将音乐理解为人类文化的产物，他们并不总是对心理学这门学科心生好感，他们认为心理学对其工具和方法论的文化建构性缺乏足够的警觉。

Existing divisions in music scholarship have not helped the situation. The study of non-Western music tends to be undertaken within the context of a discipline called ethnomusicology, with its own conferences, journals, and programs that sometimes regrettably run in parallel to those of musicology. Ethnomusicologists, committed to understanding music as a product of human culture, are not always enamored of the discipline of psychology, which they can view as insufficiently alert to the culturally constructed nature of its tools and methodologies.

音乐心理学家通常希望通过跨文化研究来阐明人类心智，但民族音乐学家却倾向于将心智视为人类文化的产物，这使得跨文化比较变得困难。跨文化研究需要大量的时间和资金用于旅行，还需要精通多种语言、多种音乐体系以及认知科学的各个学科。由于音乐方面的专家和心理学方面的专家在人类心智对特定研究类型敏感性方面往往存在根本性差异，因此很难组建有效的合作团队来完成这类项目。即使能够组建团队，那些落入既定学科夹缝中的研究也可能难以获得资助，因为专注于某一特定视角的机构会认为这些研究提案不足以代表其领域或与其核心地位相符。然而，随着人们越来越认识到超越学科界限以解决重大问题的必要性，这类研究正开始找到出路。

Music psychologists generally look to cross-cultural work to help illuminate the human mind, but ethnomusicologists tend to view the mind as a product of human culture, rendering cross-cultural comparisons problematic. Cross-cultural work requires lots of time and funding for travel as well as expertise in multiple languages and musical systems and in the various disciplines of cognitive science. Because the people with expertise on the music side and the people with expertise on the psychology side tend to differ foundationally on the susceptibility of the human mind to particular types of study, it is difficult to put together effective collaborative teams for these sorts of projects. Even when the teams are capable of being assembled, research that falls between the cracks of established disciplines can be difficult to fund, with agencies devoted to one perspective or the other finding the proposal insufficiently representative of or central to their field. Nevertheless, as the imperative of transcending disciplinary boundaries to address big questions becomes more widely recognized, this research is starting to find a way.

成功的跨文化研究会设计不依赖于言语表达的任务，即使在没有精确翻译为“音乐”的词语的地方，实验也能进行。Nori Jacoby 及其同事通过电话音乐游戏，揭示了玻利维亚偏远地区美国和齐玛内听众的节奏偏好。研究参与者聆听一段随机生成的节奏，并敲击回应。这种敲击反应被记录并重放。参与者再次被要求敲击回应。在多次聆听和敲击的反复过程中，人们产生的节奏往往反映了他们对声音通常如何进行的基本预期。对于美国和齐玛内听众来说，这意味着他们会趋向于由简单整数比组成的节奏。有趣的是，尽管两种文化的听众都选择了简单的整数比，但两组听众所偏好的特定比例却存在系统性差异。美国听众敲击的比例是西方音乐中常见的比例，而齐玛内听众敲击的比例则是他们自己音乐中常见的比例。

Successful cross-cultural work devises tasks that do not rely on verbalization, allowing experiments to work even in places where no word that precisely translates to “music” exists. Nori Jacoby and colleagues used a musical game of telephone to reveal rhythmic biases in American and Tsimané listeners in a remote region of Bolivia. Participants in the study listened to a randomly generated rhythm and tapped it back. This tapping response was recorded and replayed. Again, participants were asked to tap it back. Across multiple iterations of listening and tapping, the rhythms people produced tended to reflect their basic expectations about how sounds typically go. For both American and Tsimané listeners, this meant converging on rhythms composed of simple integer ratios. Intriguingly, although listeners from both cultures settled on simple integer ratios, the particular ratios favored by the two groups differed systematically. American listeners produced ratios that are commonly found in Western music, and Tsimané listeners produced ratios commonly found in their music.

这项研究发现，两组音乐发展相对独立的人群对简单的整数比率（尤其是周围音乐文化中常见的比率）存在共同的偏好。周围环境音景对节奏偏好的影响在相互独立性较低的文化中也得到了证实。当被要求从不同的单个音调节奏组合中进行选择时，日语母语人士更倾向于选择长短组合，而英语母语人士则更倾向于选择短长组合，这反映了两种语言在节奏上的差异。尽管人们可能无法用言语识别出他们音乐或语言中常见的比率，但此类设计可以为这种能力提供隐性证据，使其成为研究跨文化认知的有力工具。

This study identified a shared bias toward simple integer ratios—particularly to the ratios typically heard in the surrounding musical culture—for two groups of people whose music has developed independently. The impact of the surrounding soundscape on rhythmic preferences has been established in cultures with less mutual independence as well. When asked to choose from different rhythmic groupings of individual tones, native Japanese speakers prefer long-short groupings, while native English speakers prefer short-long ones, mirroring a rhythmic distinction in the two languages. Although people probably could not verbally identify the ratios typically heard in their music or language, designs such as these can provide implicit evidence for the ability, making them a powerful tool for studying cognition across cultural boundaries.

科学、人文和艺术之间的桥梁

Bridges among science, humanities, and the arts

音乐心理学在艺术、人文和科学之间占据着一个引人入胜的交汇点。自20世纪80年代以来，它一直将各个领域的专家聚集在一起，交流思想、开展合作并规划研究。在许多方面，它一直处于知识的先锋地位，在跨专业领域的价值尚未被学术界广泛认可之前，就推动了跨学科的进步。

The psychology of music occupies an intriguing nexus among the arts, the humanities, and the sciences. Since the 1980s, it has been bringing people with expertise in each of these areas together to exchange ideas, collaborate, and plan research. In many ways, it has been on the intellectual vanguard, making interdisciplinary progress happen before the value of reaching across specialty domains was widely recognized in academia.

然而，发现和对话的潜力更大。科学发现能够迅速进入大众媒体，但人文学科的研究成果往往难以被轻易概括，因此进入公共领域的速度往往较慢。更不平衡的是，科学——尤其是神经科学——被认为拥有其他知识领域并不总是具备的权威性。

Yet the potential for discovery and dialogue is even greater. Scientific findings make their way into the popular press with alacrity, but work in the humanities, which often resists easy encapsulation, is often slower to translate into the public sphere. To make things more uneven, science—and particularly neuroscience—can be seen to possess an authority not always extended to other intellectual undertakings.

科学与人文学科之间的系统性不对称影响了音乐心理学的蓬勃发展。传统的激励机制往往不成比例地奖励那些对音乐性做出简单断言的科学研究，而不是更细致而谨慎的描述反映了严谨的人文投入，但存在着一种危险，即该领域日益复杂的工具将被用来支持普遍的假设，而不是推动理论发现。

The systemic asymmetry between the reception of science and the humanities affects music psychology’s capacity to thrive. With traditional incentives often disproportionately rewarding scientific studies that make easy claims about musicality over the more nuanced and careful accounts that reflect rigorous humanistic input, a danger exists that the field’s increasingly sophisticated tools will be marshalled to support prevailing assumptions rather than drive theoretical discovery.

这些新工具中最令人眼花缭乱的一项，将研究从狭窄的地下实验室带到了现实世界的表演空间。世界各地的一些研究机构为音乐厅配备了动作捕捉、脑电图和生理传感器，在每个座位上放置了观众反应平板电脑，并安装了可以操控空间声学特性的技术。这样的设施让听众更容易获得心理学家想要研究的音乐体验。在昏暗的大厅里聆听现场表演者的音乐，可能是一种引人入胜的体验，而这在荧光灯下的隔音室里戴着耳机聆听是无法比拟的。

One of the most dazzling of these new tools takes research out of the cramped basement laboratory and into real-world performance spaces. Several research institutes around the world have outfitted special concert halls with motion capture, EEG, and physiological sensors, placing audience response tablets at each seat and installing technology that can manipulate the acoustic characteristics of the space. Facilities like these make it much easier for listeners to have the kind of musical experience psychologists want to study. Hearing music played by live performers in a darkened hall can be a riveting event not easily approximated by listening over headphones in a soundproof booth under fluorescent lighting.

古典音乐会的观众通常不会提供太多关于其感受、判断和反应的行为证据。人们在经历深刻而变革性的聆听体验时，静静地坐着，就像在脑海中制定购物清单一样。这些联网的音乐厅提供了一个场所，可以精细地测量所有可测量的指标，从手掌汗水到躯干摆动再到神经活动，从而为揭示音乐处理过程中隐藏的层面提供了一个诱人的机会。

An audience at a classical concert typically does not provide much behavioral evidence of their feelings, judgments, and responses. People undergoing a profound, transformative listening experience sit silently much the same as people formulating their grocery list in their head. By providing a venue to subtly measure everything that is measurable, from palm sweat to torso sways to neural activity, these wired concert halls provide a tantalizing chance for illuminating the hidden aspects of musical processing.

但要充分利用这些设施的潜力，研究人员必须开发能够反映对音乐和音乐行为持续思考的问题和理论。来自世界各地拥有丰富音乐实践经验的专业人士必须汇聚一堂，共同构建这些理论。必须倾听关于音乐力量的第一手资料，并将其融入研究设计中，这样，情感体验才能被归类为快乐或悲伤，评价也才能超越喜欢或不喜欢。演奏者对音乐表达内在运作方式的专业知识必须得到重视。允许塑造关于时间和感知的实验。研究人员必须在音乐行为的丰富描述性特征和研究这些行为所必需的严格、可控的设计之间流畅地来回切换。

But to harness the promise of these facilities, researchers must develop questions and theories that reflect sustained thoughtfulness about music and musical behavior. Diverse voices with expertise in musical practices from around the world must come together to formulate them. Firsthand accounts of music’s power must be listened to and woven into the research design, so that emotional experiences are categorized not merely as happy or sad and evaluations extend beyond liked or disliked. Performer expertise about the inner workings of musical expressivity must be allowed to shape experiments on timing and perception. Researchers must move fluidly back and forth between rich descriptive characterizations of musical behaviors and the rigorous, controlled designs necessary for studying them.

事实上，这种互动和灵活思考的能力，对于应对21世纪更广泛的挑战，似乎比音乐心理学本身的挑战更加重要。音乐心理学提供了一个介于科学与人文之间的思考实验室，能够推动超越学科界限的创新，同时帮助我们理解人类的一个基本属性——音乐性——它对于我们的身份认同、我们的特质以及我们相互理解的能力至关重要。

In fact, this capacity for interplay and flexible thinking seems ever more critical to the broad challenges of the twenty-first century, beyond the specifics of the psychology of music. By providing a laboratory for thinking between the sciences and the humanities, music psychology can fuel innovation that transcends its own disciplinary borders, while helping us understand a fundamental human attribute—musicality—that is key to our identity, our eccentricity, and our ability to understand one another.

有一项研究让听众能够大致分辨出乐曲中各个片段来自哪里，该研究是Eric F. Clarke和Carol L. Krumhansl 的《感知音乐时间》，《音乐感知》 7.3（1990 年）：213–252。
有一本书是哲学家杰罗德·莱文森( Jerrold Levinson)所著的《当下的音乐》 (纽约州伊萨卡：康奈尔大学出版社，1998 年)，书中他主张小规模聆听比大规模聆听更重要。
杰西卡·菲利普斯-西尔弗和劳雷尔·特雷纳的研究表明，婴儿可以将弹跳模式转化为听觉模式，“感受节拍：运动影响婴儿节奏感知”，《科学》 308（2005）：1430。
关于法国音乐和英国音乐节奏模式的比较研究可以在Anirrudh R. Patel和Joseph R. Daniele 的《语言和音乐中节奏的实证比较》中找到，《认知》 87.1（2003）：B35–B45。

第五章

Chapter 5

不同钢琴家的节奏概况的比较可以在以下两篇报告中找到：Bruno H. Repp，“音乐表演的多样性和共性：对音乐表演中节奏微观结构的分析舒曼的《梦幻曲》》哈斯金斯实验室语音研究现状报告SR-111（1992 年）：227-260；以及 Bruno H. Repp，“舒曼《梦幻曲》中的表达时机”：研究生钢琴家表演分析”，哈斯金斯实验室语音研究现状报告SR-117/118（1994 年）：141-160。
关于表现时间和力度对听众表演偏好的相对贡献的信息来自Bruno H. Repp 的《音乐表现的缩影：III. 时间和力度对钢琴家演奏肖邦 E 大调练习曲初始小节时审美印象的贡献》，《美国声学学会杂志》 106.1（1999 年）：469–479。
William F. Thompson、Phil Graham和Frank A. Russo在《观看音乐表演：视觉对感知和体验的影响》一文中报道了面部表情对感知不和谐的影响的研究，论文发表于《Semiotica》 156.1–4（2005）：203–227。
Jane W. Davidson 的《音乐表演中的表现力动作感知》（博士论文，伦敦城市大学，1991 年）详细介绍了对小提琴表演中感知表现力的动作捕捉研究。
关于表演者专业水平信息对表演评分的影响的研究来自两个来源：Carolyn A. Kroger和Elizabeth Hellmuth Margulis，“但他们告诉我这是专业的”：音乐表演评估中的外在因素，”音乐心理学45.1 (2017): 49–64；以及Gökhan Aydogan、Nicole Flaig、Srekar N. Ravi、Edward W. Large、 Samuel M. McClure和Elizabeth Hellmuth Margulis，“克服偏见：认知控制降低了评估音乐表演时对框架效应的敏感性，”科学报告8 (2018): 6229。
有研究表明，评分最高的小提琴手比其他小提琴手进行了更多的刻意练习，这是K. Anders Ericsson、Ralf Th. Krampe和Clemens Tesch-Romer的“刻意练习在获得专家级表现中的作用”，《心理学评论》 100.3（1993）：363-406。
支持基因在音乐能力中的作用的研究可以在Miriam A. Mosing、Guy Madison、Nancy L. Pedersen、Ralf Kuja-Halkola和Fredrik Ullén 的论文“练习并不完美：音乐练习对音乐能力没有因果关系”中找到，心理科学25（2014）：1795–1803。
本章讨论的爵士乐表演者的神经影像学研究是Charles J. Limb和Allen R. Braun 的“自发音乐表演的神经基质：爵士乐即兴表演的 fMRI 研究”，PLoS ONE 3.2（2008）：e1679。

第六章

Chapter 6

Zohar Eitan和Renee Timmers在《贝多芬的最后一首钢琴奏鸣曲和追随鳄鱼的人：音乐背景下的跨领域听觉音高映射》中列出了多种隐喻音高映射，《认知》 114.3（2010）：405–422。
最初的探测音研究发表在Carol L. Krumhansl和Roger N. Shepard 的《全音阶环境中音调功能层次的量化》一文中，《实验心理学杂志：人类感知与表现》5.4（1979 年）：579–594。
Carol L. Krumhansl和Peter W. Jusczyk在《婴儿对音乐短语结构的感知》中报告了这一发现，即婴儿听在其典型位置有停顿的音乐的时间更长， 《心理科学》 1（1990 年）：70-73。
Laurel J. Trainor和Sandra E. Trehub在《婴儿与成人对西方音乐结构的敏感度比较》一文中记录了对西方和爪哇音阶的反应，《实验心理学杂志：人类感知与表现》 18.2（1992 年）：394-402。
关于等时和非等时节拍的感知的研究报告见Erin E. Hannon和Sandra E. Trehub 的论文“Tuning in to Musical Rhythms: Infants Learn More Readily than Adults”，美国国家科学院院刊102.35（2005）：12639–12643。
证明儿童的同步能力在社交环境中得到提高的研究表明， Sebastian Kirschner和Michael Tomasello 的“联合击鼓：社交环境促进学龄前儿童的同步”，《实验儿童心理学杂志》 102.3（2009）：299–314。
音乐吸收量表源自Gillian M. Sandstrom和Frank A. Russo的《音乐吸收：开发一种用于识别对音乐有强烈情感反应的个体的量表》，《音乐心理学》 41.2（2013）：216–228。
Gold MSI 的详细信息请参阅Daniel Müllensiefen、Bruno Gingras、Jason Musil和Lauren Stewart撰写的《非音乐家的音乐性：评估普通人群音乐成熟度的指数》PLoS ONE 9.6（2014）：e101091。

第七章

Chapter 7

Patrik N. Juslin和Daniel Västfjäll在《对音乐的情绪反应：需要考虑潜在机制》一文中列出了音乐唤起情绪的假设机制，《行为与脑科学》 31（2008）：559–621。
Petr Janata 关于音乐和自传体记忆的研究可以在Petr Janata 的《音乐诱发的自传体记忆的神经结构》中找到，《大脑皮层》 19.11（2009）：2579–2594。
Leonard B. Meyer在《音乐中的情感与意义》（芝加哥：芝加哥大学出版社，1956 年）一书中描述了惊讶与音乐情感之间的联系。
关于倒 U 型偏好曲线的研究，可以参阅Karl K. Szpunar、E. Glenn Schellenberg和Patricia Pliner 的论文《对音乐刺激的喜爱和记忆作为曝光的函数》，《实验心理学杂志：学习、记忆和认知》 30.2（2004）：370–381。
Alf Gabrielsson 关于音乐巅峰体验的研究总结在Alf Gabrielsson的《强烈的音乐体验：音乐不仅仅是音乐》一书中，由 Rod Bradbury 翻译（纽约：牛津大学出版社，2011 年）。

第八章

Chapter 8

关于美国和齐曼听众的节奏偏见的研究是Nori Jacoby和Josh H. McDermott 的“通过迭代再现跨文化揭示的音乐节奏整数比先验”，当代生物学27.3（2017）：359–370。
